<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru   05-17 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0766,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Strike Flops; OAS to Send Mediators to Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs with OAS decision, more Noriega quotes;
pickup 11th graf, `The police...'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Edits to trim thereafter.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LaserPhotos PAN5,6,9</NOTE>
<NOTE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike called to protest
the nullified election fizzled Wednesday as fear kept most people
from antagonizing the regime of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega, in his first interview since an election May 7 that was
later annuled, criticized President Bush's call for his overthrow.
``The Panamanian conscience cannot accept appeals from men who
direct this imperialism,'' he told France's Antenne 2 network.
   In Washington, the foreign ministers of the Organization of
American States approved a resolution that held Noriega responsible
for the ``grave events and abuses'' in Panama, including election
fraud, voiding the election results and beating opposition
candidates.
   The foreign ministers also said they would send mediators to
Panama in an effort to end that country's political crisis through
a ``transfer of power.''
   The strike, called by the opposition to protest the annulment of
the elections, was timed to coincide with the emergency OAS meeting.
   Some workers and customers stayed home, but many merchants said
they kept their stores open because of possible retaliation.
   ``We were closed for two months last year and we got nothing out
of it. The crisis got worse,'' said a furniture store owner in the
capital.
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara quickly
declared the strike a ``total success,'' but it was far less
effective than a similar action last year.
   ``Frankly, I'm not satisfied with the reaction of the people,''
said vice presidential candidate Guillermo Ford at an afternoon
press conference. ``I thought people would express their
dissatisfaction in a harsher way.''
   The opposition asked the OAS to recognize its election victory
and condemn Noriega for the May 10 attacks by Noriega supporters
that injured Endara and vice presidential candidates Ford and
Ricardo Arias Calderon.
   Noriega, in the French television interview, denied his forces
beat opposition figures.
   ``The police gave their protection to the candidates. I have as
proof that those who were injured were members of the police
forces,'' he said, showing photographs of what apparently were
hospitalized policemen.
   The failed strike once again raised questions about whether the
opposition's willingness to fight and to unify is as strong as
Noriega's determination to remain in power.
   ``Noriega is willing to die here, he'll have to be carried out
of the barracks feet first,'' said one opposition supporter.
   Like most people interviewed, he feared to allow his name to be
used. Noriega possesses the real power in Panama because he
commands the Panamanian Defense Forces.
   The pro-Noriega Labor Party on Wednesday afternoon proposed
negotiations between the opposition, the government parties and the
Defense Forces.
   Arias Calderon said the government does not have a civilian
sector and any negotiations must be with the military.
   The opposition called for people to demonstrate at noon in their
own neighborhoods in the capital, where one-third of the nation's
2.5 million people live. Most neighborhoods were silent, however.
   Most stores and many banks were open, although some reported far
fewer customers than usual. Shoestore owner Angel Aguilar reported
he usually sells 15 pairs by noon, but on Wednesday sold only one.
   In the port city of Colon, 50 miles north of Panama City, stores
in a free trade zone were told they would lose their licenses if
they closed, according to one shopowner.
   The government said the strike was illegal because it was called
for political, not economic reasons.
   The government also set Wednesday rather than Monday as a payday
for government workers.
   The United States has been trying to oust Noriega since two
federal grand juries in Florida indicted him on drug charges last
year, but Noriega has withstood economic sanctions and internal
protests so far.
   Noriega denies the drug charges and says they are part of a plot
by the United States to abrogate treaties that turn the Panama
Canal over to Panama.
</TEXT>
