<FIRST>u w AM-PanamaEvacuations 2ndLd-Writethru a0814 05-17 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama Evacuations, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0814,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Offers Immediate Evacuation to U.S. Military Familes in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, The first..., to UPDATE with arrival in
Charleston, SUBBING next graf to add color; also CORRECTS number of passengers.
^By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States stepped up efforts Tuesday
to safeguard relatives of U.S. military personnel in Panama,
offering immediate evacuations for any of the 14,000 military
dependents who may want to leave that troubled country.
   The Defense Department described the escalated effort as a
cautionary move in light of recent election-related violence and
sought to avoid creating the impression that there was any need for
panic.
   But Pentagon officials said that while the program is voluntary,
some relatives ultimately might be ordered home despite their
wishes.
   The first group of 276 American evacuees, including State
Department and military families, arrived 10:45 p.m. Tuesday in
Charleston, S.C., on a chartered commercial airliner. Others will
be transported on the military cargo planes that have been ferrying
extra troops to Panama.
   The first group of tired-looking passengers, several of them
carrying infants and small children, entered the terminal in
Charleston about 10 minutes later to begin clearance through
customs.
   There are about 14,000 military dependents in Panama, most of
them already on U.S. military bases. The primary objects o the
evacuation effort are the roughly 3,100 Americans who have been
living in Panamanian neighborhoods outside U.S. military bases, but
any of the dependents may leave if they wish.
   ``We are working a plan to insure the safety of the military
dependents to the greatest degree that we possibly can,'' said Dan
Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman.
   ``The situation (in Panama) has deteriorated further. We have
seen the violence on the streets of Panama. We are offering a way
for ... dependents to return to the U.S. if they so desire. We
think this is a prudent move.''
   Last week, when President Bush ordered extra troops to Panama,
defense officials ordered 1,400 off-base dependents to move inside
the military bases on a temporary basis.
   While some of those families can find vacant on-base houses,
most are going to have to come home, Howard said.
   ``The long-term goal is that they will be in permanent quarters
on the installations or returned to the continental United States
by July 1,'' Howard said.
   ``We will certainly exercise the voluntary element to the
maximum extent that it is feasible. But I hope you understand that
we simply don't have housing accommodations for all these people on
our military installations in Panama,'' he said.
   Howard refused to characterize Tuesday's effort as an
evacuation, suggesting it was a continuation of the Defense
Department's practice during the past year of reducing the number
of military families living off base.
   ``An evacuation, at least in my mind, creates images of people
grabbing up whatever they can in the household, rushing out the
front door and getting on an aircraft to get out of the country,''
he added. ``This is not an evacuation.''
   Military sources who asked not to be named said they expected at
least one and possibly two flights would be staged each day for
military families wishing to leave Panama.
   Howard declined to give details, saying they were still being
formulated.
   But he said 110 dependents of either State Department or
Pentagon employees had returned to the United States in the last
few days on a ``space available'' basis on military transports.
   The Pentagon divides the dependents of military personnel into
two categories _ command sponsored and non-command-sponsored. In
the case of the former, the serviceman has received official
permission to bring his family with him and normally serves a
longer tour of duty.
   In the latter case, the serviceman is serving a shorter,
unaccompanied tour but decides to bring his family anyway at his or
her own expense.
   The roughly 1,400 dependents who were ordered on to military
bases last week were the command-sponsored dependents, who must
honor such directives. Howard noted that as of last week, there
were another 1,685 dependents living off base who were not
sponsored and thus could only be urged to move on base.
   While those dependents cannot be issued orders, Howard said
they, too, were being encouraged to take advantage of the military
evacuation flights.
   Howard said the administration stepped up its efforts because of
the difficulty of forecasting the actions of the government of Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, who staged and then nullified a popular
presidential election a week ago when it became clear his candidate
had lost.
   Some of the opposition candidates were then attacked during
rallies, prompting President Bush to order almost 2,000 additional
troops to Panama to ensure the safety of American citizens. There
are already some 10,000 troops in Panama.
   As of Tuesday, Howard said, 1,269 soldiers or Marines had
arrived in Panama out of the 1,881 Bush ordered south.
</TEXT>
