<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     05-17 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Becomes Winningest Network</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was weeping on ``Family Ties'' as the
series closed out a seven-year run on NBC Sunday, but the network
wasn't crying this week when it broke CBS' quarter-century-old
record winning ratings streak.
   CBS won 46 weeks in a row in the 1962-63 season. As of Sunday,
NBC had been in first place for 47 straight weeks in the A.C.
Nielsen Co. ratings and added to the honor by taking the top 11
spots in the rankings, the first time a network has done that in 10
years.
   NBC prepared a list of nostalgic trivia to illustrate how long a
26-year-old record is. In 1962-63, ``The Tonight Show Starring
Johnny Carson'' premiered, the New York Mets lost 120 games in
their first season, Marilyn Monroe died, and there was no such
thing as VCRs, personal computers, the Super Bowl, remote control,
Tylenol or People magazine.
   ``This record-breaking performance _ assuming nobody has made
another clerical mistake _ really belongs to the talented, writers,
producers, directors and actors whose consistently fine work has
won the hearts and viewing habits of the American public,'' said
NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff.
   His statement referred to NBC's premature declaration a few
weeks ago that it had set a record, until CBS pointed out that the
record actually ran to 46 weeks.
   The special one-hour finale of ``Family Ties'' was last week's
No. 1 show, with a 20.8 rating and 35 share. It was broadcast
opposite the final episode of ABC's ``Moonlighting,'' which had
lost viewers so dramatically, it had dwindled to third from the
bottom in the rankings.
   NBC, which has won four seasons in a row, won last week with an
average, prime-time rating of 15.7. ABC, whose massive miniseries
``War and Remembrance'' took up much of the week with mediocre
ratings, had an 11.8. CBS had an 11.3.
   Each rating point equals 904,000 households with television. The
share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The rest of the top 10 were all NBC's: ``Golden Girls,'' ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``Top Gun,'' ``Jackee Special,'' ``Cheers,'' ``In the
Heat of the Night,'' ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' ``L.A. Law'' and
``Hunter.'' NBC's Sunday movie, ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off,''
ranked 11th. NBC said the last time a network had the top 11 shows
was 1979, when ABC had the miniseries ``Roots II.''
   The five-part conclusion of ABC's ``War and Remembrance'' built
audience each night, but after Sunday night's conclusion, which
ranked 18th, it wound up with an average rating of 14.8 and a 23.
   The first 17{ hours of the ``Winds of War'' sequel ran in
November and had an average rating of 18.6 and a 29 share.
   The 10 lowest-rated shows last week were: ``Jesse Hawkes,''
``Murder by Moonlight,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Hard Time on Planet
Earth,'' ``North and South, Book Two, Part One,'' ``Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar,'' ``Incredible Sunday,'' ``Moonlighting,'' ``A Man
Called Hawk'' and ``The Jim Henson Hour.''
   In the news ratings, ``ABC World News Tonight'' won the week
with an average rating of 10.2 and a 21 share. The ``CBS Evening
News'' had a 9.4 and 19. ``NBC Nightly News'' had a 9.0 and 19
share.
</TEXT>
