<FIRST>r a PM-HarvardLaw     05-17 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harvard Law,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harvard Law School Professor Taking Over as Dean</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert C. Clark once planned to be a
priest. Now the professor who wrote the book on corporate law is
accepting a task some regard as sacred: shepherding Harvard Law
School.
   The 44-year-old Clark takes over July 1 as the school's new
dean, succeeding 61-year-old James Vorenberg, who wanted to return
to teaching.
   A political conservative, Clark will be in various ways
responsible for and to 1,700 students, 65 faculty members, 365
employees and 25,000 alumni. He has been a professor at the school
since 1978.
   ``We have a responsiblity to give the best education and instill
some important values,'' he said in a recent interview. ``The most
important thing is the simplest things: Lawyers should be
scrupulously honest.
   ``That's not a foregone conclusion. People are tempted in many
ways throughout their careers. It's very important for all of our
graduates to feel they owe something to society, that they're
privileged and they ought to pay back.''
   Clark also wants to increase the faculty by 10, adding a couple
of new teachers a year, hold a major fund-raising drive and boost
morale.
   ``I'm not just interested in things being OK,'' he said. ``I
want people to think they're part of the greatest law school
around, so that they do their best.''
   Clark has degrees from Maryknoll Seminary, Columbia University
and Harvard Law School. His book, ``Corporate Law,'' is regarded as
a leading textbook on the subject.
   Much has been made of Clark's outspoken dislike for Critical
Legal Studies, a movement of lawyers at Harvard and elsewhere who
contend that the American legal system is not as neutral as it is
purported to be. They say it entrenches the power of a largely
white, male, upper-middle class.
   Clark has blamed conflicts over Critical Legal Studies-leaning
faculty for lowering the quality of the teaching staff. When he was
named dean in February, The Wall Street Journal cheered with an
editorial: ``Mr. Clark's appointment signals that Harvard wants the
law school's flirtation with radical politics to come to a
screeching halt.'' Today, Clark calls the issue ``old hat.''
   ``The divisions are greatly exaggerated. The relationships are
changing,'' he said.
   Faculty proponents of Critical Legal Studies said they didn't
want to comment on Clark's appointment. But international law
Professor David Kennedy, a self-described progressive, said faculty
reaction to Clark's appointment ranges ``from anxiety to
wait-and-see.''
   ``Since he was announced, he's taken, in general, a more
moderate position on issues of diversity than he did before,''
Kennedy said. ``He's been an ardent opponent of Critical Legal
Studies for more than a decade. But I don't expect him to do
anything evil to CLS. He's a very nice guy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
