<FIRST>r w PM-Governors-Bush     05-17 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Governors-Bush,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Press Concerns on Bush, President Offers Education Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Presss Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic and Republican governors pressed a
list of state concerns on President Bush and avoided any open
disagreement with the new administration following a private White
House meeting.
   Virginia's Gerald Baliles, chairman of the National Governors'
Association, said the governors called for federal action on
schools, the environment, roads, crime and welfare reform in their
session Tuesday.
   Bush responded by agreeing to call a national summit meeting on
education, Baliles said.
   ``Governors are realistic. They know these issues are not going
to be resolved in 100 days,'' Democrat Baliles said. ``But they're
also eager for results. We want to work with Washington, but we're
not waiting on Washington.''
   Iowa's Republican Gov. Terry Branstad said he urged more federal
effort to help Midwestern farmers deal with drought, and sought a
relaxation of new federal welfare regulations affecting the states.
   The rules, Branstad said, ``don't fit the spirit'' of the
welfare reform act.
   Thirteen governors, representing the National Governors'
Association, met with the president for 30 minutes in the Cabinet
Room.
   The meeting made up for one that was canceled in February
because Bush was out of the country during the governors' annual
Washington meeting. He will host a formal state dinner for the
governors Monday night.
   ``I think that he clearly understands that for his initiatives
to suceed he needs support from those who are working at the state
level,'' said Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste, a Democrat.
   Vermont Gov. Madeleine Kunin said she encouraged Bush to support
strengthening the Clean Air Act and told him that ``delay is now
not acceptable'' on the issue. She said Bush ``seems to agree with
that fundamental message.''
   Branstad said he had first suggested a summit meeting of
governors and education leaders when Bush met with them after his
election in November. He said Bush voiced his intention to hold one
in September, including governors and state education chiefs.
   A recent report by Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos which
ranked the state's education efforts concluded that, overall,
education is not improving in the nation.
   Despite that, Branstad said, ``there are exciting and innovative
things happening in many of the states to deal with the education
problems of the nation, and this summit conference is going to give
us an opportunity to share them.''
   The governors released a report by their task force on research
and technology which said states and the federal government should
promote commercial applications of technological advances that are
necessary to make the United States more competitive with other
countries.
   It recommended a revision of federal antitrust laws to promote
joint research and development projects by businesses, and renewal
of the federal tax credit for research and development.
   Governors meeting with Bush were Democrats Baliles, Celeste,
Kunin, Mike Sullivan of Wyoming and Booth Gardner of Washington,
and Republicans Branstad, Michael Castle of Delaware, John Ashcroft
of Missouri, Norman Bangerter of Utah, Carroll Campbell of South
Carolina, Edward DiPrete of Rhode Island, Thomas Kean of New Jersey
and John McKernan of Maine.
</TEXT>
