<FIRST>r w PM-Lucas     05-17 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lucas,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lucas Reports Most Income in '88 Came From GOP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Lucas, nominated by President Bush to
be the government's civil rights chief, reported receiving more
than half his salary income last year from earnings as a Republican
Party consultant.
   The nominee for assistant attorney general for civil rights
reported that $65,000 of his $125,500 in earnings came from the
Republican National Committee.
   Lucas, a black Republican whose nomination has drawn opposition
from several major civil rights groups, reported on a financial
disclosure form that he earned the money as a consultant chairing
the GOP's minority outreach committee.
   A former sheriff and chief executive of Wayne County, Mich., who
ran unsuccessfully for Michigan governor in 1986, Lucas worked to
recruit blacks into the GOP last year.
   A number of civil rights organizations, including the NAACP and
the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, a coalition of 180
groups, question Lucas' professional qualifications to head the
Justice Department's civil rights division.
   Several other civil rights leaders, including Jesse Jackson,
support Lucas' nomination.
   On the financial disclosure form released Tuesday, Lucas
reported earning $25,000 in legal fees from two companies whose
officers benefited from a 1984 contract he approved to renovate an
historic public office building in downtown Detroit when he was
Wayne County's chief executive.
   Lucas was cleared of allegations made then that he had steered
the contract to the investment partnership because one of his top
aides was part owner of the construction firm hired to perform the
$25 million renovation.
   The law firm of Philip G. Tannian, a Detroit attorney who
represented the partnership that won the contract, paid Lucas
$10,000 in legal fees last year, according to the statement filed
with the Office of Government Ethics.
   Lucas also reported earning $15,000 in legal fees from Thorn
Apple Industries, whose president, Henry Dorfman, and vice
president, Louis Glazier, were investors in the partnership that
bought the city-county office building for $3 million.
   The contract was approved by the Wayne County Board of
Supervisors on Lucas' recommendation. It became a source of
controversy when one supervisor charged that Lucas had favored the
investment partnership because one of his aides, Dennis Nystrom,
was a shareholder in the construction company that would perform
the renovation.
   Tannian said a Wayne State University law professor hired by the
county to investigate the allegations found no evidence of
wrongdoing.
   Tannian said that when the investors selected the construction
company, there was ``no ownership interest'' by Nystrom. ``We
terminated the contract with that company within 24 hours of
finding out about that interest and went with another construction
company,'' he said.
   Tannian said he hired Lucas last year to help him represent 200
small companies involved in a Superfund pollution cleanup case
because Lucas ``is an absolute expert at dealing with people and
negotiations.''
   Lucas' disclosure form also reported a $28,000 salary from the
Detroit law firm of Evans and Luptak and a $7,500 director's fee
from the Detroit-based Armada Corp.
   He also reported receiving a $25,589 pension from Wayne County,
covering his service as sheriff and county executive.
</TEXT>
