<FIRST>r w PM-CruiseShip     05-17 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruise Ship,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Say Cruise Company Refusing Cooperation In Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cruise company whose luxury liner rammed
into a Cuban merchant vessel, killing its captain and two seamen,
is refusing to cooperate with federal investigators, according to
safety officials.
   A spokesman for Carnival Cruise Ship Lines, however, said the
Miami company is responding to investigators in Liberia, where its
vessel is registered, and accused the head of the National
Transportation Safety Board of making ``misleading and totally
irresponsible'' statements about the company.
   James L. Kolstad, acting board chairman, said Tuesday that
Carnival had refused to honor subpoenas for information and
witnesses related to the Feb. 10 collision between Carnival's
733-foot Celebration, which was carrying 2,251 people, and the
351-foot Capitan San Luis, a Cuban cement carrier.
   The San Luis, which was carrying a 45-member crew, split apart
and sank.
   ``We are especially concerned,'' said Kolstad, ``with any
American-based company using U.S. ports and carrying thousands of
U.S. citizens each year, refusing to cooperate _ for whatever
reason _ with our nation's chief accident investigation agency
looking into situations that could result in a catastrophic loss of
life.''
   Kolstad said the company's refusal ``raises serious questions
about whether this company wants to provide the highest available
levels of safety protection for its passengers.''
   He said the board would continue to ``vigorously pursue'' its
investigation into the accident.
   A board investigator, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the board is concerned that the foreign registry of ships will be
used to hinder future investigations into accidents that could
involve the loss of American lives aboard a ship operated by an
American company.
   The board has no judicial power and relies on the cooperation of
parties involved in its investigations. It determines the probable
cause of accidents and makes recommendations for government and
private action to improve safety.
   Carnival spokesman Tim Gallagher declined to say whether the
company had refused to provide the safety board with any
information, saying, ``We are fully cooperating with the
appropriate authority in the investigation, which is the Bureau of
Maritime Affairs, Republic of Liberia.''
   None of the 1,580 passengers or 671 crew members aboard the
cruise ship was injured in the collision. The ship lowered
lifeboats to rescue 42 surviving Cuban crewmembers, but the San
Luis captain and two other crewmembers were lost at sea.
   Carnival Cruise, which was established in 1974, owns seven ships
and carried about 579,000 passengers, mostly Americans, last year
on cruises around the Caribbean, the Bahamas and the Mexican
Riviera.
   The cruise ship, which was returning from a seven-day Caribbean
cruise, had an 18-inch gash in its side and black scrape marks on
its bow.
   The San Luis was en route from Havana to Tenerife in the Canary
Islands for repairs, and was reported adrift in the predawn water
without lights when it was hit.
   Authorities said the San Luis was struck in the rear deckhouse,
which separated and sank almost immediately. The bow section
remained afloat for several hours before it sank.
   Cuban authorities questioned the Celebration's Italian captain,
Rafaele Gravino, who later said the Cuban vessel was drifting in a
major shipping channel.
   Cruise officials said the Celebration had three operating radar
systems, and an officer who checked the radar 20 minutes before the
crash saw nothing in the ship's path.
   Gavino told a news conference at the time that radar is checked
frequently when there is no visibility but ``when there is good
visibility, you are supposed to see the lights of the other ship.''
   Cuba's official news agency, Prensa Latina, quoted the San Luis'
helmsman as saying the ship tried to warn the Celebration to
maneuver and avoid the accident.
</TEXT>
