<FIRST>u p AM-DenverAirport 3rdLd-Writethru a0403 05-17 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Denver Airport, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0403,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Approves Referendum To Build $2.3 Billion New Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with all votes counted, reax from
airport opponents, airline. Pick up at dash.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BURKHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters endorsed a plan to replace cramped
Stapleton International Airport, the nation's fifth busiest, with a
new airport more than 20 miles from downtown.
   With all of the city's 459 precincts reporting, the referendum
had passed by 70,122 votes to 41,754 votes, a 63-to-37 percent
margin.
   ``This is a victory for the city and the people of Denver,''
said a jubilant Denver Mayor Federico Pena, who had campaigned hard
for the referendum.
   ``It gives us direction,'' said Gov. Roy Romer, another strong
backer of the measure. ``It says we have a future and we're going
to claim it.''
   Opponents of the new airport said they were not surprised by the
vote. Dick Young and Bill Chenoweth, two of the most prominent
opponents, said they would not attempt to throw further roadblocks
in the airport's path.
   ``The election was sold on the basis it (the airport) will
create instant jobs. A lot of people are hurting, and they bought
that,'' Young said.
   The new airport, which would cost an estimated $2.3 billion,
would be the first new U.S. airport since Dallas-Fort Worth
International opened in 1974.
   The referendum was non-binding, although Pena has said the city
would abide by the results.
   The referendum would authorize the city to secure federal grants
and sell bonds, then begin four years of construction later this
year on 53 square miles of city-owned prairie.
   Airlines maintained low profiles during the referendum campaign,
but on Tuesday night, Continental spokesman Ned Walker warned that
funding for the airport was far from certain.
   ``Unfortunately, the referendum may actually have set the new
airport back because it excludes the use of city taxes as a
component of the project financing plan. It did nothing to solve
the main problem, and that is _ where will Denver find the $2.3
billion it now says the new airport will cost?'' Walker said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Supporters argued that Stapleton, built in 1929, has a limited
capacity to expand and has gotten a bad reputation for delays.
   The new airport design calls for two concourses with 94 boarding
gates, which could be expanded to 120. Stapleton has 94 gates. Its
five runways would be built in a configuration differing from
Stapleton's four parallel runways.
   Federal Aviation Administration regulations currently force the
closure of Stapleton's runways when visibility is low, causing
nationwide flight delays.
   Supporters also said the project would bring a bonanza of
construction jobs and spinoff development that would make Denver a
mid-continent hub for wholesale, shipping and telecommunications
companies.
   Opponents scoffed at that and also said the project was too
risky, given Denver's sagging economy and turmoil in the airline
industry.
   ``What kind of business would locate in an area just because
they have a huge airport? I don't see the airport driving economic
growth. I think economic growth drives the airport size,'' said
former state Attorney General J.D. MacFarlane, who campaigned
against the new irport.
   Opponents also contended the proposal was driven not by need,
but by the political ambitions of the mayor and Gov. Roy Romer and
by opportunistic land developers, consultants and investment
bankers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
