<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Contras     05-17 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Contras,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Accuses Contras of Deadly Attacks</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ The Defense Ministry has accused the Contra
rebels of killing, kidnapping and torturing civilians in a series
of attacks this week.
   A cease-fire has been in place for more than a year, but both
the leftist Sandinista government and the U.S.-backed rebels, most
of whom are said to be in base camps in neighboring Honduras,
accuse each other of violations.
   The ministry said Tuesday that one civilian was killed, three
were wounded and 15 were kidnapped Sunday in a rebel attack on the
community of El Solano, 180 miles east of Managua in Zelaya Sur
province.
   Rebels also attacked a farm cooperative called Chalmeca in the
same area and kidnapped 15 peasants on Sunday, the ministry said.
   A day earlier, rebels killed one soldier and wounded three
others in a skirmish in Chontales province, it said.
   The ministry said that on May 10, rebels kidnapped, tortured and
killed two brothers in Amerisque, a town about six miles east of
Juigalpa, the capital of Chontales province.
   The next day, rebels intercepted a civilian vehicle near El
Triunfo, 185 miles west of Managua and killed a young passenger who
had served in the Sandinista army, the ministry said.
   The statement, one of the ministry's periodic summaries of
fighting, said the civil war has claimed 488 lives since Jan. 1. It
did not break down the toll into civilians, government troops and
rebels.
</TEXT>
