<SECOND>AM-Election Rdp, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0433,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Plan Loses in Pennsylvania; Pittsburgh Mayor Wins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with Seattle growth initiative
approved, Tucson bond issue winning, 78 percent of precincts in Pennsylvania,
52 percent in Oregon. Pick up at dash.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania voters overwhelmingly rejected a tax reform plan
Tuesday that would have raised their income taxes, and Denver
residents endorsed plans to build a new $2 billion airport.
   In Pittsburgh, a self-described ``Jewish grandmother'' won the
Democratic mayoral primary, making her a strong favorite to win her
first full term as mayor.
   Seattle voters approved an initiative to limit downtown growth
with a 450-foot height limit on new buildings. With 26 percent of
the precincts reporting, the vote was 12,899 to 7,964, a 62-to-38
percent margin.
   Oregon residents rejected a proposal for a new tax system, and
in Tucson, Ariz., voters appeared to be approving a $398 million
school bond package that was 10 times more expensive than one they
rejected last year.
   In Pittsburgh, incumbent Sophie Masloff, 71, beat state Rep.
Thomas J. Murphy Jr. and three other rivals for the Democratic
nomination for a four-year term.
   With 98 percent of the precincts reporting, Mrs. Masloff had 28
percent to 23 percent for Murphy and 21 percent for Allegheny
County controller Frank Luccino. Two others divided the remainder.
   Mayoral primaries were held in several other cities, including
Erie, Pa., and Jackson, Miss.
   In Erie, Joyce Savocchio, a second-term councilwoman and a high
school assistant principal, defeated five opponents to win the
city's first wide-open Democratic mayoral primary in two decades, a
race to succeed six-term Mayor Louis J. Tullio.
   In Jackson, state Rep. Kane Ditto defeated three-term incumbent
Dale Danks Jr. in the Democratic runoff. Danks had been considered
a slight favorite.
   In all three cities the Democratic primary victor would be
heavily favored to win the general election.
   Lancaster, Pa., set the stage for the election of its first
female mayor in its 247-year history. Women won both the Republican
and Democratic primaries.
   Denver's ballot issue asked voters whether 60-year-old Stapleton
International Airport should be replaced with a new facility 17
miles away. With all precincts reporting, the referendum had passed
by 70,122 votes to 41,754 votes, a 63-to-37 percent margin.
   Pennsylvania officials offered voters a swap of sorts _ lower
property taxes if they would approve a measure allowing counties to
impose an income tax. But voters, apparently fearing that the plan
would lead to higher taxes, turned it down.
   With 78 percent of the state's precincts reporting, 382,570
votes were cast supporting the plan, or 26 percent, and 1,107,570
against it, or 74 percent. Opposition was especially strong in
Philadelphia.
   With 78 percent of the state's precincts reporting, the vote was
382,570 votes for the plan, or 26 percent, to 1,107,570 against it,
or 74 percent. Opposition was especially strong in Philadelphia.
   In Oregon, voters turned down a new property tax formula that
offered help to financially ailing school districts. With 52
percent of the precincts reporting, the plan had been rejected by a
60-to-40 percent margin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The vote in Denver came after years of debate over what to do
about Stapleton, the nation's fifth-busiest airport.
   Supporters of the non-binding ballot issue, including federal
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, argued that Stapleton was
obsolete and strained beyond its capacity. Opponents, who hired
political consultant Roger Ailes to produce their advertising, said
the new airport would be a waste of money.
   The cost of a new airport has been estimated at $1.7 billion to
$2.3 billion.
   Seattle's downtown growth initiative was prompted by concerns
over the ``Manhattanization'' of Seattle, whose skyline includes a
76-story building and 10 others that are taller than 450 feet.
   Opponents in the business community argued that the measure
would rein in economic development.
   Pennsylvania's ballot issue was intended to give local
authorities greater flexibility in setting tax rates, but it
stirred strong opposition from those who opposed an increase in the
income tax.
   Both mayor's races in Pennsylvania sought successors to men who
contracted the rare heart disease amyloidosis.
   Mrs. Masloff, who likes to use the ``Jewish grandmother'' tag as
part of her folksy image, was City Council president last year when
she was appointed to fill the vacancy left by the death of Mayor
Richard S. Caliguiri.
   Lucchino, 50, a third-term controller and former city
councilman, tried to counter Mrs. Masloff's appeal with the image
of a no-nonsense administrator.
   In Erie, Tullio announced he was retiring after he became ill
with amyloidosis, which causes a fatal protein buildup in the heart.
</TEXT>
