<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GeneticSuit     05-17 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Genetic Suit,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>NIH Gene Research to be Opened to Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Institutes of Health is settling
a suit by adopting a requirement that opens deliberations and votes
on human gene research to the public.
   The suit filed Jan. 30 by a private foundation challenged the
first planned introduction of a foreign gene into human beings, an
experiment which will be conducted on 10 patients who are
terminally ill with melanoma, a skin cancer.
   The experiment may take place later this week, Jeremy Rifkin,
president of the Foundation on Economic Trends, said Tuesday after
the court settlement was reached.
   The foundation and Rifkin filed the suit against Health and
Human Services Secretary Louis Sullivan and NIH director James
Wyngaarden.
   Rifkin said the settlement clears the way for the experiment.
However, the experiment was not held up on account of the lawsuit,
asserted Margot de Ferranti, a Justice Department lawyer who
defended the government in the case. She said NIH has been in the
process of finding terminally ill cancer patients to participate in
the experiment.
   U.S. District Judge John G. Penn signed the agreement dismissing
the suit, which alleged the NIH Recombinant DNA Advisory Committee
approved the experiment on melanoma patients without conducting
proper public hearings.
   Under the agreement, the committee must hold all future
deliberations and votes in public sessions.
   Sullivan approved amendments to the DNA committee's charter
containing the requirement.
   A knowledgeable NIH official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the committee's deliberations and voting ordinarily
are open to the public. He said the panel had earlier approved the
experiment in open session, but then conducted a mailed ballot as a
reconfirmation of that decision.
   ``The changes in the charter spell out an orderly process of
review,'' NIH spokeswoman Anne Thomas said in a statement. ``Some
of the changes were suggested by Dr. Wyngaarden with the
concurrence'' of the committee. ``We are pleased that this has been
resolved,'' she added.
   ``This will be the first major medical technology in which the
public will be allowed to fully participate in the review
process,'' said Rifkin. ``We hope it will set a precedent. Other
countries look to the United States for the lead.''
   Rifkin said the settlement allows ``active participation.
Organizations like mine can propose amendments (to proposed
experiments) in advance that then have to be put on the agenda,
that have to be voted on by that committee.''
   However, the public has long had an opportunity to participate
and make its views known to the committee, including the right to
propose amendments to the guidelines, said the NIH official.
   Rifkin and his group said a review of the original proposal by a
subcommittee wasn't conducted with public notice and public
participation and that final approval by the full committee was by
a mailed ballot, instead of in public. Under the agreement, the
subcommittee sessions may still be conducted privately.
   The DNA committee approved research in January to introduce into
melanoma patients a type of immune cell, called tumor infiltrating
lymphocytes, that has been genetically altered.
   In earlier work, three NIH researchers showed that TIL cells can
be used to battle cancer by taking them from a patient's tumor,
growing them in large numbers, and reinserting them into a patient.
The technique was at least partially successful in 12 of 20
patients.
   The scientists now want to trace the white blood cells after
they are returned to the patient to understand why TIL therapy
works for some, but not others. To do this, they want to mark the
cells with a bacterial gene that produces a resistance to neomycin,
an antibiotic. In this way, cells from the patient's tumors or
blood stream could be identified and movement of the cells into the
tumors could be monitored.
   To get the gene of the bacteria into the white blood cells, the
scientists propose to use a mouse leukemia retrovirus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
