<DOCNO> AP890517-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ChildPorn     05-17 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Porn,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Strikes Down Record-Keeping Rules in Anti-Porn Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stringent record-keeping requirements in a
child anti-pornography statute are unconstitutional, according to a
federal judge who said the restrictions infringe on First Amendment
rights.
   U.S. District Judge George Revercomb on Tuesday handed down the
decision on the 1988 Child Protection and Obscenity Enforcement
Act, which requires publishers and distributors to document the
ages of nude models in photographs.
   Under the law, models and performers must be contacted to
determine if they were at least 18 years old at the time the
photograph or film was made. The requirements cover the reissue of
images first made after Feb. 6, 1978, the date of the chief federal
law criminalizing child pornography, said the judge.
   The requirements ``have not been narrowly tailored to fit the
legitimate governmental interest of stopping child pornography,''
Revercomb said in a 43-page decision. They ``burden too heavily and
infringe too deeply'' on the right to produce material protected by
the First Amendment, he wrote.
   ``The result of the requirement ... will undoubtedly be the
effective prohibition of the distribution of much First Amendment
protected material,'' the opinion said.
   The ruling came in a lawsuit filed by the American Library
Association.
   Revercomb also found unconstitutional companion requirements
providing for a presumption of criminality by those who fail to
abide by record-keeping requirements.
   Proof that a person being prosecuted for a child porn offense
failed to keep the proper records ``shall raise a rebuttable
presumption that such performer was a minor,'' according to the law.
   Revercomb said the criminal presumptions raise the ``serious
potential'' for convicting people who have not engaged in child
pornography.
   The judge also found unconstitutional parts of a civil provision
in the child pornography law and portions of a criminal forfeiture
provision allowing seizure of materials before conviction.
   The provisions allow forfeiture of property used to promote the
commission of an offense. Revercomb blocked the government from
enforcing the provisions unless there has been a prior adversarial
proceeding.
   The court also enjoined the government from enforcing the
post-conviction forfeiture provisions of the law unless there has
been a ``pattern'' of activity.
   ``The laws at issue here appear to authorize forfeiture of vast
amounts of assets _ everything from First Amendment protected
material to bank accounts _ for a single violation,'' said the
judge.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown said the department was
``still reviewing the opinion and studying its impact'' and had no
further immediate comment.
   Bruce Ennis, an attorney representing the American Library
Association, said last month the law puts near-impossible
record-keeping burdens on legitimate businesses. It would impose a
``corporate death penalty'' on distributors because all assets
could be seized if they violate the law with even one publication,
Ennis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ForestHarvests     05-17 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forest Harvests,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bryant Wants To Stop Clearcutting In National Forests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. John Bryant is seeking to severely
restrict the practice of clear-cutting in national forests, calling
the timber harvesting method irresponsible and wasteful.
   But the U.S. Forest Service and industry representatives say
clear-cutting timber is a valuable forest management tool and is
vital to maintaining habitat for certain species of wildlife.
   ``Clear-cutting ignores the need for natural species diversity
as a requirement for a healthy forest environment,'' Bryant,
D-Texas, said Tuesday.
   He was referring to the practice of cutting down all the trees
in an area, rather than selectively picking trees to fell.
   ``A live, healthy forest is replaced after a clear-cut with a
single species of tree plantation, which forest experts believe
loses its immunity to natural infestations of tree-killing pests,
such as the Southern pine beetle,'' Bryant said.
   Bryant introduced legislation to prohibit clear-cutting in any
national forest in which one-tenth of the acreage of available
commercial timberland has already been harvested by clear-cutting.
Many national forests would be affected, he said.
   The Forest Service would be required to replace clear-cutting
with ``selection-management'' harvesting techniques, in which only
certain trees are removed from a stand and a diversity of plants
remain.
   Although backed by some environmentalists, Bryant acknowledged a
tough fight ahead and intense pressure from timber industry
lobbyists to ``prevent a serious hearing'' on the bill.
   Last year, 283,061 acres of national forest were clear-cut,
Bryant said. National forests cover 191 million acres, of which 61
million are classified as suitable for timber production.
   Dave Hessel, director of timber management at the Forest
Service, said clear-cutting is valuable in ``maintaining not only
species diversity but also in its relationship to maintaining
wildlife habitat needs.''
   Hessel said clear-cutting is needed for stands of trees that
require sunlight to develop, like the lodgepole pine. Lodgepole
pine forests provide the habitat for big game species like elk in
the Rocky Mountains.
   The roughly 300,000 acres that are clearcut represent about half
the acreage harvested in national forests, but produce 75 percent
of the volume, Hessel said.
   Mark Rey, vice president for public forestry at National Forest
Products Association, said clear-cutting is not inconsistent with
high wildlife values, species diversity, and multiple uses for
forests.
   Rey also contends the bill would ``indisputably reduce the
amount of timber production potential the lands can have'' because
some species must have sunlight to regenerate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
