<FIRST>r w PM-OAS-Glance     05-17 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OAS-Glance,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-OAS-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are facts and figures about
the Organization of American States, where hemispheric foreign
ministers meet today to discuss the Panama crisis:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PURPOSE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _The OAS, the world's oldest regional body, with origins dating
back to 1899, is designed to preserve peace and promote cooperation
among the nations of the Americas.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHARTER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _OAS guidelines are spelled out in a charter, amended in 1985,
and by the Rio Treaty, a pact designed to bring about peaceful
resolution of disputes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MEMBERSHIP</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _There are 31 active members of the OAS. The Cuban government
was expelled in the early 1960s on grounds that Marxism-Leninism
was incompatible with OAS principles.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BUDGET</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _The OAS budget is $60 million a year, of which the United
States provides about $40 million. But the United States is about
$50 million in arrears. A financial crisis at the OAS recently led
to the layoffs of 300 of its estimated 1,000 employees.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PROCEDURES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _The OAS holds a foreign ministers meeting annually. During
crises, such as the current situation in Panama, emergency foreign
ministers meetings can be convened. The last such meeting was in
1982 at the time of the conflict between Britain and Argentina over
the Falklands@Malvinas islands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
