<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>New NHTSA Safety Probes Involve More Than 4 Million Cars, Trucks</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brake problems accounted for about half the
new safety defect investigations opened in April by the National
Highway Traffic Safety Admistration.
   Altogether, the agency said Tuesday it had started 10 new
preliminary evaluations, the lowest level of probe, into alleged
problems involving more than 4 million cars and trucks made by
major automakers both in the United States and abroad.
   Alleged brake defects were the complaint that brought 2 million
of the vehicles under NHTSA's scrutiny.
   NHTSA said it was investigating 26 reports that the brakes in
1.5 million General Motors Corp. light trucks tend to pull to the
left or right. The models involved are the 1984-1986 C123, K1 and
K2; the 1987-1988 R123, V1 and V2; and the 1984-1988 G123 pickup
trucks.
   The 75,000 1988 Pontiac Lemans, according to six complaints, is
prone to weak braking. The complaints included one accident with
four injuries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Summer Gas Prices Seen 10 Percent Higher Than Last Year</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices are likely to rise four cents
more a gallon by summer, and the supply outlook is unclear, a
government agency says.
   The Energy Information Administration said Tuesday that prices
for all grades are likely to average $1.09 a gallon, up from $1.05
now. The average price last summer was 99 cents a gallon, the
report said.
   Prices rose sharply immediately after the March 24 Exxon oil
tanker spill in Alaska, which caused a brief drop in shipments of
North Slope crude oil, but then stabilized.
   The additional price increases by summer will reflect a recent
rise in crude oil prices paid by refiners and an estimated 1 cent
per gallon increase in state gasoline taxes, the report said.
   Also putting upward pressure on prices should be the usual
summertime jump in gasoline demand, reaching a level 1.9 percent
higher than last summer, the agency said.
   The report said that while gasoline supplies currently are
adequate, a squeeze could develop this summer if increased import
requirements cannot be met. It said one-half of the anticipated
increase in gasoline demand would have to be met by imports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Pacifier, Christmas Decoration Recalled</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christmas stocking decoration and a pacifier
holder that could pose choking hazards for children are being
recalled, the Consumer Product Safety Commission announced.
   Neither has been involved in any injuries, officials said
Tuesday.
   The recall covers about 3,600 ``Mother's Helper'' pacifier
holders sold nationwide from October 1987 to August 1988, the
agency said.
   The recalled pacifier holders have a metal clip for fastening
the device to an infant's clothing. The metal clip could pose a
choking hazard if it separated from the rest of the holder, the
commission said.
   Embossed on the back are the words ``Mother's Helper 1986 Steven
Barrie &amp; Company.'' Consumers should return the holders to the
store where purchased for a refund or send them to Steven Barrie &amp;
Co., 1055A Louis Drive, Warminster, Pa., 18970.
   The second recall involves a Christmas stocking decorated with a
teddy bear and two small bells. The bells could come loose and
choke a child, the commission said.
   About 4,400 of the stockings, made of red and white furry
material and topped with the teddy bear head, were sold last
Christmas season, officials said.
   These can be returned to the retailer for a refund, the
commission said. Consumers may contact the Jerry Elsner Company,
Bronx, N.Y., at 1-800-223-4119 for additional information.
</TEXT>
