<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Evacuations     05-17 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Evacuations,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dependents Evacuated from Panama, Many Reluctantly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-OAS-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: `Ju' cq in 9th graf. ^By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOWARD AIR FORCE BASE, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carrying suitcases, baby
bottles and stuffed animals, the families of U.S. military
personnel in Panama boarded a chartered Air Force jet that took
them away from a home and friends.
   ``It's just like another part of your family leaving,'' said
Regina Brown, who came to the air base Tuesday to see off her
friends Amos and Twyla Walker.
   ``My dad was in the service,'' said Ms. Brown. ``I'm used to it,
but then again I'm not.''
   She said one of the Walkers' three children was her son's best
friend.
   The Walkers were among 238 military personnel and dependents who
left Panama on Tuesday aboard a chartered L-1011 jumbo jet for
Charleston, S.C.
   President Bush last week ordered all off-base U.S. dependents to
move on base for security reasons because of the country's
political crisis.
   Since bases in Panama lack room for the nearly 1,000 off-base
dependents, many are being forced to leave.
   Gen. Fred Woerner, commander of the U.S. Southern Command, came
to say goodbye but refused to comment to reporters.
   Airman 1st Class Dana Horn was one of those who couldn't obtain
base housing and was leaving with her mother, Ju Morrison, and
two-month-old daughter, Alexia.
   She said that her security detachment had become ``like a big
family.''
   Even though she lived in Panama City, Ms. Horn said, she'd never
had trouble with demonstrations, harassment or civil unrest.
   ``I wouldn't leave til they ran me out,'' said Ms. Morrison, who
said the family was from western Kentucky.
   Airman Horn said she and her husband were separated and she
would be going from Charleston, S.C., to Homestead AFB in Florida
for reassignment.
   The Bookwalters were less reluctant to leave.
   ``Panama is very nice, but it's not our family,'' said Joann
Bookwalter, holding a bottle for her young son Randy.
   She and her husband, Airman 1st Class Wayne Bookwalter, were
ordered out suddenly.
   ``It's a big inconvenience, but it's safer to leave,'' she said.
</TEXT>
