<DOCNO> AP890517-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p PM-ElectionRdp Bjt   05-17 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Election Rdp, Bjt,0730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver OKs New Airport, Seattle Puts Cap on Downtown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Denver residents voted to boost their city's growth with a new
$2 billion airport, while Seattle residents voted to limit growth
with a lid on the height of new downtown buildings.
   Also Tuesday, voters rejected tax overhauls in Pennsylvania and
Oregon, and Pittsburgh Mayor Sophie Masloff won the Democratic
primary and practically guaranteed herself victory in November.
   In Tucson, Ariz., voters reversed themselves and approved a
school bond package totaling $398 million _ 10 times the amount of
a similar measure that was rejected last year.
   The elections in Denver and Seattle reflected different problems
and priorities in two fast-growing Western cities.
   In Denver, voters sided with Mayor Federico Pena and Gov. Roy
Romer, agreeing that it was time to replace 60-year-old Stapleton
International Airport, the nation's fifth largest, with a new
airport 20 miles from downtown.
   Pena and Romer said Stapleton was overcrowded and obsolete. They
said a new airport was needed to avoid future flight delays and
help Denver remain the economic hub of the Rockies.
   Opponents said the plan was unnecessary and, at $2.3 billion,
too costly.
   The referendum passed by 63-to-37 percent _ 70,122 votes for the
new airport, 41,754 votes against. Denver Election Commission
president Bob Shannon said the 41 percent turnout was
``phenomenal'' for a special election.
   The victory ``gives us direction,'' said Romer. ``It says we
have a future and we're going to claim it.''
   Seattle residents also voted on the future, and agreed that it
doesn't lie 80 stories above Puget Sound. The initiative they
approved restricts the density and height of downtown buildings for
the next 10 years while a long-range development plan is adopted.
   The initiative's most visible impact will be to limit the height
of new buildings to 450 feet, about 38 stories. Seattle now has the
tallest downtown on the West Coast, crowned by the 76-story
Columbia Center.
   With 98 percent of precincts reporting, the vote was 42,007 in
favor of the measure and 25,958 against, or 62-to-38 percent. A
simple majority was needed.
   While most of Tuesday's voting was on growth and money issues,
several cities held mayoral primaries.
   In Pittsburgh, the 71-year-old Mrs. Masloff, who is known for
her folksy touch and describes herself as a ``Jewish grandmother,''
beat four rivals for the Democratic nomination.
   ``Thank you to all of Pittsburgh,'' Mrs. Masloff said. ``I
accept this victory with deep appreciation and humility.''
   Mrs. Masloff was City Council president last year when she was
appointed to fill the vacancy left by the death of Mayor Richard S.
Caliguiri.
   With all but three of the city's 402 precincts reporting, she
had 30,259 votes, or 28 percent, to 25,089 votes, or 23 percent,
for state Rep. Thomas J. Murphy Jr., and 22,727, or 21 percent, for
Allegheny County controller Frank Lucchino. Two other candidates
received the rest.
   In Jackson, Miss., state Rep. Kane Ditto defeated three-term
incumbent Dale Danks Jr. in the Democratic mayoral runoff. Danks
had been considered a slight favorite.
   And in Erie, Pa., City Councilwoman Joyce Savocchio defeated
five opponents to win the Democratic primary in a bid to succeed
six-term Mayor Louis J. Tullio.
   Democrats are heavily favored to win general elections in all
three cities.
   The elections delivered setbacks to Govs. Robert P. Casey of
Pennsylvania and Neil Goldschmidt of Oregon. Both put their
reputations behind proposals to overhaul their states' taxes, and
both lost badly.
   Pennsylvania voters turned back a referendum that would have
allowed counties to impose income taxes in exchange for a promised
reduction in property taxes.
   With 97 percent of the state's precincts reporting, 496,276
people voted for the plan, or 25 percent, and 1,484,973, or 75
percent, voted no.
   Also defeated was a Philadelphia proposal to legalize charity
raffles and other small games of chance.
   Oregonians trounced a ballot measure that would have updated tax
bases for about a third of the state's school districts,
effectively allowing them to raise property taxes without asking
voter approval.
   With votes from 1,682 of the state's 2,261 precincts tallied,
the results were 191,072 votes against the proposal, or 59 percent,
to 130,816 votes, or 41 percent, in favor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
