<FIRST>r a PM-TrainDerail     05-17 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Derail,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Runaway Train In California May Have Been Overloaded, Investigators
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A runaway freight train that
jumped a track and killed four people may have been too heavily
loaded for its locomotives' braking capacity, investigators say.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators focused on
the role the 69-car train's weight may have played in the accident
that damaged or destroyed 11 houses.
   They said a Southern Pacific worker believes the train weighed
nearly 3,000 tons more than the weight recorded for the crew on
documents.
   The train ran off the tracks early Friday at 90 mph at the
bottom of a mountain grade on a curve trains are supposed to take
at 30 mph. Two boys in one of the homes and two crewmen on the
train were killed.
   Shipping documents indicated the train weighed 6,150 tons, a
measurement determined by three railroad clerks, Jim Kolstad, the
safety board's acting chairman, told reporters late Tuesday.
   Southern Pacific's assistant chief dispatcher, Albert Hale,
estimated the train weighed at least 8,950 tons, according to
investigators. Investigators said only three of the train's six
locomotives had adequate braking power.
   The three locomotives would have controlled a 6,150-ton train,
according to a computer simulation run by the NTSB. But the
simulation also showed six locomotives were needed to control a
train of the weight estimated by Hale.
   NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz said the investigation so far
has not determined conclusively what caused the accident. It will
be six to nine months before the final NTSB report is completed.
   Meanwhile, the line reopened Tuesday afternoon with two trains
rolling down Cajon Pass and through the area, said railroad
spokesman Jerry Pera.
   City Attorney James Penman, who had city council authorization
to seek an injunction to keep the track closed, had insisted that
Southern Pacific purchase the properties damaged in the accident.
   Southern Pacific and the city reached agreement hours before
Tuesday's threatened court action designed to shut down the track.
   Penman said the agreement opening the track avoided what could
have been a long court fight. ``We know it is difficult to get an
injunction against a national transportation arm,'' he said.
   Southern Pacific had agreed to buy seven destroyed house for
$70,000 each. On Tuesday afternoon, they agreed to buy four other
houses and accepted the city's demand for an undeveloped land
buffer in case of another derailment.
   ``The area will become a greenbelt area,'' said Mayor Evelyn
Wilcox. ``The rail line is there, and we've done our best to ensure
the health and safety of the residents.''
   The company also agreed to pay the costs of relocating residents
and housing them for 90 days, pick up the city's cleanup costs and
defend San Bernardino in any lawsuit resulting from the wreck.
   Homeowner Fred Revely, whose property was bought by the
railroad, said he was pleased with the agreement. ``I'm very happy
with everything that Southern Pacific has done,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
