<SECOND>PM-BRF--Roger Rabbit,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Wins $150,000 Copyright Infringement Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Walt Disney Co. won a $150,000 award from a
T-shirt printer for infringement on its copyright by making and
selling shirts with characters from the movie ``Who Framed Roger
Rabbit.''
   In his ruling Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Terence T. Evans also
prohibited Concert Shirt Inc. of Milwaukee and its owner, Jack
Kupper, from manufacturing or marketing merchandise with characters
or objects from the movie.
   Kupper was found to have infringed on the copyright by using
pictures of Roger Rabbit, Jessica and Benny the Cab.
   Disney and Amblin Entertainment, a California corporation,
brought the suit against Kupper.
   Kupper's attorney, Charles N. Quinn, said his client no longer
is in the T-shirt business.
