<FIRST>r a PM-CasinoClosing     05-17 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casino Closing,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantic City Casino Ordered Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Elsinore's Atlantis Casino
Hotel expressed frustration and fear over news that the debt-ridden
gaming hall has become the first to be ordered closed by New Jersey
regulators.
   Philip T. Forsyth, a floor supervisor, said he has found only
part-time work as a dealer or cashier.
   ``They hire part-time to save on benefits,'' he said. ``I have a
$1,140 mortgage _ how can I work part-time?''
   Other employees have been luckier than Forsyth. Myrtile Mays, a
dealer, has a job lined up with another casino.
   ``I went out looking for another job a couple of weeks ago _
just in case,'' Mays said.
   Mays said the mood among Atlantis employees on Tuesday was
``hyper, really stressful. A lot of people don't know how they're
going to pay their bills, especially their mortgages.''
   Forsyth said many employees are embittered toward company
President Jeanne Hood, blaming her for mismanagement.
   ``She was brazen enough to walk through the casino a few days
ago,'' he said. ``She was smiling and waving even though people
were calling her names.''
   Forsyth also said many employees are angered with developer
Donald Trump's $63 million purchase agreement to buy the
three-tiered Atlantis and convert it into a hotel without a casino.
   The state Casino Control Commission on Tuesday ordered the
casino to close next Monday, citing its estimated $144 million
debt. The hotel, which runs at about 80 percent occupancy on
weekends, was allowed to remain open.
   Atlantic City, which approved gambling in 1976, has 11 other
casinos.
   The Atlantis has suffered heavy losses after opening in 1981 as
the Playboy Hotel and Casino. It emerged last fall from federal
bankruptcy reorganization.
   Some employees cried when they heard news of the closing.
   ``We're all very down. The Atlantis people were a very together
people, just trying to keep the place together,'' said Michael
Bucci, a casino host.
   Some maintained optimism.
   ``A lot of these people have gone through the rough years when
the casino was still Playboy, the bankruptcy and two strikes,''
said Roy Silbert, president of Local 54 of the Hotel Employees and
Restaurant Employees International Union.
   ``They're cautiously optimistic. You never can predict whether
or not this news will force something to happen to the business.''
   In recent weeks, Atlantis' 2,100 employees have anxiously
watched as the state denied Elsinore officials a license and
appointed a conservator to control the gaming hall.
   Even if the 1,100 casino floor employees find work at other
gaming halls, many will lose up to eight years of seniority and
accompanying benefits. Others, particularly those in supervisory
positions, will be unable to find similar positions.
   Silbert said Tuesday that he planned to appeal the commission's
decision in U.S. District Court in Camden.
   ``I'm not trying to stop the closing,'' he said. ``We just want
to protect the federal mandate for adequate notice.''
   Silbert said a recently enacted federal plant closing act
requires an employer to notify workers 60 days in advance of any
closing.
   Some Atlantis customers reacted to the news with a shrug.
   ``We'll just go to another casino,'' said one customer, Sam
Giterman of Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
