<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-17 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index edged up
today, and the dollar gained against the yen for a fifth day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
33,992.45, up 66.00 points, or 0.19 percent. The index had gained
210.16 points Tuesday.
   The dollar finished at 137.70 yen, up 0.70 yen from Tuesday's
137.00-yen close. After opening at 137.12 yen, it rose despite the
central bank's dollar-selling intervention, and ranged between
136.97 yen and 137.75 yen.
   The dollar has gained 3.26 yen in five straight trading days.
   The dollar-yen rate moved little in early trading, as traders
waited for the announcement later today of U.S. trade figures for
March. But then traders began buying dollars following developments
in Japan's influence-peddling scandal, traders said.
   Tokyo prosecutors summoned Takao Fujinami, a top aide to former
Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, and Katsuya Ikeda, a lawmaker
from the Clean Government Party, for questioning in connection with
alleged attempts by Recruit Co. to buy influence.
   For the third consecutive day, the Bank of Japan intervened in
an attempt to support the yen, said Masafumi Koyama of the Bank of
Tokyo.
   The central bank reportedly sold $100 million to $200 million.
The bank does not comment on its activities in the exchange market.
   Other traders said the central bank intervention, which failed
to push the dollar lower, was only to discourage the current
dollar-buying mood.
   Kyodo News Service quoted unidentified Bank of Japan officials
as saying the dollar's recent strength comes despite a lack of any
changes in economic fundamentals, and that the dollar-buying was
``overdone'' and ``speculative.''
   Japan ``will continue to take determined measures in
cooperation'' with other major monetary nations, Kyodo quoted the
officials as saying.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei figure moved very little
today, ``mainly due to political uncertainties,'' said Kenji
Ishizuka, a dealer with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
   He said the new developments in the Recruit scandal discouraged
participants to some extent.
   ``Japanese investors were also concerned about the possible
interest rate hike by the West German federal bank, meeting
tomorrow,'' said Ishizuka.
   ``Market players bought only cheaper issues because they were
reluctant to make major moves. Still, it shows that investors have
so much money, since prices rose even when they didn't have
specific incentives to buy,'' he said.
   Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 800
million shares, up from Tuesday's 600 million. Among gainers were
ship building and chemical issues.
</TEXT>
