<FIRST>r a PM-MassSlayingsTrial     05-17 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mass Slayings Trial,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused in Slaying of Six Goes on Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing his
ex-girlfriend and five other people, including two children, spent
the first day of his trial in a holding cell after he was ejected
from the courtroom.
   David ``Moochie'' Welch was ordered out of the courtroom Tuesday
after he repeatedly interrupted the trial. He watched the
proceedings on a closed-circuit television from the cell.
   Welch, 31, is charged with six counts of first-degree murder and
two counts of attempted murder in the slayings at the home of his
17-year-old ex-girlfriend, Dellane Mabre. Also slain were her
3-year-old daughter, her two brothers, and a family friend and her
2-year-old daughter.
   Welch's and Mabrey's son, Dexter, then 3 months old, and a
21-year-old man were wounded.
   Each victim was shot in the head with a 9mm Uzi submachine or a
.357-caliber Magnum after Welch allegedly kicked in the door of the
home in the early morning hours of Dec. 8, 1986.
   Welch and Rita Lewis, 32, were arrested after a five-hour
standoff with police. Lewis pleaded guilty to six counts of murder
and was sentenced to 51 years to life in prison. Prosecutors
dropped their request for the death penalty in exchange for her
plea.
   Although not expected to testify in Welch's trial, Lewis
testified in her own case that Welch was angry about a bitter
breakup with Mabrey and had been smoking rock cocaine the day
before the slayings.
   At the time of the killings, Welch was awaiting trial for
allegedly assaulting Mabrey and her mother. He also was facing
heroin and cocaine possession charges.
   Since his arrest, Welch has filed numerous legal motions and
requests. He also has fired three attorneys, had judges removed
from his case and sought to have Lewis' public defender disbarred.
Welch also has asked for a personal barber, a private secretary and
private transportation to and from court. Those requests were
denied.
   Court records show Welch has been convicted of assaulting a
police officer, receiving stolen property and assault with a deadly
weapon. He was released from prison in January 1986.
   On Tuesday, Welch interrupted the proceedings, objecting that he
was not able to view a videotape of the crime scene being shown to
jurors.
   ``If you continue to talk, you'll be removed. Don't push me
beyond the limit,'' Alameda County Superior Court Judge Stanley
Golde told Welch, pointing out that the defendant had seen the tape
before.
   He was taken to a holding cell after his fourth interruption.
</TEXT>
