<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-VietnamWar     05-17 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Vietnam War,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: 4,000 Chinese Died in Vietnam War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 4,000 Chinese servicemen died in the
Vietnam War after China sent about 320,000 of its forces to fight
the United States, according to a news report.
   The report from the semi-official Hong Kong China News Agency
attributed its information to The History of the People's Republic
of China, a new reference book published by China's official State
Archives Publishing House.
   The report, seen in Hong Kong today, was believed to be the
first Chinese disclosure of a more precise figure on casualties,
which the Chinese have said in the past was in the ``thousands.''
   The United States claimed repeatedly during the Vietnam War that
there was evidence Chinese forces were involved in the war. China
denied the allegations.
   China has acknowledged that its assistance to Vietnam during the
war, which ended in a Communist victory in 1975, included sending
about 320,000 personnel and $20 billion in aid.
   But in 1979, when relations between China and Vietnam
deteriorated, China's official People's Daily newspaper and Xinhua
News Agency published a booklet on China's assistance to Vietnam.
   ``From January 1965 to March 1968, China dispatched to Vietnam
support forces of over 320,000 men to undertake air defense,
engineering, railway and logistics work,'' the booklet said.
   ``Together with the Vietnamese people, the Chinese support
forces defended the territorial air space of North Vietnam with
their lives.''
   It added: ``The remains of thousands of Chinese martyrs lie on
Vietnamese soil to this day.''
   China and the Soviet Union were Vietnam's principal supporters
during the war. But relations between China and Vietnam later
deteriorated over Vietnam's persecution of ethnic Chinese,
territorial conflicts, Vietnam's close alliance with the Soviet
Union and Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia in 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
