<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CrimeSign     05-17 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Crime Sign,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Eighth Robbery, Victim Tells Thieves Nothing Left</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose home has been hit by
repeated break-ins has put up a sign telling would-be robbers not
to bother.
   ``Notice to thieves: 8 robberies _ nothing left,'' says the sign
on Helen Ferris' front door.
   ``If they can read, they'll know they will be wasting their
time,'' said Ferris, who has lived at the three-room house for 15
years and posted the sign Monday. ``There's nothing in there they
can pawn.''
   Ferris said the break-ins have taken place since the early 1980s.
   ``That doesn't include the times things were stolen from outside
the house,'' she said. ``I put a Christmas wreath on my front door
five years ago and one hour later it was gone.''
   Ferris is among a growing number of burglary victims in Fort
Lauderdale. In 1988, 4,251 burglaries were reported, up from 3,958
in 1987.
   ``It's gone up primarily because of the crack cocaine problem,''
said police spokesman Ott Cefkin. ``Nobody is frustrated more than
we are. We just don't have enough police around.''
</TEXT>
