<FIRST>r p PM-DenverAirport     05-17 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Denver Airport,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Voters Say `Yes' to New Airport; Mayor Begins Hunt for Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Election Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BURKHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters approved a plan to replace the nation's
fifth largest airport, prompting a jubilant Mayor Federico Pena to
predict that construction would begin on a new $2 billion airport
later this year.
   ``This is a victory for every young person who wants to stay in
Colorado,'' Pena said Tuesday night after the airport referendum
passed. ``Denver just took off!''
   Pena and Colorado Gov. Roy Romer had campaigned hard to build a
replacement for 60-year-old Stapleton International Airport, which
detractors say is too old and small to serve a growing regional hub.
   Although the vote was non-binding, city officials had agreed to
abide by its results. Two leading opponents of the new airport
announced after the election that they would honor the vote and not
try to stop construction.
   The referendum passed 62.7 percent to 37.3 percent, with 70,122
votes to build the airport and 41,754 against. Election Commission
President Bob Shannon called the 41 percent turnout ``phenomenal''
for a special election.
   It if is built, the new facility would be the first major
airport built in the United States since Dallas-Fort Worth
International opened in 1974.
   But first, Denver will have to come up with the money.
   The city estimates that it needs $500 million in federal funds
and $1.5 billion in revenue bonds. Pena said he would go to
Washington, D.C., to deliver the city's letter of intent for
federal funds to the Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``This is a national economic development decision that will be
helpful to the entire country,'' Pena said. ``We have to have a
national transportation system that works. That is the main
argument I am making to Congress.''
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner had predicted that
Denver voters would approve the new airport, calling the plan ``the
most creative aviation development project in many years.''
   Airlines maintained a low profile during the airport campaign,
but Continental Airlines spokesman Ned Walker said Tuesday night
that airport supporters had sidestepped the financing issue.
   ``Unfortunately, the referendum may actually have set the new
airport back because it excludes the use of city taxes as a
component of the project financing plan,'' Walker said. ``It did
nothing to solve the main problem, and that is _ where will Denver
find the $2.3 billion it now says the new airport will cost?''
   Denver International Airport, scheduled for operation in 1994,
would be built about 17 miles northeast of downtown Denver on 53
square miles of land annexed last year from Adams County.
   Plans for the new airport call for 94 boarding gates on two
concourses, with expansion later to 120 gates. Stapleton has 94.
   A final environmental impact statement of the proposed airport
site is expected in July or August, and then construction can
begin. Pena said he expected groundbreaking to take place later
this year.
   The Let's Vote Yes campaign had argued that Stapleton needed to
be replaced to head off lengthy flight delays in the future. They
also said a new airport would stimulate the city's economy.
   Opponents, including the Let's Vote No and Save Our Airport
campaigns, said a decrease in air traffic at Stapleton during the
last two years was an indication that a new airport was unneeded.
They also said the new airport would be too costly and wouldn't
improve the economy.
</TEXT>
