<FIRST>r a PM-CopKiller-Sentencing     05-17 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cop Killer-Sentencing,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Applaud Maximum Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who arranged the murder of a rookie
policeman in a drug-related slaying that drew President Bush's
attention was sentenced to the maximum prison term: 25 years to
life.
   The sentencing of Philip Copeland on Tuesday prompted long,
thunderous applause from about 150 policemen who packed the
courtroom.
   ``You are unfit to be a member of our society,'' Judge Thomas A.
Demakos told the 23-year-old Copeland. ``This arrogant act assaults
our society.''
   Copeland also got a five-to-15 years in prison for weapons
possession, with the sentence to run concurrently. Demakos said he
wished the law allowed him to make the terms consecutive.
   The judge said he would recommend no parole. He said that when
he retires, his last act would be to remind the parole board of his
recommendation.
   Copeland was convicted for the February 1988 slaying of Officer
Edward Byrne, who was shot five times as he sat alone in a parked
patrol car.
   The 22-year-old officer was guarding a house that had been
firebombed after its owner complained about drug dealers in the
Queens neighborhood. The man has since been relocated in a
witness-protection program.
   Assistant District Attorney Eugene Kelly called Copeland the
mastermind of the plot.
   ``This is a crime of monstrous proportions. ... This was a
message to society,'' Kelly said of the sentence.
   Byrne's mother, Ann, wept as she heard the sentence. Her
husband, Matthew, a former police lieutenant, was stoic.
   Copeland also showed no emotion.
   When his lawyer, Frank Hancock, told the judge Copeland feared
for his safety in prison, the officers in the courtroom again
applauded.
   Hancock said later he had gotten a letter from Copeland's
cousin, also a prisoner, saying prison guards intended to provoke
Copeland, restrain and beat him.
   Asked how Copeland felt about the letter, Hancock replied,
``It's not his major concern. His major concern is that they not
cut his hair'' because of his Rastafarian beliefs.
   About 10,000 uniformed police officers from around the country
attended Byrne's funeral.
   Police, who saw the killing as a defiant message from the drug
world, established Tactical Narcotics Teams of undercover officers
to sweep dealers off the streets in drug-plagued neighborhoods.
   Byrne's father presented then-GOP nominee Bush with his son's
police shield during the presidential election campaign. Bush
showed the shield to audiences around the country when he spoke
about the need to crack down on illegal drugs.
   Copeland was one of three people convicted of second-degree
murder and a weapons charges after a two-month trial.
   The judge postponed until June 6 the sentencings of Todd Scott,
20, and Scott Cobb, 25.
   The trial of 21-year-old David McClary, identified by Scott and
Cobb as the triggerman, was postponed a day until Thursday after
his lawyer filed an appeal that it be moved.
</TEXT>
