<FIRST>r a PM-DomesticSlayings     05-17 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Domestic Slayings,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Woman Killed in 20 Months in Rural Massachusetts Village</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TURNERS FALLS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A village that went a century
without a homicide is reeling from the fourth slaying of a woman in
less than two years, all apparently the result of domestic
disputes, police said.
   Police acting on a tip found the body of Tracy Sheperd, 27,
early Tuesday in the woods, District Attorney Judd Carhart said.
   He said she was killed about a week ago, apparently after a
fight with her boyfriend.
   Carhart declined to say how the woman was killed pending an
autopsy.
   David MacDonald, a 30-year-old bartender, was arrested in the
couple's apartment, Police Chief Michael Saharceski said. He
pleaded innocent to a murder charge and was ordered to undergo
psychiatric tests.
   The chief said the only links among the four killings were that
the couples were all young and unmarried. Before the recent quartet
of slayings, the last prior homicide in the village of 5,700 was in
the 1880s, when two paper mill workers fought in a bar, Saharceski
said.
   ``They are just cases of domestic violence, and who knows why
they happen?'' he said. ``We could have a police officer on every
corner in town and we still couldn't stop what happened.''
   Last week, before the fourth slaying was discovered, several
hundred people marched in Greenfield to protest domestic violence.
The march was one of several community events held to increase
public awareness about violence.
   ``It is deeply ironic, if that's even the right word, to find
out after a whole week of education on violence that here we have
another murder to deal with,'' said Debra McLaughlin, a rally
organizer. ``It's hard not to feel overwhelmed.''
   ``It's insanity,'' said Mary Osborn, who lives just across the
Connecticut River in Greenfield.
   Ms. Osborn, a part-time student and volunteer at a women's
shelter in Northampton, blamed the violence in part on hard times
in the town of 6,000 people.
   ``It's working class, depressed, the factories are all gone, the
people have been stripped of dignity in a lot of ways,'' she said.
   The first woman to die was Vivian Morrisey, 31, strangled in
September 1987 in her home. Her former boyfriend was convicted of
murder and sentenced to life in prison.
   Nearly a year later, Virginia Ferrer, 27, onetime resident of a
shelter for battered women, was stabbed to death behind her home.
Police arrested a man identified as the father of four of her
children. He is awaiting trial.
   Catherine Gochinski, 16, was found shot to death Feb. 3 in the
apartment she shared with her 18-year-old boyfriend and his sister.
He also is awaiting trial.
</TEXT>
