<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Green     05-17 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Green,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five-Time Oscar Winner John Green Dies at 80</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Green, who pursued a music
career despite advice from his father and won five Oscars for movie
scores including ``An American in Paris'' and ``Easter Parade,''
has died. He was 80.
   Green died at home Monday night of pulmonary edema, said his
spokesman Frank Liberman. Green had suffered a stroke two years ago.
   ``He was the best of his kind,'' said frequent collaborator Gene
Kelly. ``There are none like him around any more. ... He was the
granddad of the musical score on every movie.''
   Green, an accomplished pianist, began playing at age 3. Nine
years later, he became a protege of George Gershwin.
   Green received 14 Academy Award nominations in a career spanning
decades. His Oscar victories came for scoring ``Easter Parade,''
``An American in Paris,'' ``West Side Story'' and ``Oliver!'' and
for producing the one-reel short subject ``The Merry Wives of
Windsor Overture.''
   Additional awards included the recording industry's Grammy, the
film industry's Golden Globe, and an Aggie, the highest award of
the Songwriters Guild.
   In 1983, the American Society of Music Arrangers named Green the
first recipient of its President's Award for distinguished service
to music, musicians and the entertainment industry.
   He had remained active until a few days before his death. On
Sunday, he produced the annual gala for the John Douglas French
Foundation for Alzheimer's disease, of which he was a founder.
   In March 1987, Green appeared with Leonard Bernstein, Liza
Minnelli, Bobby Short and Mikhail Baryshnikov in a gala Public
Broadcasting System tribute to Gershwin.
   A member of the Songwriters Hall of Fame, Green's best known
compositions included ``Coquette,'' ``Out of Nowhere,'' ``I Cover
the Waterfront,'' ``I Wanna be Loved,'' ``The Song of Raintree
County'' and ``Body and Soul.''
   Green, who served as the general music director for MGM Studios
from 1949 to 1958, either produced or conducted nine Oscar
presentations, including the first shown on television in 1953. For
that pioneering telecast, Green was named a lifetime member of the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
   He also worked as a producer of television films for Desilu
Productions, the company founded by Lucille Ball and Desi Arnaz.
   Born Oct. 10, 1908 in New York, Green graduated at age 19 from
Harvard University with an economics degree.
   Although his song ``Coquette'' was already a sheet-music hit, he
followed his father's advise and briefly took a job on Wall Street.
   His father had told him: ``Son, ... you can be a good banker, a
good lawyer or doctor and you'll be a proud, respected citizen in
the community. But there is no bum in the world like an artist who
is merely good, and I'm afraid as a musician you are merely good.''
   ``I was a sissy to do it,'' he once said of following his
father's advice.
   But after six months on Wall Street he went to work for
Paramount as a rehearsal pianist.
   Green is survived by his wife of 45 years, Bonnie, a former
showgirl at MGM, three daughters and four grandchildren.
   A memorial service will be held Monday at the Bel-Air
Presbyterian Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     05-17 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prominent Playwright Released Early From Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playwright Vaclav Havel,
Czechoslovakia's most well-known opposition activist, was freed on
probation today after serving half of an eight-month jail sentence
on protest-related charges.
   Havel was arrested in January during a week of anti-government
protests.
   His imprisonment, widely condemned in the West as well as by
intellectuals in Poland, Hungary and the Soviet Union, marked the
start of a new crackdown on dissent by Czechoslovak authorities.
   Czechoslovakia's Communist leaders have resisted the political
reforms that are sweeping through much of the rest of the Soviet
bloc.
   Judge Eva Kvetenska ruled after a 12-minute hearing that Havel
could be freed on good behavior but would be on probation for 18
months. If he violates the law in that time he would be jailed
again for four months.
   Czechoslovak supporters admitted to the small courtroom
adjoining the Pankrac prison where Havel was held applauded as he
embraced his wife, Olga, after the ruling.
   ``I certainly think all the actions of solidarity helped a
lot,'' Havel said after he was released about an hour later. ``I am
glad I was released, but the whole sentence was nonsense. I should
not have been in jail at all.''
   Havel, a co-founder of the Charter 77 human rights movement, may
have been released early to head off criticism at an international
human rights conference opening in Paris on May 30, opposition
activists said.
   Czechoslovakia is one of the 35 nations that signed the 1975
Helsinki Final Act that will attend the meeting.
   ``I am optimistic for one reason, that they would prefer to look
nice in Paris rather than ugly,'' said Havel's brother Ivan. ``But
all that is guesswork. We know that our authorities are not at all
concerned with their public image.''
   At least 20 opposition activists have been jailed, fined or
given suspended sentences since the January protests.
   Havel, 52, was sentenced on Feb. 22 to nine months in jail on
charges of incitement and obstructing a police officer at a
demonstration in Prague on Jan. 16.
   An appeals court threw out the obstruction charge in February
and reduced the sentence to eight months. Havel then was moved to
another jail where conditions were better and he was entitled to
ask for parole midway through his sentence.
   Havel was charged with incitement after he used Western radio
stations to appeal to the anonymous authors of a letter who wrote
him threatening to commit suicide to protest the lack of democracy
in Czechoslovakia.
   He urged the writers not to emulate Jan Palach, a Czech student
who died after setting himself ablaze in January 1969 to protest
the previous summer's Soviet-led invasion that crushed Prague
Spring reforms.
   About 3,300 people had signed a petition supporting Havel's
request for parole, Ivan Havel said.
   When the playwright was sentenced to 4{ years in jail on charges
of sedition in 1979, no one in Czechoslovakia spoke up on behalf of
Havel and fellow Charter 77 activists jailed with him.
   After Havel's trial in February, Premier Mieczyslaw Rakowski of
Poland attended the Warsaw premiere of two Havel plays, which are
banned in Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0057 </DOCNO>
