<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-17 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Lash Texas, Plains with Tornadoes, Hail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms continued to hover over Texas this
morning after a day of severe storms that spawned several tornadoes
and produced torrential rains and hail up to 4{ inches in diameter.
   Storms also continued in parts of the central and southern
Plains and lower Mississippi Valley.
   Storm clouds dropped seven tornadoes Tuesday afternoon and
plastered the town of Shamrock with 4{-inch hail.
   During the evening, tornadoes touched down in north-central
Texas at Joshua and at Cleburne, and in southern Hood County. Golf
ball-size hail struck several northern and western towns including
Amarillo and Midland, and smaller hail fell elsewhere.
   Winds gusted to 60 mph at Van Horn and destroyed a house in
Kinney County.
   Some areas of eastern Texas reported 5 to 7 inches Tuesday,
closing several roads and bridges, while more than four inches of
rain caused flash floods in some north-central areas.
   Severe storms also stretched from the Plains to the Gulf Coast
Tuesday evening. A thunderstorm touched down near Westcliffe,
Colo., and one-inch hail fell at Mooreland and Cedar Springs,
Okla., and at Baton Rouge, La.
   Strong thunderstorms were clustered over central and northwest
Texas early today.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms also extended across northern
Texas and southern Oklahoma into southwest Arkansas and northwest
Louisiana, and from northwest Oklahoma across western Kansas into
eastern Colorado.
   In the 6 hours ended at 2 a.m. EDT, 2.38 inches fell near
Amarillo, nearly 2 inches fell at Dallas and nearly 1{ inches were
recorded at Baton Rouge.
   Rain continued to fall along the East Coast, with showers
extending this morning from eastern Virginia to southern New
England. Dry weather prevailed elsewhere.
   Today's forecast called for severe storms across the southern
Plains and the lower Mississippi Valley, with numerous severe
thunderstorms and possible tornadoes expected over much of central
and eastern Texas and western Louisiana. Showers and thunderstorms
also were forecast for much of the rest of the Great Plains and
Mississippi Valley. Showers were expected to extend along the
central and southern New England coast, across New Jersey and
southeastern Pennsylvania, and along the northern Pacific Coast.
   Highs were expected to be in the 50s and 60s from central Maine
across southern New England, New Jersey, eastern Pennsylvania and
southeastern New York state, as well as from northern Oregon across
Washington state, and scattered along the California coast; the 60s
from much of Nebraska across western Kansas, southeast Wyoming,
Colorado, New Mexico and northeast Arizona; near 80 degrees over
northeast New York state and west-central New England; the 80s and
low 90s from South Carolina across Florida, from much of Kentucky
across the central Gulf Coast, much of Louisiana and southern and
central Texas, and from eastern California and much of Nevada
across western Arizona. Highs elsewhere were expected to be in the
70s.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 82 degrees at Laredo, Texas.
   Other reports:
