<FIRST>r p PM-SeattleDevelopment     05-17 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seattle Development,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seattle Slow-Growth Initiative Backers Cheered by Big Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits to correct category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Election Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An initiative to slow downtown growth passed
easily, surprising both supporters and opponents and leaving
backers of the measure ecstatic.
   ``We have won on the first try, which I think is remarkable,''
said Ted Inkley, chairman of the campaign for the Citizens
Alternative Plan. ``We had a sense when we began this campaign that
there was a great deal of anger about how government had handled
growth issues in the past 10 years.''
   Initiative 31, known as CAP for Citizens Alternative Plan, won
62 percent approval at the polls Tuesday. With 98 percent of
precincts reporting, the vote was 42,007 to 25,958. A simple
majority was required for passage.
   The plan would limit the height and density of downtown
buildings for the next 10 years while a long-range growth
management plan is adopted. It is exempt from City Council
amendments for two years.
   This city of 500,000 situated across Puget Sound from the
Olympic Mountains already has more than 10 buildings higher than
450 feet. The 76-story Columbia Center is the West Coast's tallest
building.
   Inkley and most opponents _ including the bulk of the city's
business and labor establishment _ had predicted a close vote.
   But Peter Steinbrueck, another backer of the plan, had predicted
approval by as much as 2-1.
   ``I had a feeling in my bones about it,'' Steinbrueck said. ``I
think that the city just didn't buy the incredible claims that were
made (by opponents), and I think that the growth problems were
self-evident.''
   The plan limits the height of new buildings to 450 feet, about
38 stories; protects low-income housing; reduces density of new
projects, and requires a long-term downtown growth management
program.
   Total downtown construction would be limited to 500,000 square
feet of office space a year from 1990 through 1994 and to 1 million
square feet a year from 1995 through 1999.
   The likely impact of the measure remained in doubt.
   Moreover, buildings now under construction, projects vested
under permits issued before the initiative was filed and
development permitted under the initiative are likely to maintain a
surplus of downtown office space well into the 1990s.
</TEXT>
