<FIRST>r a PM-LadleDeaths     05-17 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ladle Deaths,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Found Guilty of Killing Sons in Foundry Ladle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury rejected an insanity defense and
convicted a man who killed his two young sons by putting them in a
red-hot foundry ladle.
   Bartley J. Dobben was found guilty of first-degree murder but
mentally ill in the Thanksgiving Day 1987 deaths of his sons by a
Muskegon County Circuit Court jury on Tuesday.
   First-degree murder carries a mandatory sentence of life without
parole. A guilty but mentally ill verdict allows psychological
treatment for convicts.
   ``We're shocked,'' defense attorney Pat Nolan said, adding he
would appeal the verdict. ``We expected a verdict of not guilty by
reason of insanity. I don't think there was any evidence to support
the verdict.''
   Dobben, 28, of Muskegon, was accused of killing his sons,
Bartley, 2, and Peter, 15 months. He was charged with putting the
boys in a 1,300-degree foundry ladle at the plant where he worked
while his pregnant wife waited outside.
   Circuit Judge James Graves Jr. scheduled sentencing for June 16.
   ``We're satisfied with the verdict,'' county Prosecutor Tony
Tague said. ``Our main concern was that he be confined and not
released into society because he is a danger.''
   The defense contended Dobben, diagnosed a paranoid
schizophrenic, was legally insane at the time of the slayings.
Brett Gardner, an assistant Muskegon County prosecutor, contended
Dobben killed his sons because his marriage of four years was
failing.
   Family and friends portrayed Dobben as a loving, attentive
father who was obsessed with religion and believed the end of the
world was near.
   Bizarre behavior, suspicions that his wife was unfaithful and an
obsessive belief that his family was in danger resulted in a
60-day, court-ordered stay at a psychiatric hospital in late 1985.
   After a relatively calm year during which Dobben took powerful
psychotropic drugs that controlled his behavior, he was persuaded
by a self-ordained minister to stop taking his medication and leave
his wife, witnesses said.
   Susan Dobben testified she forgave her husband a day after the
slayings and wanted him back home with her. The couple's third son
will be 1 year old in June.
   ``He would have given his life for those kids,'' she testified.
</TEXT>
