<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Commencements 1stLd-Writethru a0442 05-17 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Commencements, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Borrowing Heavily From Himself in Speeches</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 3rd graf, He selected, to make it Boston University
sted College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has been stumping the
cap-and-gown circuit in recent days with a formula: sports,
reminiscences and apologies.
   Bush apologizes for the length of graduation speeches, recalls
his own days at Yale in the late 1940s and employs sports stories
and metaphors _ working in references to a hometown team whenever
possible.
   He selected five colleges for commencement addresses. And with
three down _ Texas A&amp;M, Alcorn State and Mississippi State _ and
two to go _ Boston University and the Coast Guard Academy _ Bush is
beginning to borrow heavily from himself.
   ``I know how deadly long graduation speeches can be. I'll never
forget Yale University where I went,'' Bush tells graduating
seniors. Then he launches into a familiar anecdote about a
long-winded speaker:
   ``A man got up, he says, `I'm going to give you a brief
graduation speech. And I will choose, because our school has a
short name _ Y, is for youth.' He went on for about 30 minutes. And
then it's A, altruism ...'''
   Bush relates that by the time the speaker has gotten through the
four letters of Y-A-L-E, an hour and a half has gone by ``and there
was only one person left, his head bent in prayer.''
   ``Well sir, I see that you are praying for these values,'' the
president's story goes. ``The man said, `no, no. I wasn't praying
for the values. I was giving thanks that I did not go to Alcorn
State University.'''
   That's how he told it at Alcorn State in Lorman, Miss., the
other day. Later, he gave the same joke at Mississippi State in
Starkville, but the punchline was: ``No sir, I was giving thanks
that I didn't go to Mississippi State University.''
   Then Bush ran into trouble. As he finished his speech, he said:
``My friends, you've worked hard and studied hard and struggled for
four years. And now you've endured the hardest part: listening to
the commencement address.
   ``And I haven't even begun. Let's see: Y-M-I-S ...''
   Bush does better on sports than on spelling.
   The captain of the 1948 Yale baseball team told Texas A&amp;M
graduates: ``When you look back at your days at Texas A&amp;M, you will
have a lot to be proud of _ a university that is first in baseball
and first in service to our nation.''
   At Alcorn State, Bush said: ``The Alcorn Braves know that you
can't steal second base and keep one foot on first.'' He paused, a
bemused expression crossing his face as he mulled over the line.
``That's profound,'' he said.
   And, at Mississippi State, Bush declared: ``I've been lucky. A
wonderful wife and five great kids. Five kids and 11 lively
grandkids, and by themselves, they could field the Bulldog's entire
pitching staff.''
   Bush surveyed the stadium audience. ``And I understand you
people with the earphones staying plugged into the baseball game.
If I were sitting up there, I'd be doing exactly the same thing,''
he said.
   Bush also has been sneaking the ``new breeze'' he talked about
in his inaugural address into his college speeches. He told Texas
A&amp;M seniors that ``a new breeze is blowing across the steppes and
cities of the Soviet Union.''
   At Alcorn State, he said, ``Politics is hardly the only arena
where a new breeze is blowing. Some of you will land in business,
maybe even start a business where you can create jobs adding to the
opportunity of other Americans ...''
   At Texas A&amp;M, Bush gave what was billed as a major foreign
policy speech on U.S.-Soviet relations. But he was apologetic about
it, telling his audience: ``It had to happen. Your last day in
college had to end with yet another political science lecture!''
   Bush's wife, Barbara, has also been spending time on campus.
   The other day, smiling in a black cap and gown at commencement
at Bennett College in Greensboro, N.C., she recalled her advice to
her own children: ``Clean your plate, remember the starving Chinese
... don't put that in your ear ... don't cross your eyes ... don't
put that in your mouth, you don't know where it's been.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   In addition to sowing seeds of wisdom at college graduations,
Bush is also traipsing around the nation planting trees for state
centennial ceremonies.
   However, the first tree he transplanted from the White House
lawn, an elm for the grounds of the North Dakota Capitol at
Bismarck, turned out to be infected with destructive gypsy moth
larvae.
   Bush is expected to plant more trees in the coming months in
South Dakota, Montana, Wyoming and Washington state. White House
aides are hopeful they won't harbor the same unwelcome guests.
</TEXT>
