<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GreenRiver     05-17 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green River,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Confirms Green River Task Force Winding Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven years after the Green River serial killer
claimed his first victim, the police task force formed to track the
slayer is slowly being phased out, a sheriff said. No arrests have
been made.
   The killer, the subject of a nationally syndicated television
show in December, is officially blamed for the deaths of as many as
48 young women, many of them prostitutes, between the summer of
1982 and early 1984. Four victims were found in Oregon, but the
killer operated primarily in the Puget Sound area.
   The task force, which totaled more than 40 people, including FBI
agents, at its peak, now comprises eight detectives, two sergeants
and two desk clerks, KIRO-TV reported Tuesday night.
   King County Sheriff James Montgomery said police officers once
assigned to the nation's worst unsolved serial murder case were
needed elsewhere to fight the county's rising crime rate.
   Although Montgomery said the task force is gradually being
phased out, he did not say when it might be disbanded completely.
   ``I suspect it'll be one of those days when we'll just simply
say, `Where did it go?''' the sheriff told the TV station.
   In July 1988, when the task force numbered about 20 officers,
Montgomery said he would recommend reducing it by mid-1989 unless
there were fresh leads in the case.
   Capt. Bob Evans, commander of the task force, said two months
ago that the TV movie ``Manhunt: A Chance to End the Nightmare''
produced 3,500 telephone tips and yielded arrests in two other
cases.
   Montgomery said the task force reduction does not make ``any
statement at all about what we feel about the victims. It's a
matter of we have to continue on with what's going on in this
particular region today.''
   The case takes its name from the Green River in south King
County, where the bodies of the first five victims were found in
the summer of 1982.
</TEXT>
