<DOCNO> AP890517-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0955EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-Students 5thLd-Writethru   05-17 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Students, 5th Ld-Writethru,a0537,0979</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 1 Million March Through Beijing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with students saying agreement with
government may be imminent, marches in other cities. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1 million people demanding democracy
and supporting student hunger strikes marched triumphantly through
Beijing streets today in the biggest protest in Communist China's
40-year history.
   Two student representatives met later with government and party
officials and said they were optimistic an agreement would be
reached soon on their demands, which include formal talks with the
government to be broadcast live.
   The protest began after student leaders rejected Communist Party
chief Zhao Ziyang's appeal that 3,000 students end a four-day fast
that has been the catalyst for this week's unrest.
   Today's huge march through the streets of the capital was the
biggest of the pro-democracy rallies that have embarrassed the
government during Mikhail S. Gorbachev's historic visit and forced
major changes in his schedule.
   The protest was dominated today for the first time by workers
rather than students. The march began in central Tiananmen Square,
the site of the hunger strike, to the sound of firecrackers set off
under the huge poster of Mao Tse-tung at the entrance to the former
Imperial Palace.
   Protesters draped banners from the rostrum over the gate, where
Mao declared the founding of the People's Republic on Oct. 1, 1949.
Many banners called for the retirement of 84-year-old senior leader
Deng Xiaoping and the resignation of Premier Li Peng.
   Fifty taxis stuffed with flag-waving passengers led a procession
of workers, journalists, government employees and even soldiers.
   Smaller marches headed outward from the square, China's symbolic
center of power, while more people streamed on bicycle and foot
toward the square, which has been clogged for four days by
protesters.
   Most streets in the center of this city of 10 million people
were clogged. Police made no effort to intervene and few were seen
on the streets.
   ``Chinese aren't stupid,'' said marching journalist Shen
Yinghua. ``You can suppress us for a long time, but when we blow,
we spit fire.''
   Later in the day, two students met with the secretaries of Zhao
and Li.
   ``Tonight we could have some good news,'' said one of the
student representatives, Cheng Zhen.
   Students also agreed that police would help direct snarled
traffic and clear paths for ambulances in streets jammed with
marchers. Police began guarding shopping areas to prevent possible
looting.
   The students prepared an open letter to the city's residents
urging they refrain from any violence.
   As pro-democracy protesters massed in the square this morning,
Gorbachev met with academicians in the adjacent Great Hall of the
People.
   The protests forced him to cancel a visit to the Imperial
Palace, the latest in a series of schedule changes they have forced.
   ``All these rallies made us nervous,'' Gorbachev said in an
interview broadcast by Chinese television. But he said his visit,
which has produced a normalization of Sino-Soviet relations after a
30-year chill, was going well.
   Similar demonstrations grew in size today in Shanghai, where
Gorbachev is scheduled to fly Thursday. At least 70 student
hunger-strikers lay in front of the Shanghai city hall, while about
20,000 students and supporters gathered around to chant for the
resignation of Shanghai Mayor Jiang Zemin. Many of the students
later marched across town.
   An American witness said the Shanghai protest began Tuesday and
grew today. Police cordoned off the area and tried to keep out
non-students, but thousands of workers managed to join them.
   Smaller marches were reported in Shenzhen and Guangzhou, both
near Hong Kong.
   In Beijing, laborers marched with banners naming their
factories. At least 1,000 soldiers joined the protest. Their
banners identified them as from the general staff office, logistics
department and political department.
   ``We're just regular soldiers, we want democracy and freedom
too,'' said a lieutenant.
   Employees from at least five government ministries participated,
as did 300 representatives from Capital Steel marching under a
banner that read: ``Return us our freedom.''
   Some postal workers declared themselves on strike and marched,
and there were unconfirmed rumors of other strikes. But most
workers said they would be back at work Thursday.
   In Tiananmen Square, the strikers lay under umbrellas and tents
fashioned from sheets for protection from the sun. At one point,
they recited their hunger-strike vow, with those able to standing
up.
   By this afternoon, 1,300 strikers had been sent to hospitals
after fainting. However, many came back after being revived and
given glucose.
   Marchers were concerned particularly with 10 hunger strikers who
have refused to drink water since early Tuesday and three who began
refusing water late Tuesday.
   In a message delivered to hunger strikers after midnight on
behalf of the top Communist Party leadership, Zhao affirmed the
students' patriotic spirit but asked that they end the strike.
   He promised that protesters would not face punishment and vowed
to ``work out concrete measures to enhance democracy and law (and)
oppose corruption,'' according to a report by the official Xinhua
News Agency.
   Zhao initially rejected demands for a dialogue with officials to
be broadcast live, but student leaders said they were optimistic
their demands would be met following the second meeting with
officials today.
   The effect of the protest on China's political make-up is not
yet clear, although some student leaders claim a Communist Party
official has warned that the strike could damage the position of
the so-called liberal faction that supports market-oriented
economic reform.
   But one student said the fasters ``are not starving here simply
to help some old man get more power. We are here for our whole
country. We want to go beyond factions.''
</TEXT>
