<FIRST>r a PM-PostalCake     05-17 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Postal Cake,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Birthday Greeting By Mail Takes The Cake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service takes the cake
_ in this case more than 200 miles, without messing the frosting,
even though it was packaged only in a shallow cardboard box with
flimsy cellophane covering.
   The turquoise-frosted birthday cake traveled from Dumont, in
western Minnesota, and arrived in this Minneapolis suburb in time
for Angie Wold's 22nd birthday Tuesday.
   ``My mother ...,'' sighed Wold when she received the
9-by-13-inch chocolate cake.
   Lorene Wold, postmistress at Dumont, mailed the cake Monday with
$4.15 of first-class priority postage stamps stuck to the flimsy
cellophane.
   ``I thought if everyone could see what was inside, they'd be
more careful,'' she said. ``I just wanted to her to have a cake on
her birthday. You know how mothers are.''
   The cake survived transfers in Dumont, Willmar, Minneapolis and
Bloomington.
   ``I've delivered 6-foot trees and coconuts with postage stamps
stuck to the side, but this is the first cake,'' said mail carrier
Joan Oswald.
</TEXT>
