<FIRST>r i PM-Hamadi-Stethems 1stLd-Writethru   05-17 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hamadi-Stethems, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0535,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Of Slain American Say Killer Should Die</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hamadi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD background, CORRECT no. of Americans testifying.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a U.S. Navy diver
slain during a TWA hijacking said today the court that convicted
Mohammed Ali Hamadi of air piracy and murder should have sentenced
him to death.
   After the court sentenced Hamadi to life in prison, the parents
said they hoped Hamadi would be forced to serve the full sentence.
   Their son, 23-year-old Robert Dean Stethem, was brutally beaten
and shot to death when the plane was hijacked to Beirut in June
1985.
   Richard Stethem, his wife Patricia at his side, read a statement
to reporters after the sentencing, breaking the silence they
maintained throughout the 10-month trial. The parents attended all
65 sessions.
   They indicated they were disappointed that Hamadi, a Lebanese
Shiite Moslem, could not receive the death penalty under West
German law. Life in prison is the maximum sentence.
   ``Our family maintains Mohammed Ali Hamadi deserves punishment
more severe,'' Richard Stethem said. He also warned against a
``possible political commutation of his sentence in the future.''
   ``We mention this because the thought of such a release is
painful for us to think of. Any commutation of Hamadi's sentence
would be a pure mockery of justice,'' Stethem said.
   Last week, Frankfurt lawyer Rainer Hamm said the Stethems and
the other 17 Americans who helped prosecute the case were concerned
that kidnappings or other types of ``blackmail'' might lead West
German authorities to release Hamadi early. Hamm represented the
American co-prosecutors.
   In the statement, Richard Stethem said: ``We would hope any
release would result in a public outcry by German and American
citizens alike and would cause people to express outrage against
this type of political injustice.''
   ``We would expect our present administration, State Department,
department of justice and Congress to monitor the fulfillment of
this sentence and to ensure it is completely served,'' Stethem
said, in a conference room at the Frankfurt prison where the trial
was held.
   He indicated, however, that he was satisified with the result so
far.
   ``We feel the German courts conducted a fair and impartial trial
resulting in an appropriate finding of guilt. We have remained
confident that with the conclusion of the many testimonies of the
American witnesses, nothing less than a life sentence would
result,'' Stethem noted.
   The Hamadi case strained relations between the United States and
West Germany after Hamadi's arrest. Bonn denied a U.S. extradition
request after two West German businessmen were kidnapped in Beirut.
   The two were taken hostage within a week of Hamadi's arrest at
Frankfurt airport on Jan. 13, 1987. Hamadi's brother, Abbas Hamadi,
was convicted of masterminding the kidnappings to force Mohammed's
release, and sentenced to 13 years in prison by a Duesseldorf court.
   The West German hostages, Alfred Schmidt and Rudolf Cordes, were
released in September 1987 and September 1988, respectively.
</TEXT>
