<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan     05-17 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Of Taiwan Submits Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Yu Kuo-hwa said today he has
resigned to preserve party unity and make way for a younger person.
   Yu, who has been premier since 1984, said he submitted his
resignation to President Lee Teng-hui earlier this week. It was not
immediately known whether it was accepted.
   ``I am resigning to maintain the unity of the ruling party ...
and to let younger people take this position,'' Yu said at a news
conference.
   Yu, 75, has been accused by members of the governing Nationalist
Party of being too conservative. News reports have said party
members intended to push for his resignation at a three-day party
meeting that begins June 3.
   Lu Ya-li, political science professor at the National Taiwan
University, said many members of the Nationalist Party believe Yu's
resignation will help strengthen the party in a congressional
election in December.
   The mass-circulation China Times Express said Lee plans to meet
Thursday with Lee Huan, secretary-general of the governing party,
to discuss the resignation.
   The newspaper said Lee Huan, 72, and Chiu Chuang-huan, 64,
Taiwan's provincial governor, are possible candidates to succeed Yu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
