<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos 1stLd-Writethru a0475 05-17 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Suffers Relapse; In Critical Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lede to UPDATE that Marcos remains critical today; Picks
up 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
has been placed back on a respirator and was listed in critical
condition today because of a recurrence of pneumonia, hospital
officials said.
   Marcos, 71, has been at St. Francis Medical Center since Jan. 15
with respiratory, heart and kidney ailments.
   He had been listed in guarded condition and was in a unit for
heart patients before his relapse prompted his return to intensive
care on Monday, hospital officials said.
   He also was reattached to a respirator, the hospital said in a
statement Tuesday night.
   ``It's an episodic thing. He has pneumonia and his condition has
been downgraded,'' said Eugene Tiwanak, assistant hospital
administrator.
   In April, doctors said Marcos was chronically ill and unlikely
to recover.
   ``Mrs. Marcos is of course very worried, but managing to hold
her composure,'' said Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, are under U.S. indictment on
charges they plundered more than $100 million from the Philippine
government and used the money to buy artworks and real estate.
   Because of his illness, Marcos has been separated from the case.
   The Marcoses have lived here since he was overthrown in a
popular revolt in February 1986.
</TEXT>
