<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   05-17 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: isn't easy.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 10
   The Bulletin, Bend, Ore., on the savings and loans bailout:
   Congress still is wrestling with the specifics of how the
government is going to bail out the failed savings and loans, but
it is obvious that the whole mess is going to land in the laps of
American taxpayers.
   Grit your teeth, because here's what you'll pay for: the
expensive promotions and lavish parties sponsored by now-defunct
S&amp;Ls; the losses suffered by depositors who eagerly opened accounts
at high interest rates the S&amp;Ls could not afford; the thousands of
unwise building projects that cost too much and went broke; and the
failed mortgages that belonged to property speculators who
defaulted when the Texas oil boom went bust.
   The latest estimates place the cost of the bailout at something
between $157-$187 billion. ... The (Baltimore) Evening Sun recently
estimated that the cost is expected to come to about $600 for every
man, woman and child in America over the next 30 years.
   That's $2,400 for a typical family of four _ a huge price to
exact from innocent taxpayers to pay for bad management, sleazy
financial deals and the government's inability to adequately
regulate this industry.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 15
   The Morning News Tribune, Tacoma, Wash., on Soviet defense
motives:
   Imagine that U.S. defense policies were decided the way Soviet
policies are: without public debate, congressional oversight or
pesky critics.
   Were that the case, the administration could turn every arms
economy into a propaganda coup. The 1990 defense budget, for
example, proposes to retire naval warships, pare back
missile-defense reseach, cut troop strength and delay the Stealth
bomber program.
   Everyone knows this is being done to save money. But if this
were a closed society, the expedience of the cutbacks wouldn't be
so obvious. The president could stand up in some international
forum and dramatically present all these reductions as a grand
sacrifice for world peace.
   That's why it's best to hold the applause on Mikhail Gorbachev's
peace initiatives, including his latest offer to unilaterally
withdraw 500 tactical nuclear warheads from Europe. As generous as
these gestures may appear, chances are they are prompted by
economic necessity or shrewd political calculation. ...
   Gorbachev's more serious overtures should be taken more
seriously, of course. His proposal for reducing and equalizing
conventional forces on both sides of the Iron Curtain is promising.
It addresses the fundamental question: Is the Soviet Union willing
to demilitarize its economy and permanently abandon the theat of
force?
   When that question is answered, there'll be no need for
guess-work about the real agenda of the Kremlin.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 12
   Wausau (Wis.) Daily Herald on the need for small businesses:
   The salaries are smaller, the employee list shorter, and the
bottom lines don't make CNN's business report, but running a small
business has its own kind of perks.
   Does the chief executive officer of Ford know every employee
personally and does he know when an employee has a baby or a parent
dies? No, but owners of small businesses often do. ...
   Family members care for each other and notice when someone's
feeling under the weather. Those are personal benefits that don't
come in the form of a paychceck, but keep people working for the
same company for a quarter-century or more.
   It's the small businesses _ all 17 million of them _ that hold
together the nation's economy and account for two of every three
new jobs.
   From the retail shop owner to the local clinic workers to the
plumber down the street, small-business men and women are working
hard to better their lives and the lives of their families.
   Multiply that type of dedication by 17 million, and you've
calculated the lifeblood of our economy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 15
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on the Hatch Act:
   For the second time in two years, the House of Representatives
has passed a bill wiping out safeguards against the politicization
of the federal work force. The 1987 bill was killed in the Senate;
this time the country may not be so lucky.
   Under threat is the Hatch Act, which bars federal employees from
partisan political activism.
   Does the Hatch Act infringe (on) the rights of federal workers
to freedom of speech? The Supreme Court has repeatedly said ``No'';
a 1973 ruling cited ``the judgment of history ... that federal
service should depend on meritorious performance rather than
political service.''
   Hatch's intent is clearly not to bully civil servants, but to
shield them from bullying by their superiors _ and by their
increasingly powerful union leaders.
   Even more important, the Hatch Act protects the general public.
If you need to talk with a federal employee about your tax bill or
Social Security check, you want to be confident that your political
activities will not influence his decision.
   Assistant Attorney General Thomas Boyd warns that if the new
assault on Hatch succeeds, ``the nonpartisan enforcement of federal
law ... would certainly be threatened and could be extinguished.''
President Bush should use his heavy artillery _ including his veto
power if necessary _ to prevent that.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
</DOC>
