<FIRST>u a PM-AbortionConsent 3rdLd-Writethru a0487 05-17 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Consent, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0487,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists: Kennedy Decision in Florida Case Tips Hand in Roe vs.
Wade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to update with lawyer's comments and recast,
picking up 8th graf, ``Before this...'; Deletes byline.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists on both sides of the abortion
debate are giving too much significance to a U.S. Supreme Court
justice's order blocking a 15-year-old girl's abortion, says a
lawyer who helped draft the appeal.
   Justice Anthony Kennedy decided Tuesday to, in effect, reinstate
a Florida law that requires women under 18 to obtain the consent of
their parents or a judge before they can get an abortion although a
state appeals court had ruled it unconstitutional.
   His order did not address any legal or constitutional issues,
but merely put off further consideration of the matter until the
full court's scheduled Thursday conference.
   Attorney Hunter Limbaugh said the only reason Kennedy was asked
for the order was because he is assigned to the 11th U.S. Judicial
Circuit which includes Florida.
   ``It isn't because we went justice shopping or that he has made
a decision on the Missouri case,'' said Limbaugh, referring to
another abortion case pending before the high court.
   The high court could use the Missouri case to change its Roe vs.
Wade ruling that in 1973 upheld the right of women to have
abortions.
   Kennedy and Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, both relative newcomers
to the court whose views on abortion reman widely unknown, are
considered to be the swing votes in Missouri's challenge to the Roe
vs. Wade decision.
   Earlier Tuesday, the Florida Supreme Court had suspended a state
law requiring minors to have a parent's or judge's consent to an
abortion until the court rules on the law's constitutionality in
September.
   Limbaugh, of Leesburg, assisted lawyer Richard Boyleston, from
Tavares, who was appointed to represent the fetus of the
15-year-old central Florida girl who challenged the state's consent
law. The teen-ager, identified in court documents as T.W. of Lake
County, is 12 weeks pregnant.
   ``I feel optimistic, but of course I'm devastated for my client
because hours and days are important right now,'' said the girl's
attorney, Jerri Blair of Leesburg, who was preparing to file a
response to Kennedy's order.
   Some activists had argued that Kennedy's first order on an
abortion issue sent a strong signal of his stance on abortions.
   ``Before this he was a totally blank slate,'' said attorney
Frank Susman, who represents an Reproductive Health Services of St.
Louis, the abortion clinic defending against Missouri's challenge
of Roe vs. Wade.
   Other pro-choice supporters said they had expected Kennedy to
vote against abortion rights.
   ``The National Organization for Women has never doubted that
Justice Kennedy is hostile to the constitutional concept of the
right to abortion, and his action today bears out that
evaluation,'' said NOW President Molly Yard.
   ``We are appalled that Justice Kennedy would stay the decision
of the Florida Supreme Court to allow the teen-ager in question to
obtain an abortion without parental consent.
   ``With this teen-ager already 12 weeks pregnant, each passing
day has the potential of making an abortion more difficult and
possibly dangerous, if not impossible, for the young woman whose
life has become a judicial football.''
   Anti-abortion activists applauded Kennedy's action.
   ``This shows that, unlike some other justices, Kennedy takes
parental rights seriously,'' said Clarke Forsythe, general counsel
of Americans United for Life in Chicago.
   ``We're elated,'' said Jean Doyle, executive director of the
Florida Right to Life in Orlando. ``I think it's an indication that
the court has an interest in Florida's young people. It's a good,
healthy sign as far as I'm concerned.''
   Lawyers at the American Civil Liberties Union's headquarters in
New York City said the high court's intervention in the Florida
case could have nationwide implications if the justices decide to
take another look at whether a fetus has legal rights.
   The high court decided in Roe vs. Wade that a fetus doesn't have
the same constitutional rights as a newborn.
   ``There was no basis for appointing a legal guardian for an
11-week-old fetus,'' said Lynn Paltrow of the ACLU's Reproductive
Freedom Project. ``It could have a far-reaching trend that every
pregnant woman might need a guardian for her fetus.''
   Paltrow was referring to Richard Boylston, an attorney appointed
by a Lake County circuit judge after the girl made her request May
2.
   Boylston was the attorney who asked Kennedy for an emergency
stay, fearing that the girl might get an abortion immediately after
the state Supreme Court's decision Tuesday allowing the girl and
other minors to obtain abortions without consent from parents or a
judge.
   Parental consent laws in Ohio and Minnesota also are awaiting
action by the Supreme Court.
   Florida is among 14 states with consent laws, but two are
unenforced and three have been blocked by courts, said Kathryn
Kolbert, an ACLU lawyer in New York.
   In 12 other states, Ms. Kolbert said, parents only have to be
notified about the abortion, but that is not enforced in four
states and courts have blocked the laws in five other states.
</TEXT>
