<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Airlines     05-17 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Airlines,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks on Japan-U.S. Air Links Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks to expand air links between the United States
and Japan failed after Tokyo halved a proposal Washington had found
inadequate five months ago, a U.S. negotiator said today.
   ``We were taken by surprise,'' said the negotiator, who
requested anonymity.
   Talks were scheduled to resume in July, according to a Japanese
Transport Ministry spokesman.
   U.S. and Japanese airlines want to expand service on the
lucrative and busy passenger and cargo air routes.
   Seven million passengers traveled between the two countries in
1988 _ a 25 percent increase over the previous year _ and about a
quarter of all U.S.-Japan trade in goods moves by air, the official
said.
   In December, Washington proposed 16 new services for Japanese
carriers and 13 new services for U.S. carriers, while Japan
countered with 10 new lines for Japanese carriers and six for U.S.
carriers.
   The United States had hoped the two countries would reach a
compromise, the official said. But the new Japanese proposal was
for five new Japanese services and three new U.S. services, he said.
   Japanese negotiators reportedly said its already crowded
airports cannot accommodate much expansion.
   But the official said Japanese airlines have opposed expanding
U.S. air services and the government wants to protect its carriers
from competition.

</TEXT>
