<SECOND>PM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0570,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Strike Only Partly Successful In Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-OAS-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with merchants afraid to strike,
state-run oil company operating. Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``The government...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many factories, stores and street
stands were open today, though commuter traffic was lighter than
normal, as an opposition general strike to protest the voiding of
the May 7 election got under way.
   ``Some factories are opening, and some aren't. In those that
open some will come to work and some will support the strike,''
said a man standing outside a poultry and egg processing plant in
an industrial area.
   Some merchants said they were afraid to observe the strike. The
government of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega declared the strike
illegal because it has political, rather than economic, motives and
said order will be guaranteed.
   Panamanian military trucks dropped off patrolmen for their
normal beats, but no soldiers were visible at places they are often
stationed when the government expects trouble.
   The strike was also to protest the brutal beatings by Noriega
supporters of the opposition prsidential candidate and his running
mates.
   The one-day work stoppage coincides with the start of a special
meeting on the Panamanian crisis in Washington. The opposition
wants the Organization of American States foreign ministers to
recognize its victory in the elections.
   The government and the opposition _ which international
observers say won the election _ said they were sending
representatives to the meeting.
   As rush hour began in Panama City, traffic appeared lighter than
usual and there were no lines at many bus stops. Some normally
crowded buses ran almost empty. But gasoline stations were open, as
were many restaurants and markets. Street vendors sold their wares.
   A spokeswoman for the state-run oil company said many office
workers stayed home but that the company's trans-Isthmian oil
pipeline was operating normally.
   ``One is afraid of the consequences,'' said a woman who opened
her downtown office supply store. She said two of her four workers
did not report for work.
   The owner of a furniture said he feared reprisals and added that
business was so bad that ``to close down again would be fatal.''
   To frustrate the strike, the government set today instead of
Monday as a payday, and government-controlled union leaders
condemned the strike.
   The government began continuous jamming of U.S. Armed Forces
television Tuesday. That meant the only television station
available was one controlled by the government. Normally, the
government only jams news programming.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. government prepared to evacuate another
planeload of military personnel and dependents.
   On Tuesday, a jumbo jet chartered by the U.S. Air Force
evacuated 238 U.S. citizens in the first of many flights to
evacuate Americans who want to leave.
   U.S. Air Force Maj. Joan Ferguson said some of those aboard the
flight were vacating housing for people living off base who
President Bush had ordered to move onto military installations for
security reasons.
   The United States had been trying to oust Noriega for more than
a year and Bush last week ordered 1,900 reinforcements into the
country to beef up the 10,000-strong U.S. force already stationed
in Panama.
   In February 1988, Noriega was indicted on federal
drug-trafficking charges in Florida. The head of Panama's
15,000-member Defense Forces, he formerly was a close U.S. ally in
the region.
   Noriega denies the drug charges and says they are part of a ploy
to get rid of him in favor of someone who might abrogate the
treaties that cede U.S. control of the Panama Canal at the end of
the century.
   The opposition asked businesses to close today and people to
stay in their homes until noon, when they were to emerge for
protests ``by any imaginable means.''
   A restaurant owner who asked that neither he nor his
establishment be named said he planned to stay open during the
strike.
   ``The situation is too rough,'' he said today.
   The strike is also aimed at keeping pressure on the Organization
of American States.
   The opposition wants the OAS to impose sanctions that would
amount to a political and diplomatic quarantine of Panama if the
government refuses to recognize opposition candidates Guillermo
Endara as president and Ricardo Arias Calderon and Guillermo Ford
as vice presidents.
   The opposition claims it won the vote by a 3-1 margin.
   The government claimed a 2-1 margin for Noriega business
associate Carlos Duque. It said it nullified vote-counting on May
10 because Washington had interfered in the political process by
aiding the opposition. The CIA reportedly contributed $10 million
to the opposition campaign.
   No new election has been scheduled.
</TEXT>
