<FIRST>r a PM-High-TechSmuggling     05-17 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Tech Smuggling,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents: Network One of Largest Suppliers to Eastern Bloc</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Customs Service today announced the
seizure of $1.8 million worth of computers from a smuggling network
described as one of the largest U.S. suppliers of high-technology
equipment to Eastern bloc nations.
   The network purchased sensitive VAX computer systems in the last
two years for illegal shipment to the Eastern bloc, and tens of
millions of dollars worth of high-tech equipment had been shipped
in the past several years, Customs said.
   The 13-month, Miami-based undercover investigation, which
produced four arrests Tuesday and an arrest warrant for a Canadian,
was handled by a Customs operation named ``Miami Exodus Group.''
   Steve Smylie, his wife, Carole Smylie, and Kerry Blalock were
arrested in Houston, and Rick Parish was taken into custody in
Dallas. Warre Wetstein of Toronto was named in the arrest warrant.
   Two Digital Equipment Corp. VAX 8820 computer systems worth $1.8
million were confiscated in Colorado Springs, Colo. The system has
military and civilian applications and can be attached to existing
systems to upgrade them.
   The suspects were accused of using domestic and foreign
companies, brokers and freight forwarders to illegally export
computers, said Customs, which described the network as one of the
largest high-tech smuggling organizations ever investigated by the
agency.
</TEXT>
