<FIRST>u w PM-Shuttle-CloseCall 1stLd-Writethru a0469 05-17 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Close Call, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Astronaut Has Close Call With Pan Am Airbus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs with new details, changes separation to 100 feet;
picks up at pvs 10th graf: Leyden explained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aviation officials today were investigating a
possible violation of flight regulations by the commander of the
space shuttle Atlantis after he reportedly flew his jet trainer
within 100 feet vertically of a Pan Am airliner.
   Navy Capt. David M. Walker, was flying a NASA T-38 plane en
route to a White House ceremony honoring the Atlantis astronauts
when the incident, reported by the airliner's pilot as a ``near
midair collision,'' occurred Monday evening outside Washington.
   Near-collision reports generally are filed whenever planes come
within 500 feet of each other and are in danger of colliding.
   The National Transportation Safety Board opened a formal
investigation into the accusation, and the FAA and the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration were conducting separate
inquiries, officials said today.
   ``We are looking at a possible pilot deviation,'' FAA spokesman
John Leyden said. He said air traffic controllers reported the
alleged deviation after Walker's plane descended to 7,000 feet _
the same altitude as the airliner _ when it had been instructed to
go to 8,000 feet.
   The FAA spokesman said air traffic controllers reported the
vertical separation between the planes at 100 feet, and
investigators would have to examine recordings of data to determine
exactly how far apart they were at their closest point.
   Leyden said possible enforcement action against a civilian pilot
who deviates from procedures could range from an administrative
letter to action affecting his license, but since Walker is a Navy
pilot any conclusion would likely be referred to the military for
further action.
   The incident occurred at about 6:35 p.m. Monday some five miles
west of Washington Dulles International Airport in the northern
Virginia suburbs, Leyden said.
   Walker, contacted at his hotel room in Washington on Tuesday
night, refused to comment on the report of the near collision.
   ``That's something that I need to probably talk about with the
FAA about, not with the news organizations,'' he said. ``I'm going
to have to get my information from them before I start talking to
you all.''
   NASA spokesman David Garrett said Walker flew the jet to
Washington to attend Tuesday's White House ceremony at which
President Bush honored the shuttle astronauts. Garrett said he had
heard reports of a possible close call involving Walker but had so
far been unable to reach the pilot.
   Leyden explained, ``The pilot (of the NASA craft) was given an
8,000-foot assigned altitude. He was descending below his assigned
altitude of 8,000 feet to 7,000 feet, and that caused him to come
close to a Pan American Airbus 310.''
   Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon confirmed that the small plane
crossed the path of Pan Am Flight 140, which had just taken off for
Paris. The plane, which has 296 seats, was carrying 166 passengers
and a crew of 10, she said.
   ``It had taken off from Dulles and was at 7,000 feet when it
reported a T-38 aircraft came within what the captain believed to
be approximately 500 feet of the Airbus aircraft,'' said Hanlon.
   ``The pilot did not take any evasive action,'' but immediately
reported the incident to the Dulles Airport tower, said Hanlon.
   Bush honored Walker and his fellow shuttle astronauts, along
with two groups of school children who picked the winning name for
the newest space shuttle.
   Bush told Walker, Ronald Grabe, Norman Thagard, Mark Lee and
Mary Cleave, who returned May 8 from a four-day shuttle mission,
``You've reaffirmed your nation's genius in science and technology
and yet, I think we would all agree, this really is only just the
beginning.''
   The crew on the 29th shuttle flight launched the Magellan space
probe, which will orbit Venus after an 800-million-mile, 15-moth
journey and map the surface of Earth's fog-shrouded sister planet.
   The pupils, from Senatobia Middle School in Senatobia, Miss.,
and Tallulah Falls School in Tallulah Falls, Ga., had each
submitted the name ``Endeavour,'' for the shuttle being built to
replace the Challenger, which exploded after its launch in January
1986.
</TEXT>
