<FIRST>r p PM-Giuliani     05-17 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Giuliani,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prosecutor Announces for Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudolph W. Giuliani, who gained fame with his
high-profile prosecutions as U.S. attorney in Manhattan, announced
his candidacy for mayor today, promising to fight crime and restore
honest government.
   Giuliani, a Republican, told several hundred cheering supporters
that he was running in the spirit of Fiorello LaGuardia, a
Republican who won the mayoralty in 1933 in a city dominated, then
as now, by Democrats.
   ``He led a fusion movement, a movement forged by people of every
political stripe, to kick out an old, tired and corrupt
administration,'' Giuliani said. He spoke at the Metropolitan
Republican Club in Manhattan, where LaGuardia announced his
candidacy.
   Giuliani suggested that his election in itself would promote
honesty in government, declaring, ``A multiparty system is the most
effective check and balance on corruption in government.''
   ``Corruption in New York must be confronted and confronted
directly,'' he said. ``I am seeking support on one basis and one
basis alone _ that you agree with me that honest, decent, effective
government must be restored.''
   The city's last Republican mayor was John V. Lindsay, elected in
1965.
   Giuliani has made national headlines prosecuting mobsters, Wall
Street cheats and corrupt politicians.
   In the Republican primary Giuliani faces cosmetics heir Ronald
Lauder, who is running as a conservative more in tune with the
city's GOP stalwarts.
   Democratic Mayor Edward I. Koch, a 12-year incumbent, suffers
from lagging popularity and trails in the polls to a fellow
Democrat, Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins.
</TEXT>
