<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0564 05-17 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0564,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Parliament Approves Shamir Election Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with parliament approving Shamir
election plan. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``The plan...'' TRIMS thereafter to
tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today approved the prime minister's
Palestinian election plan after he defeated a challenge by
right-wing legislators in his Likud bloc who argued the plan could
lead to a Palestinian state.
   The tally was 43 to 15, with 11 abstaining, in a vote of
confidence in the government that was considered a test for the
plan. Fifty-one members of the 120-seat Knesset, or parliament,
were absent for the vote.
   The vote followed a seven-hour debate in the Knesset and a
contentious meeting of Likud legislators.
   The prime minister, Yitzhak Shamir, told Likud opponents of the
plan that pro-PLO activists in the occupied lands would not be
allowed to vote in the elections and insisted Israel would not give
up land to achieve peace.
   Before the vote, Shamir played down opposition by leading
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip who have
called his plan a ploy to cheat them out of a Palestinian state.
   ``From the Arab side, there have been voices of refusal and
rejection of the whole plan,'' Shamir told the Knesset. ``We do not
think these voices are the final word.''
   The plan, approved 20-6 by the Cabinet on Sunday, calls for
Palestinians in the occupied lands to elect representatives to
negotiate an interim autonomy settlement with Israel.
   In Tunisia on Tuesday, the Palestine Liberation Organization
formally rejected Shamir's plan. The PLO executive committee said
it denies the Palestinian's ``legitimate, national rights and
ignores international resolutions...that condemn the appropriation
of another's territory by force.''
   In Israel today, two extreme, right-wing opposition parties,
Tehiya and Moledet, submitted motions of no confidence over the
peace plan.
   Geula Cohen of Tehiya told parliament that Shamir's proposal
would cause violent opposition in Israel similar to the 17-month
Palestinian uprising against the Israeli occupation.
   ``If you fail to see the writing on the wall, then there will be
an uprising that will force you, Mr. Prime Minister, to bring an
entirely new proposal,'' she said.
   Before his parliament address, Shamir discussed his plan with
Likud legislators. Leading Likud figures oppose the plan, saying it
would pave the way for negotiations with the PLO and the creation
of a Palestinian state.
   ``The initiative states that we shall negotiate with any Arab
who is elected,'' said Likud legislator Pessah Grupper. ``This is
leading toward negotiations with the PLO.''
   Shamir said Palestinians ``involved in PLO activity will not be
able to run in elections or vote.'' It was not immediately clear
whether he also was referring to Palestinians who are sympathetic
to the PLO.
   Regarding a Palestinian state, Shamir said: ``It won't be and it
won't be created. And whoever says this, should his tongue cleave
to the roof of his mouth.''
   Shamir, who repeatedly banged his fist on a table during the
session with Likud, said he received PLO offers daily for direct
negotiations, ``but there is nothing to talk about because they
want a Palestinian state.''
   He said elections would not be held until the Palestinian
uprising has been crushed. Since the rebellion began in December
1987, 479 Palestinians and 21 Israelis have been killed.
   Shamir said Palestinians in east Jerusalem should not be allowed
to participate in the elections but told Likud members the issue
was left open.
   Israel annexed east Jerusalem after capturing it from Jordan in
the 1967 Middle East war. The United States would like to see
participation from Palestinians in the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
