<DOCNO> AP890517-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BotchedBurials     05-17 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Botched Burials,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Funeral Director Pleads Guilty in Burials Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former funeral director accused in a
string of improper burials pleaded guilty today to two counts of
grand larceny for burying bodies without caskets or vaults their
families had purchased.
   Bobby Wilks, 53, who pleaded guilty to burying Joseph Roath
without the casket and vault his family had ordered, could be
sentenced up to six years on each count.
   Investigators found the man's body had been wrapped in cardboard
and buried only 3 feet deep. Wilks also pleaded guilty to burying
Ollie Hester without a vault that had been paid for.
   ``Mr. Hester was buried. His son paid $750 for a vault, which
was not received,'' said District Attorney Ray Whitley. ``He later
paid $1,600 for a casket.''
   An investigation later showed that Hester was buried in a
cheaper casket than the family had purchased.
   A sentencing hearing will be scheduled after separate burial
fraud charges against Wilks are settled in neighboring Robertson
County, where he faces a 71-count indictment.
   Wilks operated funeral homes in Milldale and in White House,
small communities about 25 miles north of Nashville, before the
State Board of Funeral Directors and Embalmers suspended his
license on Oct. 20.
   His son, Gary, was charged with obtaining money under false
pretenses and larceny by false pretenses in connection with the
burials. Records showed he was not a registered apprentice or
licensed embalmer.
   The investigation into the family's mortuary business began Oct.
7 after a complaint that a Robertson County man was buried without
a vault that had been purchased.
   Authorities opened the grave and verified it had no vault, and
more than 30 bodies were exhumed in the following months at
graveyards in Sumner and Robertson counties in Tennessee, and in
Franklin, Ky.
   In some cases caskets were missing, trash was found buried with
other bodies.
</TEXT>
