<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     05-17 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says U.S. to Pay Rent for U.S. Facility for First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has agreed to pay
rent for a U.S. cultural center in South Korea for the first time
in more than 40 years, it was reported Wednesday.
   The Yonhap News Agency quoted a senior Foreign Ministry official
as saying the U.S. agreement to pay rent was ``an important event
in Korea-U.S. relations.''
   Yonhap also quoted Charge d'Affaires Thomas Brooks as saying the
United States will return the cultural center in the central city
of Kwangju to the city and start paying rent on a new office after
a two-year grace period.
   The Kwangju center has been a target of radical student attacks
and U.S. officials closed it temporarily May 10.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jack Sears declined to comment on the
report and said officials were still negotiating a new agreement.
   The U.S. government used the Kwangju center free under a 1948
agreement between the two nations, Yonhap said. It said Seoul also
has decided to ask for rent for the U.S. cultural center in Pusan,
a southern port city.
   Yonhap said the nations would review the 1948 agreement under
which the United States was allowed the continued use of some
facilities free of charge.
</TEXT>
