<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-US     05-17 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-US,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkey Allows U.S. to Modernize a Listening Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After two years of negotiations, Turkey
has accepted a U.S. proposal to modernize an American listening
station that monitors Soviet activities, officials said Wednesday.
   The United States would install a new computer to replace an
obsolete one from 1960, and build a ground satellite station for
better communication between the Pirinclik listening station and
the United States, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Inal Batu.
   Turkey approved the proposal a few weeks ago, he said.
   A Turkish official, who spoke on condition he was not
identified, said the Pirinclik station is mainly used for
monitoring Soviet activities in space.
   Batu said the approval stemmed from Turkey's desire ``to have a
good start'' with the Bush administration.
   The spokesman added that the U.S. government, complaining about
the level of noise from nearby Ankara, also wants to move the
Belbasi seismological station to another location and modernize the
Sinop station on the Black Sea.
   Negotiations were continuing on these two projects, he said.
   Under a defense cooperation pact, the United States maintains 12
bases in this NATO-member country.
</TEXT>
