<FIRST>r a PM-LATeachers     05-17 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Teachers,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Cease in Los Angeles Teachers' Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in the nation's second-largest
school district began the third day of their strike today, with
both sides disputing reports that a new salary package was under
consideration.
   Informal talks between Los Angeles Unified School District
officials and union leaders ceased, and union President Wayne
Johnson said today he was mystified by the lack of communication.
   ``I am less hopeful today than I was yesterday,'' Johnson said.
   Both sides awaited the release of a fact-finding report later
today. The state fact-finder began investigating the dispute in
March, when talks reached an impasse in the 16-month contract
negotiation.
   Diana Munatones, a district spokeswoman, said the report would
serve as a focal point for both sides to return to the bargaining
table.
   The seven-member school board met in executive session for four
hours Tuesday but there were no breakthroughs.
   School Board President Roberta Weintraub said they also awaited
details of Gov. George Deukmejian's revised state budget, to be
released Thursday, to determine if additional state funding will be
available for teacher salaries.
   ``This board again finds itself in the same dilemma that they
have continuously been in, and that is that until they get some
better picture of exactly what the dollars are ... then we can make
the better decisions than we've been able to make up until now,''
Ms. Weintraub said.
   Teachers are demanding a 21 percent pay increase in two years.
They also want relief from unpaid duties such as playground patrol,
and greater control in choosing curriculum and how money is spent.
   The district most recently offered a 21.5 percent pay increase
over three years. It also has offered to set up councils at
individual schools so that teachers would have greater input in
setting curriculum.
   The union represents about 22,000 teachers, counselors, nurses
and librarians. Striking teachers account for almost two-thirds of
the district's 32,000-member workforce.
</TEXT>
