<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CityEmployment     05-17 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-City Employment,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>City Government Employment on the Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of people employed by the nation's
cities is on the rise again, the Census Bureau reported Wednesday.
   Cities employed 2,541,000 people as of October 1987, the Bureau
said. That's 47,000 more than a year earlier and just 20,000
workers short of the all-time high in October 1980.
   The increase in 1987 _ the most recent figure available _
reflects hiring to provide services to growing city populations,
said Alan V. Stevens, head of the governments division of the
bureau's employment statistics branch.
   After peaking in 1980, city employment dropped sharply early in
this decade after cancellation of the Comprehensive Employment
Training Act, which provided federal money for governments to hire
and train workers. A weak economy at that time also held down
municipal hiring, Stevens said.
   More recently, he said, cities have responded to improving
economic conditions and the needs of the times by increasing their
workforces.
   For example, while overall municipal employees were up 1.9
percent between 1986 and 1987, city-employed corrections officers
increaseed 7.3 percent to 27,295.
   Corrections, Stevens noted, is a fast-rising job category for
states, counties and other governments also, with the spreading
drug problem and an increasing emphasis on jailing criminals.
   Judicial and legal employees of cities also increased sharply,
rising 11.9 percent to 38,609.
   The number of city-employed police officers, however, was up
only 1.7 percent to 312,123, the report showed.
   Overall, city governments had 148.2 workers per 10,000 residents
as of October 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
