<TEXT>
   A drought has forced electricity
rationing in northern Pakistan, with households and factories
having power cuts of two to six hours a day, a government official
said Wednesday.
   The generation of electricity has fallen from 6,000 megawatts
daily to 4,000 megawatts, with dams at only half their capacity,
said Zahid Ali Akbar Khan, head of the government utility company.
   In the capital of Islamabad, two-hour power cuts are in effect.
