<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Students     05-17 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Students,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Urges Negotiated Settlement of Demonstrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev urged a
negotiated settlement of China's internal turmoil on Wednesday and
said he has met with some of the students leading the huge rallies
for democracy.
   But the Soviet leader refused to take sides in the pro-democracy
demonstrations that have caused major disruptions in his historic
trip.
   The unrest rippling across the country reached a peak Wednesday
when more than 1 million people surged through Beijing's streets to
demand reform. Because of the crowds, officials moved Gorbachev's
news conference to the guest house where he is staying.
   Gorbachev told reporters he had seen the students who launched
the mass action and had talked to some of them, but he did not
elaborate.
   Gorbachev, who came to China to normalize relations after a
30-year rift, said it was not for him to judge who was right in the
dispute.
   ``I wouldn't take upon myself the responsibility or the role to
pass judgment, and I wouldn't seek to assess what is going on here
in this country,'' he said. ``I believe this is for the Chinese to
do and for the Chinese party.''
   But the Kremlin chief observed ``that a difficult, painful but
political dialogue is going on between the leadership, the youth
and the public concerning these events, and it seems to me that we
should welcome that fact.''
   ``I would only wish that solutions will be found in the process
of negotiation,'' Gorbachev said.
   Gorbachev, who was sent a petition signed by 6,000 students,
made a point of noting that he received ``a very warm letter'' from
students that endorsed his reforms in the Soviet Union. ``I value
their position and appreciate it,'' he said.
   Asked what he would do if similar demonstrations occurred in
Moscow, Gorbachev said he would negotiate.
   ``If problems of a similar nature occurred in the Soviet Union,
we would discuss those problems within the political process, in a
spirit of democracy and glasnost,'' he said.
   Several events planned for Gorbachev were canceled or
rescheduled to avoid the huge crowds. On Wednesday, Gorbachev and
his wife, Raisa, were prevented from touring the Forbidden City
just off Tiananmen Square, the sprawling plaza at the center of the
demonstrations.
   Gorbachev said he ``got a little emotional'' from the warmth of
young people he met during a visit to the Great Wall on Wednesday.
``But I'm human.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
