<DOCNO> AP890517-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildLabor     05-17 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Labor,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Seeks to Probe Alleged Abuses of Child-Labor Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumers group announced Wednesday a
national campaign to investigate alleged abuses of child-labor laws
and to pressure governments to improve enforcement of the standards.
   The National Consumers League also said it would seek to
determine the impact of increased employment among teen-agers on
education and family and personal relationships.
   ``From the sweatshops in New York to the fast food restaurants
in California, more and more young people are working _ and often
illegally,'' said Linda Golodner, the league's executive director.
   Ms. Golodner said the federal Labor Department's Wage and Hour
Division is woefully understaffed, with just 985 compliance
officers whose duties including monitoring labor laws.
   In most states, enforcement staffs are so small they cannot
conduct investigations, only investigate complaints and often are
discouraged from alleging violations unless there are repeat
offenses, she said.
   Ms. Golodner cited a recent Massachusetts study that found a 614
percent increase in child labor violations from 1983 to 1987 and a
New York report released last week that showed a 9.5 percent
increase in violations statewide from 1987 to 1988, with a reported
487 percent increase in violations in New York City, primarily in
the garment industry.
   ``Our goal is to gather information and statistics on child
labor in this country and recommend change in public policy,
regulation and legislation,'' Ms. Golodner said.
   She said the league would work with labor organizations, other
public interest groups and federal and state officials. Results of
the review are to be presented at a symposium in May 1990.
</TEXT>
