<FIRST>r w PM-Bennett-Sports     05-17 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bennett-Sports,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Policy Chief Meets With Pro Sports Executives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal drug policy coordinator William J.
Bennett met with commissioners and player representatives of
several professional sports today to exchange ideas on ways to
improve anti-drug standards for the country as well as pro
athletics.
   ``We all agreed on the importance of sports in American life,''
Bennett told reporters. ``We talked about the effort that
professional sports has made to get out a good, clear message to
kids about being drug-free, and the need to extend these efforts
and improve on them.''
   Bennett said he was anxious to see professional sports match the
fervent effort to curb drug use that he has suggested at the high
school level.
   ``I pressed pretty hard, I guess,'' he said. ``I said that from
my perspective, it would seem to me that when talked about being
tough on high school students and others, those policies needed to
matched at least at the level of professional sports.''
   No policies were put in place, but Bennett expressed hope that
some concrete ideas might come out of a follow-up meeting to be
held soon.
   ``Most important we have agreed to meet again this summer in a
month or two so we can have some specific suggestions for the
national strategy which I am writing,'' Bennett said.
   Among those at the meeting were National Football League
Commissioner Pete Rozelle, National Basketball Association
Commissioner David Stern and major league baseball Commissioner A.
Bartlett Giamatti.
   Steve Ryan, senior vice president for marketing and public
relations for the National Hockey League, was also present. NHL
President John Ziegler was not able to attend because of the start
of league playoffs.
</TEXT>
