<FIRST>r w AM-StarkRemembrance     05-17 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stark Remembrance,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribute to Sailors of Stark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new secretary of the Navy, H. Lawrence
Garrett, joined a tribute Wednesday to the 37 sailors who died
aboard the USS Stark two years ago in the Persian Gulf .
   The men ``gave themselves to the greatest value of human
existence _ freedom,'' Garrett said.
   ``The men of Stark ... were patriots and professionals,'' he
said. ``They knew the possible costs of their commitment. Yet these
men chose still to serve. And the memory of their service, of their
sacrifice, of their commitment to the values of our nation serve us
still.''
   The ceremony, at the Navy Memorial on Pennsylvania Avenue, was
sponsored by the group ``No Greater Love.'' The organization was
founded to help the children of Vietnam War prisoners and missing
in action as well as the families of hostages or victims of
terrorist attacks.
   The 37 sailors killed on the Stark died when the ship was hit by
missiles fired by an Iraqi fighter while the frigate was conducting
a patrol in the Persian Gulf.
   Iraq subsequently apologized to the U.S. government, saying its
fighter had mistaken the Stark for a tanker bound for arch enemy
Iran.
   On March 28, Iraq agreed to pay $27.3 million in compensation to
the 37 families, and the settlement checks were distributed by the
Navy on April 28.
   Garrett, the under secretary of the Navy at the end of the
Reagan administration, was sworn in as the Navy's secretary on
Monday.
</TEXT>
