<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CrisisEssays     05-17 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crisis Essays,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Use Essays to Spot Personal Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When teachers grade the year-end essays
of 50,000 Louisiana high school sophomores, they'll also be reading
between the lines for signs of personal crisis such as suicidal
tendencies or child abuse.
   The essay portion of the statewide 10th-grade exam will be
graded by a company that will flag compositions that ``need to be
brought to someone's attention,'' Robert Schiller, Louisiana deputy
superintendent of education, said Tuesday.
   The Education Department will send alarming papers to school
districts, where officials will decide whether to intervene,
Schiller said.
   Critics of the plan said it is an invasion of students' privacy,
and they questioned whether the test-graders are qualified to
recognize psychological problems.
   Officials expect warning signs to crop up in 0.2 percent of the
tests, or about 100 students. The tests were given in April and are
being graded now.
   The supervisor of the state's school psychological services, Jim
Canfield, has filed a protest memo calling the practice ``immoral,
unethical and probably illegal.''
   The state is required by law to get parental consent before
using the exams to make psychological judgments, Canfield said.
   ``Their intent may be good, but there has to be prior consent,''
he said. ``Parents don't know that this is happening, and if
nothing else, they should be made aware.''
   Measurement Inc. of Greensboro, N.C., has hired 70 people to
score the tests, most of whom have bachelor's degrees in English or
education, said Rebecca Christian, assistant director of the
Education Department's bureau of accountability.
   Measurement Inc. has done similar work for Mississippi, New
Jersey, South Carolina and Texas.
   Wendy Littlefair, project coordinator at Measurement Inc., would
not discuss the procedure.
   The essays ask the student to write about teen-age problems, a
format that could give students a chance to express suicidal
tendencies, instances of child abuse or other problems, Christian
said.
   Schiller said the evaluation is legal and part of the state's
``moral obligation to protect youngsters.''
   ``Measurement Inc. has the capability to flag when there might
be a particular problem, and we are setting up a mechanism whereby
we might bring it to the attention of local districts,'' he said.
   East Baton Rouge Parish School Superintendent Bernard Weiss, a
former English teacher, said he had ``serious concerns about having
the background to make such an assertion about a child.''
   ``I certainly don't feel an English teacher is basically
qualified to make that kind of determination,'' he said.
   Keith Cruz, director of student assessments in Texas, said some
papers flagged by the company have been used in court in child
abuse cases.
   ``It's our idea to have the flagging done,'' Cruz said. ``It's
made us very proud to provide the school districts with help for
youngsters.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
