<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-17 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capitalism Thrives in Marxist-ruled Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Official media were silent when Moslem
guerrillas kept a column of gasoline trucks from reaching Kabul
recently, but the currency traders knew about it and moved the
dollar up against the afghani.
   Word came two days later that the army had reopened the road and
the convoy had safely completed the 260-mile journey from the
Soviet border. The sober-faced men on the bank of the Kabul River
moved the dollar down again.
   Capitalism flourishes in Kabul, which was a crossroads for
merchants and traders many centuries before it became a Marxist
capital 11 years ago.
   The money market, or serai shazad, is conducted in the inner
courtyard of a balconied building with rusting beams, where camel
trains once sojourned overnight.
   Traders in turbans count bundles of notes _ blue, beige, pink _
pausing occasionally to tend their goats or other animals grazing
nearby. It is no secret that the men who dominate the serai shazad
are wealthy, some of them millionaires many times over.
   Civil war, which began with a communist coup in April 1978, has
created periodic and sometimes critical shortages of food, fuel and
medicine.
   For those with money, however, the dun-colored city is a
cornucopia.
   Merchants sell goods from wooden containers at roadsides in
western Kabul. Business is always brisk in rice, flour, wheat,
kerosene and other goods taken from supply convoys that do not make
it through guerrilla-held territory.
   The pocked streets and winding alleys of the old bazaar overflow
with everything from expensive 100-year-old carpets and Mercedes
automobiles to Japanese videocassette recorders, Soviet combat
uniforms and second-hand Western jeans.
   Highways running north to the Soviet border and east to Pakistan
are the city's lifeline and what moves on them sets the rhythm of
the market.
   Helicopter gunships, tanks, rockets and artillery are some of
the tools used to keep them open.
   Then come lulls in guerrilla activity, when convoys rumble into
Kabul without interference. Juma Mohammad, a 38-year-old money
changer, says some rebel commanders have their price.
   ``In's really quite simple,'' he said. ``There is a road.
Somebody controls the road. Somebody else wants to use the road and
deals are made. It's strictly business.''
   Information moves through the money bazaar's grapevine as if it
were an electronic data system, and the afghani rises or falls as
convoys reach Kabul or are attacked.
   Pounds, marks francs and nearly all other currencies are traded,
but the dollar is supreme.
   Dollars, sometimes tens of thousands, are stacked neatly in
chipped cabinets in the traders' tiny offices on the balconies
overlooking the ``trading floor,'' which is dusty or muddy
depending on the weather.
   As Mohammad discusses rates on the telephone, other traders
stand nearby, listening attentively.
   Money is not their only business.
   ``We are international businessmen, Mohammad said. ``We buy and
sell everythingg. I have bank accounts in London, Geneva and Paris
and I have traveled the world.''
   Like most of his colleagues, Mohammad is strictly neutral in
talking about the war.
   ``War is terrible, but this is business,'' he said. ``We will
accept any government that will end this war and leave business
alone.''
   Mohammad Sayeed, a colleague, observed: ``If we are left to live
in peace, then the success we have will be nothing special. We will
just be rich.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
