<FIRST>r i AM-China-Fast     05-17 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Fast,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Dozen Students Stop Drinking Water For Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen drama students have cast themselves in
the hero's role of China's student movement, vowing not to drink or
eat until the government agrees to discuss demands for a freer and
more democratic system.
   Their stage could not be better: a huge patch of Beijing's
biggest boulevard in front of the Great Hall of the People just off
Tiananmen Square, the symbolic political center of China.
   ``We are all artists,'' said Xiao Min, a 27-year-old set
designer at the Central Academy of Dramatic Arts. ``We had to take
this one step further.''
   More than 3,000 college students began a hunger strike for
democracy on Saturday. Xiao and his classmates, who already had
begun fasting, decided to stop drinking water Monday night.
   ``We were upset with the progress of things,'' Xiao said, as he
sat under a blanket on Changan Avenue. ``We decided we should be
ready to die.''
   From a high of 12, the number of people who are not drinking
water dwindled to five on Wednesday when seven were hospitalized.
   But several escaped from their hospital beds, ripping out the
intraveneous needles and rejoined their classmates. By midday, 10
students lay in the shade, sheltered by white sheets on bamboo
sticks.
   Xiao was one of them.
   ``My people are here and I had to be with them,'' he said,
clutching his left hand, swollen when he pulled a needle from his
vein. ``If we are going to fall, we will fall together.''
   Even more than the fasters, those students going without water
have touched a chord among Beijing residents _ of whom more than 1
million marched Wednesday to support calls for sweeping democratic
reforms.
   ``The government is killing them,'' said one high school teacher
as he demonstrated with his pupils near the fasting ground.
``Without water they will die. The government knows it must talk
with them.''
   On Wednesday, nurses and doctors hovered near the students.
   ``They all have fevers and we are worried about their hearts,''
said one doctor. He said nurses were dabbing their heads and lips
with wet cloths.
   As he spoke a siren cut the night and another student was taken
away. Seven remained, swathed in blankets.
   ``That was Xiao Ming. He is a veteran of our war with Vietnam.
That struggle didn't make him fall but this one has,'' Xiao said.
   Students lay under the portrait of a naked man and woman. A
poster reading, ``Save me,'' flapped in the wind.
   ``My child, you are burning up,'' cried one of their mothers as
temperatures soared into the low 80s.
   By late afternoon, the chrysanthemums and roses presented by
passers-by had wilted in the sun.
   ``They are still beautiful,'' Xiao said. ``I never thought my
people would raise their heads.''
</TEXT>
