<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WarDebt Bjt   05-17 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-War Debt, Bjt,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retirement Home Repays War Debt After 50 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A half century ago Irene Opdyke spied on the
Nazis in Poland, then turned her boss' villa into a refuge for her
Jewish friends.
   Last month a group of Jews provided a refuge for Mrs. Opdyke's
83-year-old husband, William, who has Alzheimer's disease.
   Victory Village, a retirement community run by the Jewish Homes
for the Aging of Greater Los Angeles, calls it repayment of a war
debt. Mrs. Opdyke, 68, calls it a miracle.
   ``We violated all the rules. He's not from our region. We are
sectarian. We are so short of beds. But there are certain times
when there are no rules. This is one of those times,'' said Sheldon
Blumenthal, executive director at Victory Village.
   Mrs. Opdyke, raised a Catholic, said, ``Jewish people are my
friends, my family.''
   She recounted in broken English the aftermath of the 1939 German
invasion of her native Poland, when the Nazis seized Jewish
property and subjected Jews to forced labor and extermination camps.
   ``They were working as slaves in an ammunition factory. I was
there serving breakfast, luncheon and dinner to the German officers
and secretaries. We knew each other. We tried to create like a spy
organization,'' she siad.
   ``I listened with my eyes and ears, carry to the laundry room,
was spread all around. And it was working for quite a few months.
But then when we find out that's it, it will be end. They asked me
for help.''
   Remarkably, she was able to hide 12 people for eight months,
first in the basement and attic of a villa occupied by a German
major, and then in a tunnel below.
   ``I didn't have a home, family, just a tiny little room by the
diner. I could not take them there,'' she said. ``I prayed. I
prayed like I never prayed before. Not from Bible, from my heart.
And you know, couple days later, the major called me and said, `I
have villa. You be my housekeeper.'
   ``It was miracle. So I open window, one by one they came, they
were there. Then I realize we need a better hiding place because I
didn't know the major want to have parties and everything,'' she
said.
   She said one couple pointed out that the villa had belonged to a
Jew and might contain a hiding place. ``We search and we find it,''
she said.
   Mrs. Opdyke came to the United States in 1949. She married
William Opdyke, a Naval officer, 31 years ago. From time to time,
Mrs. Opdyke, an interior decorator, was called on by the Jewish
Federation to speak to young people about her role in the war.
   Then her husband got ill. Dementia changed his personality. His
memory came and went. He would shake, throw things, scream, yell,
forget and accuse others of imagining things. He stopped eating. He
started slurring his words.
   When she took him to a hospital, ``they said he was not sick
enough.'' She appealed to her insurance company but ``when you
needed help, forget it. It was bad,'' she said.
   She had known Esther L. Brenner, regional coordinator of the
U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum since 1986. After losing her
interior decorating business, Mrs. Opdyke depended more and more on
the stipends she received for speaking engagements.
   ``I called Esther and cried my heart out. She said, `I'll see
what I can do,''' Mrs. Opdyke said.
   Ms. Brenner contacted Victory Village, which admitted her
husband to its Alzheimer's unit on April 25.
   Unable to do much for her husband but visit, she said her zeal
is in her work.
   ``I can survive the trauma because I have so much to do. I am
traveling and speaking to thousands of children. ... I talk to them
about Holocaust,'' she said.
   ``I tell them to try and understand we all belong to one human
family and only one way to defeat the ignorance of prejudice is to
reach out _ reach out without nationality, religion, creed or
color.''
</TEXT>
