<DOCNO> AP890517-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Stark     05-17 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stark,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Ceremonies Mark 2nd Anniversary of USS Stark Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former crewman of the USS Stark cast a
wreath into the water Wednesday to mark the second anniversary of
the Iraqi attack that killed 37 Americans and altered U.S. policy
in the Persian Gulf.
   The Pentagon, meanwhile, disclosed that $27.3 million in
compensation for the dead has been paid by Iraq and distributed to
their families. Millions in additional claims for the wounded and
damage to the ship remain to be settled.
   The Stark, a 3,600-ton missile frigate, was nearly sunk on May
17, 1987, by two French-made Exocet missiles fired by an Iraqi
warplane, while the ship was conducting what U.S. officials called
routine duty in the central gulf.
   The attack killed 37 of its crew of 220 and injured 21. Iraq
later apologized, saying the pilot of the F-1 Mirage had mistaken
the U.S. frigate for an Iranian ship.
   The incident spurred the United States to expand its forces in
the gulf to protect U.S.-flagged shipping from the ``tanker war,''
a spinoff of the Iraq-Iran war. It also led to a revised policy
that U.S. commanders should not hesitate to fire first if they
believed an attack was immiment.
   With the waterway quiet since Iraq and Iran agreed to a
cease-fire Aug. 20, the United States has cut its regional force
from 40 ships to 19, but continues to ``maintain a presence, show
the flag and monitor U.S.-flagged shipping,'' a Navy spokesman said.
   The 10-ship gulf patrol unit would be trimmed further if the
Pentagon approves a plan to remove the last three mine sweepers
dispatched in 1987, U.S. sources said.
   The memorial service was performed aboard the USS Curts, now on
duty in the northern gulf, according to Navy witnesses.
   Sonar Technician 3rd Class Philip Matagavage, 22, of Hellertown,
Pa., a Stark crewman at the time of the attack, tossed the wreath
over the side on the final note of the Navy hymn, ``Eternal
Father.'' A 21-gun salute echoed across the calm waters and a
crewman played taps on a trombone.
   Cmdr. David J. Alexander, of New London, Conn., skipper of the
Curts, told his sailors who had assembled on deck in dress whites
that the Stark was saved by its crew in a 24-hour battle against
flames fed by missile fuel.
   ``They simply would not let their shipmates fail each other or
their ship,'' Alexander said.
   At a local school, U.S. Ambassador Sam H. Zakhem and Rear Adm.
William M. Fogarty, commander of the U.S. Joint Task Force Middle
East, also praised the Stark crew's courage and sacrifice.
   ``For a grateful nation tha since birth has paid the price, we
say to the men of Stark, `Thank you,''' said Fogarty.
   The Navy also circulated to all ships a suggested prayer on
behalf of ``our comrades who have lost their lives in defense of
freedom in the gulf these past years.''
   The death toll of 53 since 1987 includes the Stark victims, 14
killed in air crashes and two in a carrier deck fire.
   Iraq has paid $27.3 million in compensation for the dead aboard
the Stark and the checks were distributed to the families April 28,
according to Marine Maj. Robin Higgins, a Pentagon spokeswoman.
   Baghdad had agreed to the restitution in March after months of
prodding by the United States. It came to about 92 percent of the
original U.S. demand.
   Still to be submitted by the United States are separate claims
for the 21 injured and an $82.9 million bill for damage to the
ship. The rebuilt Stark returned to sea duty last year.
   Zakhem said Mrs. Barbara Kiser, a Stark widow, flew to Baghdad
to donate a $10,000 check out of her settlement to an Iraqi war
orphans home.
   A Pentagon inquiry following the Stark incident found that its
commander had failed to defend his ship adequately in dangerous, if
ambiguous, circumstances. He and and another officer were allowed
to resign from the Navy rather than face court-martial.
   The revised policy allowing commanders to shoot first if under
apparent threat was cited by U.S. officials after the cruiser USS
Vincennes mistakenly shot down an Iranian jetliner July 3. All 290
aboard the plane were killed.
</TEXT>
