<FIRST>r w AM-VictimsMemorial     05-17 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Victims Memorial,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Proposes Memorial to Crime Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nonprofit group based in suburban Virginia
said Wednesday it was launching an effort to organize support for a
Washington memorial dedicated to the victims of crime.
   ``Many victims and families of victims for years have expressed
a need for a public place that remembers victims who are killed and
marks the grief and suffering of survivors and loved ones,'' said
John Wheeler, president of the Center for the Vietnam Generation,
based in McLean, Va.
   He added that ``a beautiful, landscaped memorial for victims of
crime could prove to be a turning point in healing the dreadful
national situation of violence, disrespect, drug and alcohol abuse
and diminished sense of community.''
   Wheeler told a news conference that he would like to see a
memorial built on privately owned land near Pennsylvania Avenue
between the White House and the Capitol.
   Locating the memorial on privately owned property rather than on
the Mall or other public land, he said, ``avoids the difficulties
of having to go to Congress and to the several government approval
agancies.''
   Money for the project, expected to cost $10 million to $20
million, would come from philanthropists, real estate developers
and individual donors, Wheeler said.
   He said that over the next six months, he was aiming to organize
a coalition of organizations and individuals to support the
proposal. Groups that have already agreed to join the effort,
Wheeler said, include the Washington-based National Organization
for Victim Assistance and the National Victim Center of Fort Worth,
Texas.
   The Center for the Vietnam Generation describes itself as a
nonprofit group ``fostering knowledge about the 60 million
Americans who came of age in the Vietnam era'' and advocating
public service.
</TEXT>
