<FIRST>r i AM-Havel     05-17 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Havel,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banned Czechoslovak Playwright Freed From Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banned playwright Vaclav Havel, a
symbol of dissent in this communist country, was paroled for good
behavior Wednesday midway through an eight-month jail sentence.
   Jiri Wolf, a leader of the Charter 77 human rights movement who
spent six years in prison for subversion, also was freed Wednesday.
Unlike Havel, Wolf was not granted parole and served his full term.
   Havel's arrest during demonstrations in January caused protest
in the West and among Hungarian, Polish and Soviet intellectuals.
It marked the beginning of a crackdown on dissent that conflicted
with reforms under way elsewhere in the Soviet bloc.
   Hours after being freed, Havel was speaking out for political
reform and urging those who campaigned for his release not to
forget about other political prisoners.
   He and his brother, Ivan, said the release was a victory for
thousands of Czechoslovaks who signed petitions protesting Havel's
arrest and supporting his request for parole.
   At least 20 people have been jailed, fined or given suspended
sentences since the January protests.
   Havel said Czechoslovak leaders have adopted the language of
reform, but have yet to emulate what he described as the
astonishing change occurring in Hungary, Poland and Moscow.
   ``Changes of the facade, not of the structure,'' have taken
place in Czechoslovakia, Havel told a Czech reporter who shared the
comments with other journalists.
   A step toward genuine change, Havel said, would be the
retirement of Communist Party chief Milos Jakes and other leaders
who presided over the death of reform after the 1968 Soviet
invasion ended the liberal ``Prague Spring.''
   Jakes welcomed President Nicolae Ceausescu of Romania, who runs
the most repressive regime in the Soviet bloc, for a one-day visit
Wednesday. A statement issued after their talks stressed the right
of each Communist Party to pursue its own policies.
   Ivan Havel and other dissidents speculated the decision to
release his brother was intended to deflect Western criticism of
Czechoslovakia's record at a 35-nation human rights conference that
begins May 30 in Paris.
   He said he believed domestic support for the playwright put
pressure on the regime, noting that a petition signed by 3,000
people backing the request for parole was ``not done by dissidents,
but by the broader public.''
   Havel was sentenced Feb. 22 to nine months on charges of
incitement and obstructing a police officer. An appeals court
reduced the sentence in March to eight months, dropping the
obstruction charge.
   Police arrested Havel on Jan. 16 at an unofficial memorial
ceremony in Prague's Wenceslas Square for Jan Palach, a student who
burned himself alive in January 1969 to protest the crushing of
reforms.
   On Wednesday, the playwright said he was reminded of his growing
status as a national figure by the privileged treatment he received
in prison.
   Conditions were much better than during a 4{-year jail term to
which he was sentenced in 1979 on subversion charges, Havel said.
   ``The prison staff expressed so much sympathy with me that I was
embarrassed because of the bitter thought: What about the others?''
he said.
   Havel said he wrote very little in jail because he was not sure
he could get the material out. His works are performed in the West
and in Poland, but are banned in Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
