<FIRST>r w AM-CommoditiesProbe     05-17 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Officials Says New Regulations Not Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the four largest commodity
futures exchanges told the Senate Wednesday they were opposed to
any additional legislation regulating their industry.
   ``We recognize that, in recent months, some have questioned our
integrity and expressed doubt about our ability to police our
markets,'' said Karsten Mahlmann, chairman of the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   But he said that the existence of the exchange ``depends on our
integrity.'' He outlined for the Senate Agriculture Committee the
surveillance procedures the exchange uses to detect trading
improprieties.
   Mahlmann's opinion was shared by Leo Melamed, chairman of the
Chicago Mercentile Exchange; Z. Lou Guttman, chairman of the New
York Mercantile Exchange, and Robert Fink, first vice president of
the Commodity Exchange Inc.
   They also explained how they monitor traders to protect against
misdeeds and the penalities imposed when wrongdoers are discovered.
   Sen. Robert Kerrey, D-Neb., however, challenged their diligence,
saying he thought violations in student loans and among farm
borrowers were being pursued more vigorously than in commodity
futures trading.
   He cited Justice Department figures showing that $12 million in
fines for trading violations had not been collected.
   ``I think the message going out to crooks and swindlers is `the
odds are in your favor','' said Kerrey.
   He said he wanted figures from the industry executives on the
exact amounts collected in fines, which all four said they would
supply later.
   Their appearances were part of Congress' inquiry into
commodities trading before reauthorizing the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission, the federal agency charged with overseeing such
markets.
   After it was revealed earlier this year that the FBI had been
conducting an undercover investigation of alleged fraud on the
Chicago exchanges, Congress has been considering strengthening the
powers of the CFTC.
   At a previous hearing before the Agriculture Committee, the
General Accounting Office questioned the intensity of exchange and
CFTC efforts to detect and punish trading abuses.
   At another earlier session, the CFTC issued reports that were
critical of some of the exchanges' internal enforcement programs.
   In gathering information about the futures industry, the
committee has expressed concern about statistics showing that the
Board of Trade has levied significantly fewer sanctions against
violators than the other exchanges in relation to their size.
   Mahlmann said the figures the committee had received from the
CFTC were wrong. He said that the Board of Trade had levied $1.45
million in fines in 1988, not the $287,000 shown by the CFTC.
   When Leahy asked him how the discrepancy could exist, Mahlmann
said the lower figure resulted from ``a very narrow
interpretation'' of what a violation was.
</TEXT>
