<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Books     05-17 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Books,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underground Publishers a Hit at International Book Fair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After surviving years of harassment by
authorities, Poland's top underground publishers exhibited hundreds
of uncensored books for the first time Wednesday at an official
international book fair.
   ``Times have really changed,'' said Jan Kofman, an editor of the
poltical quarterly Krytyka, as he answered questions from people
who crowded around the display.
   ``Next year we are going to have our books shown right in the
center (of the show),'' said Grzegorz Boguta, the head of NOWA, the
Independent Publishing House, the country's premier clandestine
publisher.
   NOWA and other independent publishing houses such as Krag, CDN
and Przedswit were tucked away at the end of a corridor off the
main hall of the cavernous Palace of Culture, a skyscraper built by
the Soviet Union for Poland that dominates downtown Warsaw.
   ``The main question people ask is where they can buy the
books,'' Kofman said. At one point, Rudi Jankovic, director of
Quadra Enterprises Ltd, a private British book distributor, walked
up and offered to buy and market Nowa's entire underground display.
   ``This is real publishing, aggressive and creative,'' Jankovic
said.
   Boguta said the exhibits represent the first step to operating
as a normal publishing house, but that there is still a long way to
go.
   ``There is now a very optimistic political situation for
underground publishing houses. We want to be official because we
want to publish more, better quality books than today, but
uncensored,'' he said.
   Toleration of underground publishers, known in Poland as ``the
second circulation,'' has been growing in the last year _
especially after the start of formal talks between the opposition
and authorities in February.
   Among NOWA's more than 400 titles published in the last 12 years
are books by such authors as Nobel Prize winners Alexander
Solzhenitsyn and Andrei Sakharov, philosophers Hannah Arendt and
Jean-Paul Sartre, and American writers Kurt Vonnegut Jr. and Philip
Roth.
   NOWA was also one of the main outlets for Polish opposition
activists such as essayist Adam Michnik, political theorist Jacek
Kuron and labor leader Zbigniew Bujak.
   But why should underground publishers surface at all?
   ``We couldn't stay hidden. We can publish only a few thousands
copies of books in very poor technical conditions. Now censorship
is very liberal,'' Boguta said. ``Now we have a chance to be
official, but we must be quite independent.''
   Boguta, who also heads the group Association for Free Speech,
would like to create a nationwide network of independent book clubs
and start a company with foreign investors to publish uncensored
books.
   On a lower level of the Palace of Culture, the emigre press also
was allowed for the first time to exhibit Polish-language books
printed abroad, including works long banned.
   A crowd peered at editions published by the Paris-based Kultura
that has published many of Poland's finest authors and preserved
them from oblivion.
   Not all authors must rely on the independent press to get books
published.
   The official Czytelnik publisher announced a Polish edition of
``Mercy and Gallows,'' a social history on charity from the Middle
Ages to the present by Bronislaw Geremek, a historian and adviser
to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa.
   Czytelnik also has published ``The Painted Bird'' by Jerzy
Kosinski, an emigrant to the United States long vilified in his
homeland but recently restored to official good graces.
   The Catholic publishing house Znak took orders for its books
that include the Polish version of Walesa's autobiography, ``A Way
of Hope.''
   More than 20 countries are represented at the fair. All of the
East bloc countries except Romania have displays and there are
publishers from West Germany, France, Great Britain, Italy and the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
