<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-RochesterSchools     05-17 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Rochester Schools,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Visit Draws Attention To Rochester School Innovations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School officials are hoping a visit
Thursday by President Bush will help boost confidence in an
innovative new setup that offers teachers big pay raises for more
work and more responsibility.
   Critics of the plan adopted two years ago say it has not paid
off in better education.
   ``We sure could use the president's power of persuasion that
there's no alternative but to improve public education,'' said Adam
Urbanski, president of the teachers union.
   Urbanski helped formulate a three-year teacher contract to boost
salaries and make teachers more accountable for what goes on in the
classroom. Education reformers pointed to the program adopted by
the district as a model for the nation.
   Bush is expected to visit Wilson Magnet High School, an
inner-city showcase for the changes going on in the district. He
also is scheduled to give a speech about education at an Eastman
Kodak Co. plant in the suburb of Gates.
   The visit comes as officials feel increasing pressure to show
that education has improved since teachers were given the chance to
earn $60,000 to $70,000 a year in exchange for more work and
responsibility for the curriculum and spending.
   ``We understand that the public wants to see some kind of
result,'' said Benjamin Douglas, school board president. ``I hope
they realize that President Bush's visit is recognition that we're
further down the road of reform than most places.''
   Last week, school officials asked the city to increase school
taxes 10.2 percent to help continue the program, and critics became
more outspoken.
   ``Over a two-year period they've asked for almost a 20 percent
increase,'' said Gordon Johnson, executive director of the
Rochester-based Citizens Tax League. ``Any time any unit of
government keeps galloping along at 10 percent while inflation is
running at 2 and 3 percent, it's too much.''
   Advocates of the setup, like William Johnson, president of the
city's Urban League, also are starting to express concerns. ``I'm
still optimistic, but I think we should be able to see some
instant, short-term improvement that can be measured,'' he said.
</TEXT>
