<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1522EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Gorbachev     05-17 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Gorbachev,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aspin Says Bush Administration Has No Vision to Challenge Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is losing a global public
relations war against Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev by
making lackluster arms control proposals and offering ``no vision''
of a better world, the House Armed Services Committee chairman
charged Wednesday.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., in a hearing before his panel, also
chastised the White House for making belittling statements about
the Soviet leader instead of moving to counter his plethora of arms
control proposals with imaginative responses.
   ``Not only is this administration not very good on substance _
they're not very good on p.r. (public relations),'' Aspin said.
   Aspin charged that the administration has chosen a cautious and
reactive ``stand pat'' approach to Gorbachev, rather than
attempting to challenge the Soviet leader with ambitious proposals.
Aspin particularly complained the administration's proposals to cut
conventional forces in Europe were ``unambitious.''
   ``It's not just a p.r. problem _ it's a substantive problem. If
we want to score, we've got to come up with some creative,
seize-the-opportunity initiatives,'' Aspin said. ``You guys need a
proposal _ and frankly `Open Skies' doesn't make it.''
   Last week, Bush called for a revival of the 1950s ``Open Skies''
proposal by President Eisenhower that would have allowed the
Soviets and United States to fly unarmed inspection aircraft over
the other's territory. The 30-year-old proposal was never
implemented.
   Other House Democrats told Paul Wolfowitz, undersecretary of
defense for policy, and Reginald Bartholomew, undersecretary of
state for security assistance, that the administration has not done
enough to battle Gorbachev's initiatives, particularly in light of
the heated argument within the NATO alliance over modernizing the
pact's short-range nuclear weapons.
   The issue is expected to prove devisive at Bush's first NATO
summit later this month.
   The United States and Britain want to move forward with the
modernization of the Lance missile force, but West Germany and
several smaller nations oppose it. The West Germans have also
called for U.S.-Soviet negotiations on reducing or eliminating the
weapons, but the United States objects, contending the weapons are
needed to deter any attack from the larger Soviet bloc ground and
tank forces.
   Wolfowitz and Bartholomew argued that many of Gorbachev's
initiatives, such as his most recent offering to get rid of 500
short-range nuclear weapons, were designed to glean publicity and
were not actually substantial when viewed against the overwhelming
superiority in Warsaw Pact forces.
   And, they argued, Gorbachev is actually getting mileage by
moving closer to positions the United States has long advocated
   ``It's not a pure picture of progress,'' Wolfowitz said.
``Instead of `new thinking,' we're still seeing a lot of old
thinking,'' he added, noting that the Soviets still retain the
largest armed force structure in the world.
   ``We have to keep our eyes on the warts as well as the more
positive steps that have been taken,'' Bartholomew said.
   Wolfowitz and Bartholomew said that the administration was being
cautious in areas where they deemed it was necessary, and had put
forward a serious and far-reaching proposals to trim the
conventional forces in Europe, which the Soviets are now just
coming around to meet.
   But Aspin argued that even though the administration's position
might find agreement among diplomats and the military, it wasn't
winning in the political arena.
   ``You can't beat something with nothing in politics,'' he said.
``There's no vision there. ... You have to give me a better world I
can point to. ... You've got to have some vision out there _ and it
just ain't there.''
   Aspin also criticized statements made Tuesday by White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, who said the administration of
``leery'' of Gorbachev's promise to halt military aid to Nicaragua.
Fitzwater also accused Gorbachev of throwing out arms control
proposals like a ``drugstore cowboy'' in the effort to win
attention.
   ``I don't think you ought to run down the Gorbachev proposals. I
don't think the kind of statements Marlin Fitzwater is making are
helpful,'' Aspin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
