<FIRST>u i AM-China-Notebook     05-17 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Notebook,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Stuff of Democracy: Balloons &amp; Firecrackers, Popsicles &amp; Noodles</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She might not have hit all the notes, but Fan
Lili sang China's national anthem with gusto.
   As she strolled down Changan Avenue with more than 1 million
other protesters, the young entrepreneur was just one
representative of the many segments of society in Wednesday's march.
   Striking taxi drivers honked their horns and hung flags out
their windows. Police officers wrote ``We support you,'' on their
hands and then continued directing traffic.
   Soldiers and steel workers also protested.
   Not to be outdone, a group of men proudly marched beneath a
banner reading, ``unemployed youth.''
   ``Everybody has a voice,'' Fan said. ``It's time we start using
it.''
  
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sacrilege abounded.
   A fat balloon with ``Demands'' written on it floated on top of
the Monument to the Revolutionary Martyrs, a giant obelisk in the
middle of Tiananmen Square.
   Posters for freedom dangled from the Museum of Revolutionary
History. Firecrackers popped under the portrait of Chairman Mao
Tse-tung at the entrance to the Forbidden City.
   Drama students occupied the front of the Great Hall of the
People and went on a no-water strike.
   ``I think everything is more beautiful this way,'' said art
student Wang Kegang. ``Banners and balloons are nice things.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Throughout the day, hundreds of relatives of the fasters flocked
to the square to get them to leave.
   ``Our family is not like other families,'' said one woman to her
younger brother. ``Mama has put all the hope in her life on you. If
you die, everything will be over for her.''
   ``The government isn't going to listen to you. Use a more normal
way of protest,'' she said.
   Her brother nodded.
   Thousands of workers passed before him.
   ``Support the students!'' they yelled.
   ``Big sister,'' he said, ``I took an oath.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   For democrats, Jiang Guoli and his cronies have a long way to go.
   Jiang and the boys _ some of the hundreds of students assigned
to keep order on Tiananmen Square _ rule their roost with an iron
first.
   ``Beat it!'' Jiang said to a reporter, slapping him on the knees
with a bamboo rod.
   ``Keep to the side. Hurry up!'' said a colleague, shoving a
nurse into line.
   Organized to prevent plainclothes policeman from infiltrating
their demonstration, the groups have taken on new airs since their
first goal was achieved.
   ``Don't cross that line,'' Jiang said as one man prepared to
leave the square. ``You must cross over here.''
   ``Why?'' the man asked.
   ``It's a matter of principle.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   What do you eat at a demonstration?
   For 5{-year-old Meng Yuanyuan, it was easy: popsicles and lots
of them.
   Others munched on bread, which was selling briskly up and down
Changan Avenue.
   Still more said they felt a bit out of place, eating while their
classmates were on a hunger strike to change China.
   But not Wu Gang, the drummer in the Agricultural College's
marching band.
   ``It's got to be noodles,'' said Wu, slurping a bowl. ``I've
beem pounding the drum all day and I'm starving.''
</TEXT>
