<DOCNO> AP890517-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Trade Bjt   05-17 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade, Bjt,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record Export Sales Send Deficit Shooting Downward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit, bolstered by record
export sales, shrank dramatically to $8.86 billion in March, the
government said Wednesday in a report that prompted some economists
to question their earlier assessment that the country's trade
improvement had stalled out.
   The Commerce Department said the March deficit was down 9.8
percent from the February imbalance of $9.82 billion, a figure that
was itself lowered from an initial report a month ago, which had
put the February deficit at $10.5 billion.
   The March improvement came from a 7.4 percent rise in exports,
which hit a record $30.78 billion. Imports rose 3 percent to $39.64
billion, pushed upward by rising oil prices.
   Analysts, who had been looking for little or no improvement in
the March figure, noted that sales of American manufactured goods
and farm products were up sharply, helping to lower the deficit
with all major U.S. trading partners.
   The deficit with Canada, the country's largest trading partner,
declined to $248 million, its lowest in almost eight years. The
United States ran a rare trade surplus of $397 million with Western
Europe, the best showing in six years.
   The trade report was hailed as good news by the Bush
administration, which is counting on continued strength in American
exports to propel domestic growth this year.
   ``These numbers support our contention that a favorable movement
in our exports and imports is underway,'' said Commerce Secretary
Robert Mosbacher. He noted that the average overall monthly deficit
from January through March was 10 percent lower than the average
from October through Decmeber.
   Prviate economists have been worried that the dollar's strength
over the last year could jeopardize further trade improvements by
making American goods more expensive overseas.
   After reviewing the March figures, however, some analysts said
they were revising their trade projections for 1989 based on a
belief that strong economic growth overseas was fueling demand for
American products and would offset the adverse effects from the
dollar's increase.
   ``U.S. trade is off the sticky track and has moved to a
permanently improved position,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist
of the Boston Co. ``Healthy economies overseas contributed to an
explosion of exports in March.''
   Last year, the trade deficit shrank by $32 billion to $119.76
billion, down from an all-time high of $152.12 billion in 1987.
   Sinai said he was looking for the 1989 improvement to be around
$16 billion, putting the deficit at $103 billion. For the first
three months of this year, the deficit was running at an annual
rate of $109.4 billion.
   ``The performance in the first quarter suggests that demand
abroad is vigorous and American firms are competitive enough to
take advantage of it,'' said Robert Dederick, chief economist of
Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
   But some economists remained unconvinced that the trade deficit
would show much improvement this year, based on a belief that
rising oil prices and continued strong demand for imports would
offset any further gains in export sales.
   ``There is not a chance that this trend toward lower trade
deficits will continue,'' said Michael Evans, head of a Washington
forecasting firm. ``I expect to see $10 billion to $11 billion
monthly trade deficits for the rest of the year.''
   The Bush administration has a lot riding on the country's trade
performance because it needs robust economic growth to bring in
enough revenues to lower the federal budget deficit without raising
taxes. Last year's trade improvement was responsible for almost
half of total growth in the economy.
   The March trade improvement came despite the fact that the bill
for foreign oil climbed to $3.69 billion, the highest total in 16
months. The increase resulted from the fourth consecutive monthly
increase in the average price per barrel, which rose to $15.97. The
average price had been $12.42 in November.
   U.S. exports posted across-the-board increases in most
categories. Sales of manufactured capital goods climbed to $10.05
billion, up 8.4 percent from February, while sales of agricultural
products shot up 20.7 percent to $3.36 billion.
   As usual, the biggest deficit was recorded with Japan, a $4.2
billion imbalance, down from a $4.7 billion gap in February. Other
large deficits were recorded with Taiwan, $790 million; South
Korea, $427 million, and Brazil, $341 million.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills must decide by the end of
this month which countries the administration will target for
possible retaliation unless they agree to lower barriers keeping
American goods out. Japan, South Korea and Taiwan are the leading
candidates for inclusion on that list.
</TEXT>
