<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Soviet     05-17 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Soviet,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Treated to Gorbachev at Great Wall</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet TV viewers were treated Wednesday to
pictures of their president strolling along the Great Wall of China
and joking with young people about Chinese cooking.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's visit to China dominated the state-run
media, taking up all 45 minutes of the evening TV news program
``Vremya'' and most of the first two pages of the government
newspaper Izvestia.
   The coverage continued reports by the official media about the
trip that were unusally lengthy and detailed.
   State-run TV showed Gorbachev's speech to Chinese intellectuals
before its evening news program, and his news conference in Beijing
after the news was over, giving viewers several hours of virtually
uninterrupted coverage of Gorbachev's visit.
   Many of the images of Gorbachev at the Great Wall showed him
talking to young people. Students are at the heart of a protests
that coincide with Gorbachev's visit that have turned into the
largest display of defiance of authorities in 40 years of communist
power.
   Official Soviet TV did not show pictures of demonstrators on
Beijing's Tiananmen Square as it did on Monday night.
   In the TV report, Gorbachev said repeatedly he was impressed by
the desire of Chinese youth for better relations with the Soviet
Union.
   The Soviet leader has been careful in his public statements not
to get into the middle of the dispute between student-led
protesters and the Chinese government that has forced several
changes in his schedule.
   ``This has been preserved not only among the old, but the young
as well. This is very important,'' Gorbachev told a Soviet TV
interview. ``This is my strongest impression.''
   At one point, talking with Chinese young people at the Great
Wall, Gorbachev reached out to hug a young woman. At another point,
talking about Chinese food, he said: ``It is said Chinese cooking
is some of the best in the world. Now I can confirm that.''
   Gorbachev said he hoped Chinese students would once again come
to Moscow to study, as they had done before the rift between the
communist giants that he is trying to mend with his visit.
   Izvestia said Gorbachev's meeting with senior Chinese leader
Deng Xiaoping was an historic occasion.
   ``From this day a new stage of Soviet-Chinese relations is
beginning,'' Izvestia's evening edition said in its lead article.
   ``There was practically full agreement in this historic
conversation in relation to new political thinking and new
international political order,'' Izvestia said.
   Asked by the TV interviewer if he thought the Soviet Union and
China would begin to compete instead of cooperate in economic
relations, Gorbachev said he saw great promise for cooperation with
China in energy, transportation, light industry and other economic
spheres.
   The news broadcast also carried Gorbachev's interview with
Chinese TV, and reports on the activities of his wife, Raisa, and
of Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
</TEXT>
