<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1821EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Poland     05-17 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Official Sees No Objecton to German Reunification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a sign of the changing mood in Europe, a
top Polish official said Wednesday his government would not object
to the reunification of Germany as long as Poland's borders were
guaranteed.
   ``We feel that European security systems can change, whereas the
basis for security arangements being based on respect for integrity
is unchangeable,'' said Jozef Czyrek, the No. 2 official in the
Polish Communist Party.
   Czyrek also said in an interview with The Asociated Press that
two Soviet regiments were being withdrawn from Poland and that he
envisions a day when all of Moscow's troops leave.
   He also expressed hope that President Bush, scheduled to visit
Poland this July, would issue a reciprocal invitation to Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski, who declared martial law in 1981 but is now
guiding his nation toward democratic elections in June. Czyrek met
with Bush at the White House Monday.
   Jaruzelski is expected to remain Poland's president after the
elections and Czyrek has been mentioned widely as Jaruzelski's
successor as first secretary of the Polish United Workers', or
Communist, Party.
   The changes in the Soviet Union and tentative steps that Poland
and Hungary have taken toward democracy have prompted speculation
that the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact and the North Atlantic Treaty
Alliance could play a diminished security role in Europe, and that
East and West Germany, divided during the Cold War, might
ultimately reunite.
   The German invasion of Poland 50 years ago triggered World War
II. Since the war, Poland has expressed reservations about the
reunification of East and West Germany.
   Czyrek, by contrast, expressed cautious acceptance of eventual
German reunification.
   ``All the processes which would include that security, Poland
would support. At this point in time, Poland has good relations
with the GDR (German Democratic Republic or East Germany) and tries
to improve its relations with Western Germany,'' said Czyrek.
   ``At this point in time, European security is based on
territorial integrity, a respect for territorial integrity and the
shape of Europe as a result of the Second World War, and
developments after the Second World War,'' he said.
   A Polish government aide later said that Czyrek's formulation
marked a change in the official stance.
   ``Our position used to be'' in non-diplomatic terms, ``that we
liked Germany so much that we wanted to see two of them,'' said the
Polish government source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The United States views possible reunification as an issue to be
decided by the German people, although U.S. officials say they
worry what would happen if West Germany left NATO.
   Asked whether Poland would view a unified Germany as a threat,
Czyrek said:
   ``A nation that does not take its historical experience into
consideration puts itself in danger. That applies to Poland also.
We do not forget our experiences. Obviously, it has an influence in
shaping our attitude towards Germany. We are not closing our eyes
to the future.''
   Czyrek also said that within the last few days, Polish and
Soviet officials had agreed that two regiments of Soviet troops
would be withdrawn from Poland.
   The Soviet Union maintains 40,000 soldiers in Poland, according
to the Institute for International and Strategic Studies in London.
Most of those are logistical support troops for the estimated
380,000 Soviet soldiers in East Germany, said Czyrek, but he was
unable to say precisely how many Soviet troops were being pulled
out.
   Czyrek, asked whether he foresaw the day that all Soviet troops
would go home, replied:
   ``Surely I do. Is that so difficult to imagine?''
   David Isby, an expert on the Soviet military, said the average
Soviet tank regiment has 95 to 100 tanks and 1,575 people.
</TEXT>
