<FIRST>r w AM-DiplomaticNominees     05-17 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diplomatic Nominees,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Quickly Embroiled in Squabble over Nominations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE KNUTSON ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An undiplomatic wrangle over three of President
Bush's diplomatic nominees broke out in the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee on Wednesday.
   When it ended, the prospects were that two appointees would face
lengthy delays and perhaps prolonged Senate debate.
   And one had received the verbal equivalent of having his mouth
washed out with soap.
   The three nominations that caused the problems: Richard R. Burt,
to be the new U.S. strategic arms negotiator; Donald Gregg, to be
ambassador to South Korea; and Reter V. Secchia, to be ambassador
to Italy.
   The situation:
   _Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., accuses Burt of leaking classified
information to a female journalist with whom Burt says he once had
a ``social relationship.'' Helms vows to delay action on the Senate
floor pending a State Department investigation. Sen. Joseph R.
Biden, D-Del., defended Burt saying he ``broke no law.'' The
committee eventually endorsed the nomination _ 14-2.
   _Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., says he is prepared for lengthy
and investigative hearings into Gregg's alleged involvement in the
Iran-Contra affair unless President Bush withdraws the nomination
of the man who was his vice presidential national security adviser.
   _Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., says he fears that Secchia, a
former Michigan Republican national committeeman, will be ``an
embarrassment to the administration and the United States'' as
ambassador to Italy because of a ``penchant for making gross
remarks'' in public.
   But Pell, who said Italian friends were ``aghast'' at the
choice, said he would not block action. The committee sent the
nomination to the Senate, 11-0.
   Cranston _ who opposes Gregg and supports Burt _ and Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C. _ who opposes Burt and supports Gregg _ accused each
other, in effect, of holding's each other's candidate hostage.
   Helms said Cranston has launched ``a fishing expedition'' to
uncover adverse information against Gregg, a 30-year veteran of the
CIA.
   ``You swore him in as if he was some sort of culprit, which he
is not,'' Helms complained. ``You hope to be able to milk the
Iran-Contra cow again''
   Cranston said his concerns revolve around the nominee's
``credibility and judgment'' and whether or not he had misled the
Congress by denying any knowlege of the covert resupply of
Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   ``I have no intention of dragging out this matter at any great
length, but I think we do not yet have full information.'' Cranston
replied.
   ``As far as I'm concerned you didn't catch a thing,'' Helms
asserted.
   Cranston then spelled out a series of events that began with
Gregg's introduction of former intelligence operative Felix
Rodriguez in December 1984 to Oliver L. North, then a member of the
staff of the National Security Council. Cranston said the eveznts
and documentary evidence strongly indicate that Gregg may well
known that Rodriguez had been deeply involved in the illegal
resupply of the Contras.
   The possibility also is posed, Cranston said, that Gregg
deliberately misled the congressional Iran-Contra investigating
Committee when asked about his alleged involvement in the affair as
well as the Foreign Relations panel.
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., defended Gregg and declared: ``Don
Gregg did not want to slink off into the shadows and hide, he
wanted to be named to a position subject to confirmation so he
could put this thing to rest. If either he or the president had
anything to hide, the president would never have sent this
nomination up here.''
   Helms then counterattacked.
   ``If you hold this up, I've (also) got a nominee about which
information has come in,'' Helms said. ``He's the darling of your
side of the aisle _ Richard Burt.''
   Helms served notice he would delay the Burt nomination on the
Senate floor and appeared to link its fate to that of the Gregg
nomination.
   He repeated allegations that Burt had abused his security
clearance in various State Department positions and had published
classified information in his previous career as journalist.
   He said Burt's alleged actions violated federal law, ``which is
what this is, a crime,'' he said.
   Biden disagreed, saying Burt had ``broken no law.''
   Pell pressed for a committee vote, but that was delayed.
 
</TEXT>
