<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Smoking     05-17 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Smoking,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Seek Support for Anti-Tobacco Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressmen on Wednesday issued the formal
report of an anti-smoking conference as part of a bid for support
for a variety of anti-tobacco measures including a tax increase and
restrictions on cigarette advertising.
   ``While we are gaining on some fronts, we are losing the battle
with our children,'' said Rep. Michael A. Andrews, D-Texas, lead
organizer of the conference held in Texas. ``Each year, a million
young people start smoking.''
   Among the co-sponsors of the conference Jan. 27-28 in Houston
was the Coalition On Smoking Or Health _ comprised of the American
Cancer Society, the American Heart Association and the American
Lung Association _ and the American Medical Association.
   Scott Ballin, chairman of the coalition and vice president for
public affairs of the American Heart Association, said the
conference report ``strengthens the advocacy campaign of the
tobacco-control movement'' and also supports the legislative agenda
announced by the coalition at the start of the current Congress.
   Among the recommendations of the January conference:
   _The Food and Drug Administration should be given some authority
over all tobacco products. Under present law, the FDA does not
regulate tobacco use because it does not meet the legal definition
of food or drug.
   _Tobacco advertising must be restricted to eliminate its
influence on children.
   _Excise taxes on tobacco products should be increased.
   _The federal tobacco price support program should be eliminated.
   _Non-smokers should have legal protection from having to inhale
the smoke of others in airplanes, all public places and in the
workplace.
   _The federal government should stop encouraging the export of
U.S. tobacco to other countries.
   Ballin noted that the coalition has been working ``with key
members of Congress to put the conference's recommendations into
action'' since they were issued made in January.
   Among bills being pushed are two separate proposals to boost the
16-cent-per-pack cigarette tax _ one by 22 cents and one by 25
cents.
   Also pending are at least 13 other bills that would _ in one way
or another _ restrict the use, sale and advertising of tobacco.
</TEXT>
