<HEAD>Students Support University Lecturers' Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professors at state-run Makerere
University on strike for higher pay defied a government ultimatum
to return to work Wednesday or lose their jobs.
   Students gathered with professors to discuss the ultimatum,
issued Tuesday, and cheered the decision to stay away. No classes
were held.
   ``Education, in our opinion, is not possible under duress. It
requires, at minimum, freedom of speech and freedom from hunger,''
the professors said after the meeting.
   The professors want a salary increase from the present $35 a
month to $576 monthly. On Monday, they rejected a government call
for further negotiations and vowed to continue the strike until
their salary demands were met.
   The strike began May 2 but was suspended six days later for
talks with government negotiators. Professors voted to resume the
walkout Friday after the government failed to meet their demands.
