<FIRST>r w AM-Alar     05-17 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alar,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Vow Fast Action to Ban Apple Chemical Alar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four senators proposed Wednesday to ban use of
the chemical Alar on apples and other agricultural products and
said they expected fast floor action on their measure.
   ``The train is under way,'' Sen. John Warner, R-Va., told a news
conference called to unveil an Alar ban he said would benefit
producers as well as consumers. He indicated he would move to
bypass committee action and attach the bill as an amendment to
legislation ripe for quick floor action.
   The bill would reduce to zero the amount of the growth-enhancing
chemical that could be used on apples and other crops, primarily
grapes, cherries and peanuts. The ban would be effective as soon as
signed by the president.
   Alar, which enhances the appearance of apples and keeps them
fresh longer, has also been identified as a cancer-causing agent in
laboratory animals.
   Despite initial assessments from the Environmental Protection
Agency that Alar does not constitute a health risk for consumers,
apples sales have plunged since disclosures that the chemical,
manufactured by Uniroyal, is widely used.
   Apple producers are facing a $100 million loss ``on the raw
crop'' this year as a result of unfavorable reports about Alar and
there has been an additional 30 percent drop in apple juice sales,
according to Derl I. Derr, president of the International Apple
Institute, based in McLean, Va.
   Derr said his group, composed of 23 state organizations
representing an estimated 90 percent of the nation's 15,000
commercial growers, favors taking Alar off the market, but not by
legislative means. He said reducing the allowable amount to zero
would require an EPA finding that Alar poses an ``imminent hazard.''
   ``And if you think we have a bad market now, you should see what
it would be like then,'' Derr said. He said his organization is
urging growers to stop using the compound and hoping Uniroyal will
voluntarily halt sales.
   On Monday, Derr said that ``by September of this year, the
already low levels of Alar will be reduced to virtually zero.
Simply, the U.S. apple industry is not going to use Alar.''
   The Environmental Protection Agency estimated in March that Alar
was being used on just 10 percent of the nation's apple supply and
it was starting a procedure that could lead to a ban on the
chemical in 18 months.
   The Senate bill would affect only food crops and would allow
continued use of Alar on commercially produced flowers.
   None of the measure's sponsors is a member of the Senate
Agriculture Committee, which for years has proven an obstacle to
tough farm chemical regulations recommended by environmentalists
and consumer advocates.
   Similar legislation was quietly introduced in the House earlier
this year, although no action has been taken on it.
   Senators at the news conference said there was no time to lose
in clamping down on the chemical.
   ``If we do not ban Alar from the market, American consumers, in
increasing numbers, will ban apples from their diet,'' declared
Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn.
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., called the measure ``a major step in
the right direction, but no one should fool themselves into
thinking that this action eliminates the danger of pesticides for
American consumers.''
   ``There are 50,000 other pesticides out there,'' he said.
   ``If our children are at risk,'' said Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr.,
D-Mich., ``it is our responsibility to alleviate the risk right
now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0146 </DOCNO>
