<DOCNO> AP890517-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1958EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     05-17 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>50,000 Protesters Demand Roh's Downfall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KWANGJU, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of protesters
chanting ``Down with the dictatorship!'' Wednesday demanded the
overthrow of President Roh Tae-woo and protested the violent
suppression of a May 18, 1980 uprising.
   ``Punish Roh Tae-woo!'' was the cry from about 50,000 students,
workers and townspeople who marched through Kwangju, a city 168
miles south of Seoul.
   Thousands of students led the procession, waving red, blue and
yellow streamers and placards and accusing police of torturing a
student to death earlier this month.
   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo who committed murder and torture!''
screamed protesters who also demanded ``Yankees Go Home!'' They
accused the United States of ``patronizing the Roh regime.''
   Also Wednesday, the official Yonhap news agency reported
thousands of students staged peaceful campus protests in seven
other cities over the death of radical student Lee Chol-kyu.
   Thousands of people have protested daily in Kwangju since Lee's
body was found May 10 in a reservoir near the city. Police had
sought the student for anti-government acts.
   Government officials say Lee appears to have fallen into the
reservoir after fleeing from police who stopped him at a checkpoint.
   Speakers at a Wednesday rally in Kwangju called for a continued
campaign to end military rule in South Korea.
   ``Let's punish Roh and expel the Yankees forever by inheriting
the will of the patriot, Lee Chol-kyu,'' one dissident leader said.
The crowd responded with slogans demanding an independent
investigation into Lee's death.
   Police stayed away from the rally in an apparent move to avoid
clashes, but a spokesman said 7,000 riot policemen were on standby.
   The police are on a nationwide alert to block possible protests
marking the ninth anniversary of the nine-day civil uprising in
Kwangju in which at least 192 people were killed.
   Dissidents say Roh, a former general, is a front for military
rule and accuse him of helping his disgraced predecessor, Chun
Doo-hwan, to suppress the pro-democracy revolt.
   Government officials say they deployed troops as a last resort
to end an armed rebellion.
   The dissidents claim Chun and other army officers provoked the
uprising to seize power. They also say the United States condoned
Chun's actions _ a charge Washington denies.
   Chun went into rural exile last November after making a public
apology for misdeeds under his seven-year authoritarian rule.
Opposition parties want Chun to testify before the National
Assembly.
   South Korea has experienced a wave of violent anti-government
and anti-American protests and labor strikes in recent months.
   Roh ordered a crackdown on dissidents after six riot policemen
died in a May 3 campus clash.
   Dissidents and radical students have been calling for Roh's
overthrow, but they lack support because of their violent tactics
and extremist views.
   They also do not have the support of most South Koreans in their
demands for the withdrawal of about 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in
their country under a mutual defense pact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
