<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-Commissioners     05-17 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Commissioners,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Asks Pro Sports Officials for Tough, Uniform Drug Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GINSBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug Policy Coordinator William J. Bennett
told sports commissioners and player representatives Wednesday they
should set a single, tough drug policy for the pro athletes who set
examples for America's youth.
   Participants said the give-and-take with Bennett was useful, but
most said adoption of a uniform drug policy for major professional
sports was unlikely.
   ``It's far-fetched to believe that we can all agree'' on such a
policy, said Gene Upshaw, head of the National Football League
Players Association.
   While Bennett expressed a strong desire that the commissioners
toughen their stand on drug use in sports, he stopped short of
pressing the leagues to randomly test athletes for drugs.
   ``Surprisingly, he was not in there mandating that we have
random testing,'' Upshaw said. ``That was music to my ears.''
   All that may change, however, when the group convenes again this
summer.
   ``We didn't talk about random testing today, but we might talk
about that next time,'' Bennett said. ``We'll get into specifics at
the next meeting.''
   No policies were put in place Wednesday, but Bennett expressed
hope that concrete ideas might come out of the follow-up meeting.
   ``Most important, we have agreed to meet again this summer, in a
month or two, so we can have some specific suggestions for the
national strategy which I am writing,'' Bennett said.
   Among those at the meeting were commissioners Pete Rozelle of
the National Football League, David Stern of the National
Basketball Association and A. Bartlett Giamatti of major league
baseball.
   Steve Ryan, senior vice president for marketing and public
relations for the National Hockey League, was also present.
   Bennett, the top federal official in the fight against illegal
drugs, said he spent much of the 90-minute meeting exchanging ideas
with sports officials on ways to improve anti-drug standards in
general as well as for pro sports. While he listened to their
advice, he also made suggestions.
   ``I told them that professional sports has to be part of the
solution,'' Bennett said. ``The question I put to the group is,
`While we are pressing very hard on schools and others to have
tough policies, it seems only right that professional sports have
those kind of standards.'''
   Bennett said he was interested in getting the opinions of
high-ranking sports officials because most athletes are considered
role models by children.
   ``Pro sports play an important part in American life,'' Bennett
said. ``If they are so important, and they do have such a hold on
the American imagination, then this ought to be the focal point of
our effort.''
   Giamatti said, ``Pro sports has in place programs which, if not
perfect, are real comprehensive and, I think, he found
interesting.''
   Donald Fehr, executive director of the Major League Baseball
Players Association, said, ``Hopefully we were able to begin to
acquaint the secretary with the kinds of problems we've had and the
successes and the failures we went through in trying to solve
them.''
</TEXT>
