<FIRST>r w AM-People-Hamlisch     05-17 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Hamlisch,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oscar-winning Composer Serenades Senators On Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar-winning composer Marvin Hamlisch
serenaded a group of Democratic senators Wednesday after their
Republican counterparts were pulled away by a White House summons.
   Hamlisch was performing at a reception hosted by Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, to celebrate the musician's upcoming marriage
when the GOP contingent was called away to discuss minimum wage
legislation.
   ``I'm so sorry the president had to blow my little party by
taking all the Republicans,'' said Metzenbaum.
   So while the esteemed senators from the GOP did business at 1600
Pennsylvania Ave., Metzenbaum's Democratic pals enjoyed a bit of
Broadway in a government office building
   Hamlisch and Metzenbaum are longtime friends, and the musician's
fiancee, Terre Blair, hails from Columbus, Ohio.
   That was reason enough for Metzenbaum and his wife Shirley to
have tables, linens, asparagus salad and upright piano moved into
the Democrat's Capitol Hill office for a small celebration with
selected senators and spouses.
   Hamlisch played ``They're Playing My Song'' and Metzenbaum's
favorite Hamlisch composition, ``The Way We Were,'' for which the
composer earned one of his three Academy Awards.
   Hamlisch then asked the senators to call out any phrase so that
he could form a song around the lyric. Uncharacteristically, they
fell silent.
   The future bride, Ms. Blair, 33, said she met Hamlisch on a
blind telephone date set up by her Los Angeles housekeeper and the
housekeeper's New York sister.
   Ms. Blair said she almost didn't return the call when Hamlisch
left his number on her answering machine, but did so at the urging
of a friend.
   Ms. Blair and Hamlisch hit it off over the telephone and fell in
love before they met face-to-face.
   ``We had phone conversations that were incredible _ six and a
half hours long,'' Hamlisch said.
   ``I had no idea what she looked like, but I could tell that she
was a very giving person,'' said Hamlisch, who'll turn 45 a few
days after his May 29 wedding at New York's Tavern On The Green.
``It's really been magical. It's been wonderful.''
</TEXT>
