<FIRST>r a AM-MinorityClaims     05-17 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minority Claims,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Firefighters Resign in Minority Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two firefighters reportedly resigned amid an
investigation into charges they and nine others pretended to be
Hispanic to get preferential hiring treatment.
   Fire Department spokesman Bill Murphy and other city officials
would not confirm the report Wednesday in The Boston Globe.
   City Councilman Bruce Bolling, who called for an investigation
of minority hiring last year, said he could not obtain confirmation
either but that it appeared the probe by the state Personnel
Department was ending successfully.
   ``Hopefully, this chapter in the Boston Fire Department and city
could never be replicated again in terms of someone misrepresenting
themselves and getting away with it,'' Bolling said.
   The investigation began with the case of two fair-skinned
brothers who said they were black and went unchallenged for 10
years. The 33-year-old twins, Paul and Philip Malone, were
suspended without pay in August after officials determined they had
misrepresented their race.
   The Malones have refused to discuss the case on the advice of
their attorneys but told officials that their maternal
great-grandmother was black. A court hearing on their suspension
has been scheduled for next Wednesday.
   The Fire Department had forwarded the names of 11 firefighters
who identified themselves as Hispanic to the state. Officials have
said the 11 were hired between 1976 and 1983 before a screening
process was established in 1984.
   ``If they can substantiate that they in fact are minorities then
that's fine, but to the extent that they can't and they've clearly
misrepresented themselves they've taken an employment opportunity
away from a legitimate minority,'' Bolling said.
   In 1974, a federal court established a preference system for
hiring minorities after finding that Fire Department hiring had
been based on a discriminatory examination.
   At the time, only 19 of more than 2,100 city firefighters were
black or Hispanic. Today, the department is 21 percent black and
Hispanic, compared with 20 percent for the city's population.
   The Globe reported that firefighter Richard L. Pardo resigned
March 31 and Thomas France quit Monday. Pardo hung up when called
by The Associated Press on Wednesday. There was no listing for
France in the Boston telephone directory.
</TEXT>
