<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Envoy Seen for South Africa; More Contacts Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is expected to name
veteran diplomat William Swing as ambassador to South Africa and
will invite the leader of that nation's ruling party to Washington,
U.S. officials said Wednesday.
   Swing, 54, has previously served as ambassador to the Congo and
Liberia. In South Africa, he would replace Ambassador Edward
Perkins, who is returning home to become director general of the
Foreign Service. Swing is now deputy director in that office.
   The U.S. officials, insisting on anonymity, also said Bush is
expected to name conservative columnist Smith Hempstone as
ambassador to Kenya.
   The Nairobi post had been expected to go to career diplomat
Princeton Lyman, now ambassador to Nigeria, but the administration
decided to send a political appointee to Kenya, the officials said.
   Meanwhile, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration would invite the leader of South Africa's ruling
National Party, Frederick W. de Klerk, to visit.
   De Klerk is expected to succeed South Africa President P.W.
Botha once parliamentary elections are held in September.
   Asked about such a visit, State Department deputy spokesman
Richard Boucher said the United States is in touch with the South
African government ``regarding possible meetings and
consultations'' with de Klerk.
   He said the administration is planning to consult widely with
both black and white South Africans and to solicit viewpoints
across the South African political spectrum.
   More than 30 years have passed since a South African president,
prime minister or National Party leader has come to the United
States.
   A commentary aired on South Africa's state-run radio, reported
in Wednesday's edition of The Washington Post, said a visit by de
Klerk ``would be an important breakthrough'' in U.S.-South African
relations.
   The Post quoted a State Department official as saying that de
Klerk is ``obviously a very important person for us to be talking
to'' if serious negotiations between the races in South Africa are
to be renewed.
   Relations between the United States and South Africa soured
during the Reagan administration because of economic sanctions
imposed by Congress.
   But the commentary noted that President Bush, like Reagan, is a
strong opponent of further sanctions against South Africa.
</TEXT>
