<FIRST>r w AM-Refugees     05-17 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Begins Deporting Nicaraguans from South Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has deported the first
Nicaraguan refugees from South Texas since it began detaining
Central American asylum-seekers in February, officials said
Wednesday.
   Department spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade said the
deportations do not signal a change in policy and were delayed
because ``there were some bottlenecks.''
   Although dozens of Salvadorans, Guatemalans and Hondurans have
been deported since the Immigration and Naturalization Service
began detaining Central American asylum-seekers on Feb. 20, no
Nicaraguans had been deported until Monday.
   INS spokesman Duke Austin said 10 Nicaraguans were deported
Monday and 16 on Tuesday, with deportation orders pending on more
than 100 others.
   In July 1987, then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III issued a
memorandum encouraging the INS to look favorably on asylum cases
filed by Nicaraguans. That memo required the Justice Department's
asylum policy review unit to examine all requests for refugee
status from Nicaraguans, Austin said.
   The INS recently received approval from the Justice Department
to remove some Nicaraguans, Austin said. Ms. Burstion-Wade said
Deputy Attorney General Harold Christensen has final word on
Nicaraguan deportations.
   In the six months after the Meese memo, the Nicaraguan asylum
approval rate rose to 83 percent, compared with 30 percent before
the directive, according to INS figures released by Rep. John
Bryant, D-Texas.
   On Wednesday, religious leaders who toured the Rio Grande Valley
earlier this week condemned the INS' practice of detaining refugees
and disputed agency claims that the flow reaching Texas has dropped
under its get-tough approach.
   ``Despite the expenditure of a large sum of money (millions of
dollars) by the Immigration and Naturalization Service during the
past 60 days, we saw no convincing evidence that the policy of
increased enforcement, detention and rapid deportation has resulted
in any significant decrease in the flow of Central American
refugees across the border,'' the group's statement said.
   The group from the Interfaith Committee for Central American
Refugee Protection said the INS policy has succeded only in
removing the refugees and the problem from public view, while
creating ``serious obstacles to the filing of legitimate claims.''
   Austin said the group cannot back up claims the flow of aliens
has not fallen, adding: ``We can support with empirical data that
the flow has dramatically decreased,'' Austin said.
   Austin said the number of refugees filing for asylum has fallen
to about 70 or 80 a week, down from about 1,700 to 2,400 a week
earlier this year.
</TEXT>
