<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     05-17 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Accuse West Germans of Hiding Kidnappers' Identity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization
accused West German relief workers Wednesday of concealing the
identity of their kidnappers and asked them to vacate their base in
a refugee camp within 10 days.
   The PLO announcement came one day after police reported that
three workers in the private relief organization, ASME-Humanitas,
were abducted in Sidon by gunmen.
   One of the captives, nurse Petra Schnitzler, was freed after a
few hours when a local militia intercepted the kidnap vehicle in
the belief they were stopping escaping thieves.
   Police had no word on the whereabouts of Heinrich Struebig, 48,
an administrator, and Thomas Kemptner, 28, a nurse.
   ``All I can say about this case is that it stinks,'' said a
police spokesman.
   It was the third time Ms. Schnitzler and Struebig had been
reported abducted since last year. The two said they had been freed
from overnight captivity 13 days ago to transmit the demands of the
kidnappers holding a third colleague, Markus Quint. Quint was freed
Sunday.
   Palestinian security officials in south Lebanon quoted Ms.
Schnitzler and Struebig as saying the kidnappers were demanding a
mild sentence for confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi, a
Lebanese Shiite Moslem.
   A West German court sentenced Hamadi on Wednesday to a life
sentence for air piracy, murder and related charges in the June
1985 hijacking of a TWA passenger jet during which U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem was killed.
   A statement issued by the PLO at its Tunis headquarters and
transmitted to the Mieh Mieh Palestinian refugee camp said the
relief workers were covering up the identity of their abductors.
   ``Please, kindly, move out of our area for we are not
responsible for your security conditions from now on,'' the
handwritten, English-language statement said.
   They were given 10 days to pack and leave, a local official said.
   Asked to comment on the accusations that she helped conceal the
kidnappers' identity, Ms. Schnitzler said sarcastically: ``That's a
nice sentence. I would be happy if it were true.''
   She said the group will not take any decision without contacting
their organization.
   West German foreign ministry spokesman Juergen Chrobog said the
government had asked the group 15 times to pull out of Lebanon.
   Besides the two West Germans, 15 foreigners are missing in
Lebanon. Most are believed held by Shiite abductors loyal to Iran.
</TEXT>
