<FIRST>u i AM-Hamadi-Stethems     05-17 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamadi-Stethems,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victim's Parents Want US to Make Sure Hamadi Serves Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hamadi Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of U.S. Navy diver
Robert Stethem said Wednesday they want the United States to make
sure the man who murdered their son on a hijacked airliner never
gets out of prison.
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi deserved a death sentence, Richard and
Patricia Stethem said, but the maximum sentence in West Germany is
life imprisonment.
   He was given a life sentence Wednesday for murder, air piracy
and other charges connected with the June 1985 hijacking of a TWA
jetliner, during which 23-year-old Robert Stethem was beaten, shot
and thrown from the aircraft.
   The courtroom in Frankfurt's Preungesheim prison compound was
packed to hear the verdict and sentencing.
   Hamadi, 24, was standing next to his translator and appeared to
slump slightly and bowed his head momentarily when Chief Judge
Heiner Mueckenberger pronounced the maximum sentence.
   Soon afterward, Mr. and Mrs. Stethem met with reporters and read
a statement that said: ``Our family maintains that Mohammed Ali
Hamadi deserves punishment more severe than allowable under German
law.''
   When asked what he meant by a more severe punishment, Stethem
replied: ``The death sentence. I believe that if he had been tried
in the United States, that very possibly he would have been given
the death sentence.''
   In their first public comment since the trial began July 5,
1988, the Stethems expressed concern about speculation that Hamadi
might be freed someday for political reasons.
   ``We mention this because the thought of such a release is
painful for us to think of,'' Stethem said. ``Any commutation of
Hamadi's sentence would be a pure mockery of justice.''
   Last week, Frankfurt lawyer Rainer Hamm said the Stethems and
the 17 other American co-prosecutors feared kidnappings and other
types of ``blackmail'' might lead West Germany to release Hamadi
early. Hamm represented the Americans.
   Stethem said Wednesday, reading from the statement: ``We would
hope any release would result in a public outcry by German and
American citizens alike and would cause people to express outrage
against this type of political injustice.
   ``We would expect our present administration, State Department,
Department of Justice and Congress to monitor the fulfillment of
this sentence and to ensure it is completely served.''
   Prosecutors said Hamadi would be eligible for a parole review in
15 years. The Stethems attended the trial from the beginning.
   ``It was very hard to sit there and hear this, but it was better
to be sitting here and hearing it than sitting in the States and
not knowing what was going on,'' Richard Stethem said. ``We had to
be here to hear it.''
   Mrs. Stethem said, her voice shaking, ``Our purpose for being
there was to represent our son. I thought he deserved that. With
all his bravery, I felt he deserved more than that.''
   Passengers on TWA Flight 847 testified that Robert Stethem was
beaten repeatedly before he was shot.
   During the proceedings, the Stethems sometimes appeared to stare
for long periods directly at Hamadi, across the courtroom from
them. On Wednesday, they acknowledged making eye contact with the
Lebanese Shiite Moslem.
   ``We could look at him and we stared at him a lot, but he wasn't
one to look back at us,'' Richard Stethem said. ``We could catch
him a very few times looking at us.''
   His wife said: ``When we did make eye contact he immediately
dropped his eyes in a guilty sort of way and I felt a lot of guilt
on his part in that way.''
   Asked what she felt in those moments, she replied without
hesitation: ``Like I could go over and punch him out.''
   ``I think that we felt that we probably would like to harm
him,'' her husband added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
