<FIRST>u w AM-JapanFighter     05-17 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan Fighter,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats, With GOP Help, Back Senate Restraints on FSX Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic House members, joined by some
Republicans, vowed Wednesday to write into law Senate-passed
restrictions on President Bush's plan to coproduce the FSX jet
fighter with Japan.
   The lawmakers said they will ask the House Foreign Affairs
Committee on Thursday to endorse Senate legislation sponsored by
Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., directing the White House to forbid
the transfer of sophisticated jet engine technology to Japan and to
guarantee the United States gets at least 40 percent of the
benefits of the deal.
   The White House said it has ``grave concerns'' that the Byrd
amendment could erode presidential authority. The State Department
said the provision could force renegotiation of the agreement with
the Japanese government.
   The House prepared to begin work on the FSX plan following the
Senate's narrow 52-47 defeat of a bid to reject the arrangement
entirely.
   Although the Senate kept the plan alive, it also voted 72-27
Tuesday to adopt the Byrd amendment's restrictions.
   In the House, Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who campaigned for
the Democratic presidential nomination last year on a platform of
protecting U.S. industry against Japanese imports, said it is
essential that Congress adopt the amendment because ``we don't want
some vague promise that doesn't get fulfilled.
   ``It is important to hold the administration's feet to the
fire,'' said Rep. Mel Levine, D-Calif. ``We're saying that when you
negotiate a deal, demonstrate that we are really going to get the
40 percent you were talking about.''
   The Senate passed the Byrd amendment by a virtually veto-proof
margin and Levine said there is a good chance the House can follow
suit.
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., said the amendment was a
classic example of meddling ``micromanagement'' by Congress. He
described it as ``a sour-grape amendment by those who lost the vote
against FSX in the Senate.''
   But Rep. Helen Delich Bentley, R-Md., predicted that a number of
Republicans would join the House's Democratic majority in
supporting the restrictions proposed by Byrd.
   One reason they will do so, she said, is that Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries, the Japanese company slated to build the FSX, also
built part of a complex in Libya the United State says is capable
of producing poison gas in large quantities.
   ``You are going to find a lot of Republicans who are against
this,'' Mrs. Bentley said.
   Gephardt was asked if Byrd's proposal is a ``killer amendment''
that would prove fatal to the FSX codevelopment and coproduction
plan.
   ``If it is, it ought to be killed,'' Gephardt said.
   At the White House, press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush
told House Republicans his administration would work against the
Byrd amendment when the measure gets to a HouseSenate conference
committee to resolve variances between the two houses' versions.
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel of Illinois said Bush had
asked Republicans to stick with him on the FSX even though they
face pressure back home.
   Fitzwater said Bush was concerned by the Byrd amendment because
``it creates a system of congressional approval over these kinds of
projects that we consider to be erosive of presidential power.''
   Even before Tuesday's vote, Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
S. Eagleburger made it known that the administration regarded the
new directives as unneccessary and likely to trigger new and
lengthy negotiations.
   Byrd told the Senate on Tuesday the restrictions were essential
because ``it would be foolhardy not to be vigilant in protecting
our aircraft industry and the vital technologies associated with
it.''
</TEXT>
