<FIRST>r w AM-DrugSupplies     05-17 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Supplies,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine is Cheaper and Purer, and Users are Hospitalized More Often</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine was readily available nationwide at
record-low prices last year while hospitals reported emergency-room
visits by users jumped nearly a third, a government study said
Wednesday.
   Users paid between $50 and $120 per gram of cocaine while
wholesale prices ranged between $11,000 and $34,000 per kilogram,
according to the 11th annual survey of illicit drugs by the
National Narcotics Intelligence Consumers Committee.
   Wholesale prices have declined for the fourth straight year from
1985, when a kilogram cost betweeen $30,000 and $50,000, said the
study.
   Last year, a kilogram of cocaine cost between $12,000 and
$40,000, according to the study based on law enforcement reports.
Retail prices ranged between $80 and $120 a gram in 1986 and 1987.
   The study also found that purity of cocaine available to users
had increased from about 50 percent to 70 percent last year,
according to laboratory tests performed by the Drug Enforcement
Administration.
   The availability of purer and cheaper cocaine was accompanied by
a projected 30 percent increase in the number of hospital
emergency-room visits due to cocaine use last year, the report said.
   Based on data from the first nine months of 1988, the study
projects there were 42,491 hospital emergencies from cocaine use
last year compared to 32,578 recorded in 1987.
   There were 19,090 emergencies reported in 1986 and 10,397 in
1985, the study said.
   Peru remained the world's largest source of coca and unprocessed
cocaine last year, while ``Colombian nationals continued to be the
predominant ethnic group involved in cocaine processing,
importation and distribution,'' the report said.
   The report also noted that cocaine processing at illegal
laboratories in this country continued to decrease last year. It
concluded that drug traffickers had transferred their operations to
Latin America in the wake of stepped-up U.S. enforcement efforts.
   The number of cocaine laboratories seized by police and federal
agents dropped from 17 in the 1987 fiscal year to nine during the
1988 fiscal year, the report said.
   The report also found that crack was available in most major
metropolitan areas. Only a few major cities, notably Chicago and
St. Louis, did not report serious trafficking in crack.
   Increased crack use was reported last year in Washington,
Boston, Philadelphia, Atlanta, New Orleans, Denver and Phoenix.
   The study was written by the interagency committee that is
composed of representatives from 11 agencies, including the FBI,
the Coast Guard, the Drug Enforcement Administration, the CIA, the
State Department and the U.S. Customs Service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
