<FIRST>r w AM-ForeignPurchase     05-17 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Purchase,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Block Possible Foreign Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has decided not to block the
possible foreign acquisition of Westinghouse Electric Corp.'s
interest in a joint venture with a European company, the
administration said Wednesday.
   Bush made his decision after an investigation by an inter-agency
committee headed by Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady. The
president has the power to block foreign acquisitions of American
companies if the sales would endanger national security.
   The latest review involved a joint venture between Westinghouse
and ASEA Brown Boveri LTD (ABB), a manufacturing firm based in
Switzerland.
   The joint venture, known as Westinghouse-ABB Power T&amp;D Co., was
created earlier in the year to manufacture and sell high-voltage
electrical transmission equipment.
   In announcing Bush's decision, the administration said that ABB
had confirmed its intention to continue manufacturing the high
voltage transformers in the United States even if it did excercise
its option under the agreement to purchase Westinghouse's share of
the joint venture.
   Under the agreement, Westinghouse, which is based in Pittsburgh,
now owns 55 percent of the joint venture and ABB owns 45 percent.
   The joint company planned to serve the electrical transmission
markets in the United States, Brazil and Argentina with expected
annual sales of $1 billion, according to a company news release.
   The operation employs 10,000 workers in 20 Westinghouse
facilities and three ABB facilities in the United States and Latin
America, the company said.
</TEXT>
