<SECOND>AM-Boy Murder,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder Defendant, 12, Enters Plea In Fatal Torching</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIDDEFORD, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old pleaded guilty Wednesday
to murder and arson for setting a fire that killed his babysitter.
   Clutching a stack of baseball cards, fidgeting and frequently
grinning at his attorney, blond-haired, crew-cut Scott James enter
the plea as he was about to go to trial in the Dec. 31 death of
53-year-old Raymond R. Lauzon.
   Sentencing was set for May 30. The boy, who was 11 when he set
the blaze, will be freed from custody by his 21st birthday because
he was charged as a juvenile.
   ``Scott needs a lot of help and it's time he got it,'' defense
attorney Thomas Van Houten said.
   ``We hope that something good will come out of it for him,''
said Assistant Attorney General Eric Wright.
   The defendant told the judge he started the fire. But he
disputed the prosecution's contention that he told his younger
brother he wanted to see what it would be like to burn the house
and kill the man.
   Wright said Lauzon had caught the boy trying to steal some money
from his wallet.
   Scott and his brother were staying in Lauzon's apartment while
their mother went to a bar with Lauzon's son on New Year's Eve.
