<FIRST>u p AM-ElectionRdp     05-17 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Election Rdp,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver OKs New Airport, Seattle Puts Cap on Downtown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Seattle voters put the brakes on growth in the tallest city in
the West, Denver residents gave clearance to build a $2.3 billion
airport, and Pittsburgh's ``Jewish grandmother'' won the
all-important Democratic nomination for mayor.
   In other elections Tuesday, voters rejected tax overhauls in
Pennsylvania and Oregon and approved a Tucson, Ariz., school bond
package totaling $398 million _ 10 times the amount of a similar
measure that was rejected last year.
   In Pittsburgh, Mayor Sophie Masloff, 71, won the primary and
practically guaranteed herself victory in November. She was City
Council president last year when she was appointed to succeed the
late Mayor Richard S. Caliguiri.
   Denver voters sided 63 percent to 37 percent with Mayor Federico
Pena and Gov. Roy Romer, agreeing it was time to replace
60-year-old Stapleton International Airport, the nation's fifth
largest, with an airport 20 miles from downtown.
   It would be the nation's first new airport since Dallas-Fort
Worth International opened in 1974. Pena and Romer said Stapleton
was overcrowded and obsolete. Opponents said the plan was
unnecessary and too costly.
   Seattle residents approved an initiative that restricts the
density of buildings downtown and limits their height to 450 feet,
about 38 stories, for the next 10 years while a long-range
development plan is adopted.
   The city's tallest building is the 76-story Columbia Center.
   With 99 percent of precincts reporting, the count was 42,643 to
26,303, with only a simple majority required.
   Voters delivered setbacks to Govs. Robert P. Casey of
Pennsylvania and Neil Goldschmidt of Oregon, who put their
reputations behind proposals to overhaul their states' taxes.
   Pennsylvania voters turned back, 75 percent to 25 percent, a
referendum that would have allowed counties to impose income taxes
in exchange for a reduction in property taxes.
   Also defeated was a Philadelphia proposal to legalize charity
raffles and other small games of chance.
   Oregonians rejected, 59 percent to 41 percent, a measure that
would have updated tax bases in about a third of the state's school
districts, effectively allowing them to raise property taxes
without asking voter approval.
</TEXT>
