<FIRST>r a AM-CalifCorruption     05-17 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Calif Corruption,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Senator Charged with Corruption After Undercover Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury indicted a state
senator and his former aide Wednesday on bribery and extortion
charges.
   Joseph Montoya, chairman of the Senate Business and Professions
Committee, was indicted as a result of a three-year FBI undercover
investigation. The investigation became public in August when
federal agents searched the Capitol offices of Montoya and three
other legislators.
   U.S. Attorney David Levi said Montoya, a Democrat, and Amiel A.
Jaramillo were named in a 12-count indictment under two
anti-corruption laws, the Racketeer Influenced, Corrupt
Organizations Act and the Hobbs Act.
   The indictment says Montoya and Jaramillo used the office of
state senator ``to unlawfully obtain campaign contributions and
other payments, including speaking fees.''
   In the FBI probe, federal agents posed as businessmen and set up
phony companies that dispensed at least $90,000 to lawmakers and
political consultants in return for favors, according to public
documents and private business records.
   Montoya and Jaramillo were not available to comment, an aide
told a reporter at Montoya's office.
   Montoya faces maximum penalties of 160 years in prison and $1
million in fines, plus forfeiture of any illegally acquired
property if convicted. Jaramillo faces 80 years in prison and
$250,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
