<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--HowardAward     05-17 0125</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Howard Award,110</SECOND>
<HEAD>Late Congressman Honored for Highway Safety Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Rep. James J. Howard, a New Jersey
Democrat who had led efforts to raise the drinking age to 21 and
hold the national speed limit at 55 mph, was honored Wednesday for
leadership in highway safety.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and Rep. Glenn Anderson,
D-Calif., chairman of the Public Works and Transportation
Committee, discussed Howard's accomplishments during presentation
of the National Safety Council's James J. Howard Legislative
Leadership Award.
   Howard, who came to the House in 1965, died in 1988. Marie
Howard, one of the late congressman's daughters, accepted the
award. Future recipients will be members of Congress who
demonstrate leadership in the field of health and safety.
