<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-US 1stLd-Writethru   05-17 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-US, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0631,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>New U.S. Ambassador Leaves Stetson at Office For Palace Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to ADD details on Catto. Pick up 6th pvs,
`During the...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dallas-born Henry Catto, the new U.S. ambassador,
traded his Stetson for a top hat Wednesday to lead a horse carriage
procession to Buckingham Palace and present his credentials to the
queen.
   Catto set off from his embassy to the cheers of colleagues, then
returned to fulfill the custom of treating the state footmen to
champagne and their horses to sugar and carrots.
   The ceremony and private audience with Queen Elizabeth II marked
his introduction as the 27th U.S. ambassador to the Court of St.
James, the nearby 16th-century palace where envoys still are
accredited.
   ``I feel wonderful,'' beamed the 58-year-old businessman and
close friend of President Bush. ``How could you not, on a day like
this?''
   Catto, who has businesses in Houston and San Antonio but whose
Texas drawl has been diluted by decades in Washington, said, ``The
queen is just the easiest person in the world to talk to.''
   During the 20-minute audience in the palace's white-and-gold
1844 room _ named for the year Czar Nicholas of Russia visited
Queen Victoria _ they discussed the visit of Bush at the end of
this month, the private visit of former President Reagan in
mid-June and ``generalities.''
   Catto presented her with two letters from the White House: one
for his accreditation and the other with his predecessor's recall.
   He didn't show her the Texas hedgear he'd lovingly carried with
him to London. ``It's up in the office,'' he said of his Stetson.
``I didn't have the nerve.''
   Catto, who runs a string of TV stations with his wife, Jessica,
arrived April 23 to replace Charles H. Price II, who retired at the
end of February after a six-year term.
   The ``special relationship'' between the United States and Great
Britain is also a personal relationship for Catto, who hopes to
have time to trace the ancestors of his Scottish grandfather who
emigrated to the United States a century ago.
   Catto's only other appointment as an ambassador came in 1969, as
deputy U.S. representative to the Organization of American States.
He subsequently was chief of protocol, permanent representative to
the European Office of the United Nations in Geneva and chief
spokesman for the Pentagon.
   He has kept his hand in business, through the H and C
Communication television network he runs with his wife. She once
edited, and he owned, the Washington Journalism Review magazine,
and he continues to write for various publications.
   On Wednesday, Mrs. Catto was in Colorado attending to her real
estate business, and none of their four grown children was present.
   Followed by eight embassy counselors in top hat and tails, Catto
and the uniformed marshall of the diplomatic corps, Lt. Gen. Sir
John Richards, led the procession of three open carriages the short
ride to the palace.
   Back at the embassy, Catto distributed champagne and carrots, as
required.
   ``Can I interest you in a drop?'' Catto asked one footman in a
bright orange-red coat. ``To your very good health, sir,'' came the
acceptance.
   Later, rubbing sugar from his hands, Catto said he'd begun to
settle in.
   ``No culture shock yet,'' he said, smiling. ``I can now find my
way to the office. And so far I've almost been able to master the
language.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
