<FIRST>u i AM-China-Complaints     05-17 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Complaints,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Air Complaints Shared With Student Boycotters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese long have complained about corruption and
their lack of basic freedoms, but they dared not protest until a
plucky group of students with the same grievances staged a defiant
hunger strike.
   Inspired by the 3,000 students fasting for democracy in
Tiananmen Square, the Chinese masses have found their voice and for
the first time are telling their Communist leaders loud and clear
what they think of their rule.
   In a massive show of dissatisfaction, more than 1 million people
_ including workers, students and even government employees _
poured into central Beijing on Wednesday to support the hunger
strikers, who are fasting to press student demands for more freedom
and clean government.
   As they marched up and down the broad avenues of the nation's
capital, workers and students chanted, ``Down with official
profiteering!'' and ``Oppose corruption!''
   Some boldly called on Premier Li Peng and China's senior leader
Deng Xiaoping to resign _ they consider Li too conservative and the
84-year-old Deng too old. A student standing on top of a school bus
repeatedly shouted, ``Li Peng!'' and the crowd replied, ``Step
down!''
   Just a few weeks ago, said a 38-year-old auto worker who was
marching with hundreds of his colleagues, such a display would have
been unthinkable. ``I absolutely would not have believed this could
happen,'' he said.
   The protests result from a general dissatisfaction has been
growing for some time.
   In the past 10 years, China's economy has made a remarkable
recovery under Deng's pragmatic market-oriented policies. But
widespread corruption by Communist officials and dismay that
political liberalization has proceeded at a much slower pace than
economic reform has caused increased grumbling.
   Privately, Chinese relate their latest brush with corrupt
officials or criticize the lack of democracy. But before last
month, only a handful of intellectuals dared speak out.
   China's most prominent critic was astrophysicist Fang Lizhi,
whose international prestige as a scientist probably protects him
from extreme government action.
   When the students first began demonstrating for democracy after
the death of former Communist Party leader Hu Yaobang, workers
obviously were sympathetic.
   Students who marched through Beijing received cheers and
donations, but many workers still were frightened to join the
processions.
   The hunger strikers have changed that.
   Workers were touched by the students' plight, and the resolve of
the hunger-strikers remained strong while their health
deteriorated. The widespread admiration for the fasters, whose
goals are shared by many Chinese, was obvious Wednesday.
   ``They're hearts are bleeding,'' said one laborer. ``They have
been on hunger strike for several days; the workers can no longer
be silent.''
   Many people said that the students' demands, such as a dialogue
with the government, were reasonable and should be accepted by the
government to end the strike.
   But the delay in resolving the impasse has bolstered the student
protest with hundreds of thousands of workers and other supporters
who otherwise might have stayed silent.
   One poster in Tiananmen Square on Wednesday summed up the new
order: ``The students are the vanguard, the workers are the backup
force.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
