<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-US     05-17 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-US,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Accuse US Continuing to Support Contra War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry claimed Wednesday
the United States was continuing to support guerrilla war by
Nicaraguan rebels and said it had complained to Washington.
   The ministry said more than 1,000 people on both sides had been
killed or wounded this year and that the rebels, known as Contras,
attacked military or civilian targets 58 times in the first half of
May alone.
   Contra spokesmen denied the claims, accusing Nicaragua's leftist
Sandinista government of trying through propaganda to avoid
complying with a regional peace agreement.
   Nicaragua's protest was contained in a letter to Secretary of
State James A. Baker III from Jose Leon Talavera, the deputy
foreign minister.
   ``If the United States is truly interested in advancing toward a
solution of the Central American crisis, it should begin by
respecting the will of Central Americans themselves,'' Talavera
said in the letter, dated May 16.
   Barricada, the newspaper of the ruling Sandinista National
Liberation Front, published the letter Wednesday, and ministry
spokesman David Silva said it had been sent to Baker.
   Last month, Congress approved $48 million in non-lethal aid to
keep the Contras intact through Feb. 25, 1990, when general
elections are scheduled in Nicaragua.
   About 10,000 Contras are in jungle camps in neighboring Honduras
along with 11,000 family members. Most of the rebels left Nicaragua
after Contra and Sandinista leaders signed a temporary truce in
March 1988.
   Since then, the Sandinistas have extended the truce unilaterally
on a month-by-month basis and only sporadic skirmishes had been
reported.
   Talavera said in the letter, however, that Contras attacked 58
times in the period May 1-15. So far this year, he said, the
Contras had killed 47 civilians, wounded 38 and kidnapped 131.
   He said the army had suffered 309 casualties and the Contras 707
since Jan. 1, but did not give a breakdown of dead and wounded.
   The letter to Baker said the ``account of actions against my
country is more than enough to show that your government's current
policy is not contributing toward peace in Central America.''
   Wilfredo Montalvan, a member of the Nicaraguan Resistance
directorate, denied the letter's claims.
   ``The Sandinista regime has always wanted to present the civil
war, which is now suspended, as Yankee aggression,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Miami. The Sandinistas use ``that old
tactic ... every time they find themselves in difficulties'' and
want to avoid fulfilling the peace agreement, Montalvan said.
   Contra spokesman Jorge Rosales, also in Miami, said 2,000-3,000
rebels remain in Nicaragua and have been ``strictly observing the
cease-fire.'' He claimed the Sandinista army attacked rebels and
their sympathizers, but he would not give casualty figures.
   Talavera said any aid not intended to dismantle the Contras goes
against the will of the presidents of Nicaragua, El Salvador,
Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala and serves to continue the war.
   The presidents signed a regional peace pact Feb. 14 in El
Salvador in which Nicaragua promised more democracy and also agreed
to draft a plan by May 15 to disband the Contras, most of whom are
in neighboring Honduras.
   At the request of President Jose Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador,
the deadline was extended until an unspecified date in July after
the inauguration of his successor, Alfredo Cristiani.
</TEXT>
