<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-NuclearTreaty     05-17 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Nuclear Treaty,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Urge Bush to Ask Gorbachev to Clarify Soviet Commitment
to Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 19 members of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee urged President Bush on Wednesday to ask Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to clarify the Soviet commitment to the treaty
banning medium-range nuclear-armed missiles worldwide.
   The senators said they were disturbed by a recent remarks by
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze that the Soviets might
not dismantle their SS-23 medium-range missiles as required by the
treaty if NATO nations modernize their short-range nuclear weapons.
   Sen. Nancy Landon Kassebaum, R-Kan., an organizer of the
letter-writing effort, noted that the Intermediate-Range Nuclear
Forces treaty does not ban short-range missiles with a range under
300 miles.
   Therefore, she said, modernization by NATO of such short-range
missiles would not violate the treaty.
   ``We find these remarks very troubling,'' the committee members
told Bush.
   ``Mr. Shevardnadze's suggestion that the Soviets might not abide
by the terms of the treaty in response to the modernization of
systems which are not covered by the treaty, threatens to challenge
the integrity of the INF accord, as well as overall confidence in
the arms control process,'' they said.
   It is in ``neither side's interest at this time to challenge
that agreement,'' the senators said. ``Both sides should instead be
building on the achievements of the INF accord and moving forward
to take advantage of the many promising opportunities before us in
East-West relations.''
   The senators urged the president ``to seek a clarification from
General Secretary Gorbachev as to the Soviets' commitments to the
INF accord and to consult with us on these developments.''
   The Senate ratified the INF treaty on a 93-5 roll call last year
after a lengthy debate.
</TEXT>
