<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-ArtTheft     05-17 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Art Theft,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stolen Art Works Recovered By Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN SILVERSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested five men and
recovered millions of dollars worth of art stolen from a museum
this month, including works by Salvador Dali and Henri Matisse, a
police officer said Wednesday.
   Alvaro Luis Souza, who commanded the raid leading to the
arrests, said officers, responding to an anonymous phone tip
Tuesday night, raced to an apartment building in Rio's Botafogo
neigborhood.
   They staked out the apartment and apprehended a man as he was
leaving the building, Souza said. The stolen goods were discovered,
undamaged, inside the apartment.
   Souza said four other men were arrested hours later.
   Police still are searching for three more men who they believe
were involved in the May 3 robbery of the Chacara do Ceu Museum,
Souza said. Six men took part in the actual robbery, and police
believe they had two accomplices.
   Souza said police had recovered all the stolen art except two
Chinese ceramic sculptures from the 7th century and a collection of
silverware.
   Among the works recovered were:
   _A 1929 painting by the late Spanish surrealist Dali, ``Les Deux
Balcons,'' or ``The Two Balconies.'' It was the only Dali on public
display in Brazil.
   _A 1905 painting, ``Le Jardin du Luxembourg,'' or ``Luxembourg
Garden,'' by Matisse, the 20th century French post-impressionist.
   _Three works by the late Candido Portinari, one of Brazil's most
important contemporary artists, including ``O Sonho,'' meaning
``The Dream,'' and ``As Lavadeiras,'' or ``The Washerwomen.''
   At the time of the robbery Marcio Fortes, the museum's director,
estimated the total value of the works stolen at $30-$40 million.
   The museum, suffering financial problems, had insured the works
only in case of fire.
   The museum was robbed when the gunmen _ disguised as police
officers _ tied up three employees and fled with the art.
   The museum had been the residence of the late Brazilian
industrialist Raymundo Ottoni de Castro Maya, who left his home and
collection to the nation.
   The collection, opened to the public in 1972, includes
paintings, sculptures, silverware, furniture and other objects.
</TEXT>
