<DOCNO> AP890517-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpendingBill     05-17 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Postpones Action on Bill Bearing Veterans, Anti-Drug Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House postponed action until next week on
a multi-billion dollar domestic spending bill when Democrats and
Republicans became embroiled Wednesday in a dispute over anti-drug
spending.
   The stall occurred despite outcries from the Bush
administration, lawmakers and veterans groups that $340 million in
the measure for veterans health programs was needed as soon as
possible.
   The dispute began when House Appropriations Committee Chairman
Jamie Whitten, D-Miss., attempted to bring a $3.7 billion
supplemental spending bill for this year to the House floor.
   Republicans blocked Whitten with a procedural move, with Rep.
Bill Frenzel of Minnesota, ranking Republican on the House Budget
Committee, arguing that the measure would be ``veto bait.''
   Bush administration officials have said they would urge the
president to veto the bill unless $822 million it contains for
anti-drug programs is removed.
   Rep. Silvio Conte of Massachusetts, ranking Republican on the
Appropriations Committee, offered a bill bearing only the $340
million for veterans, but majority Democrats refused to allow it to
be debated.
   Democrats claimed Republicans simply don't want to put extra
federal muscle into efforts to crack down on illegal drug
trafficking.
   ``There's only one thing holding up this'' bill, said Rep. Neal
Smith, D-Iowa, chairman of the Appropriations justice subcommittee.
``The administration does not want this Congress to appropriate any
more money for crime and drugs.''
   In addition, several liberal Democrats are attempting to amend
the measure with language that would transfer about $900 million
next year from the Star Wars anti-missile program to anti-drug
initiatives.
   Secretary Edward Derwinski of the Department of Veterans Affairs
on Wednesday called the need for money ``a real emergency.'' A day
earlier, he warned in a letter that a delay in the money would mean
gradual reductions in numbers of workers, delays in purchasing
medical equipment, and a halt in construction projects.
   The House does not plan to consider the measure again until next
week. The Senate leaves town this week for a Memorial Day recess
and does not return until May 31.
   Last month, a $4.7 billion version of the spending measure had
been pulled off the House floor after objections that it was too
expensive.
   The Appropriations Committee had stripped $1 billion from it for
the costs of fighting last year's forest fires, the Federal
Aviation Administration, the homeless, public housing, reparations
to Japanese-Americans who were kept in camps during World War II,
and other programs.
</TEXT>
