<DOCNO> AP890517-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Palau     05-17 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Palau,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomats Call Palau's Complaints About US a Bargaining Tactic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Complaints by Palau of inadequate
development and economic dependency under U.S. administration are a
bargaining tactic to get more money from Washington, a U.N.
investigative mission said Wednesday.
   The British and French diplomats and U.N. officials who visited
Palau in April also said Soviet claims of ``militarization'' of the
Pacific archipelago were groundless.
   According to their report, ``The only United States military
presence in Palau is a small U.S. Navy detachment, the Seabees,
numbering 21 men, which is doing construction work at the request
of the local authorities.''
   Soviet diplomats, environmentalists and peace activists have
accused the Pentagon of planning to establish bases in the islands,
possibly armed with nuclear weapons.
   The investigators, sent by the U.N. Trusteeship Council, found
Palauans concerned with ``the level of compensation and the manner
in which such compensation would be negotiated rather than ... the
possible end use of the land.''
   ``As regards the `nuclear issue,' this was scarcely raised in
the course of the mission's visit,'' they said. ``In particular, it
was not brought up as a subject of major significance in any of the
mission's meetings with political leaders of all persuasions.''
   Palau is the only chain of islands still under U.N. trust
supervision.
   Vice President Kuniwo Nakamura of Palau said Monday the
territory was economically weak, with inadequate health and social
services, and the United States had failed in its duty as trustee.
   In its evaluation, the U.N. mission praised U.S. support for
political development and the archipelago's education system.
   It said of Palauan complaints about economic development and
social conditions:
   ``Among the problems frequently cited as examples were the
inadequacy of the road system, except in Koror, and the limitations
of the hospital system.
   ``In view of the considerable sums of money spent by the
administering authority in the past in the field of economic and
social development, and of additional commitments under the
proposed new status arrangements, the Mission considers that this
attitude largely reflects tactical considerations.''
   The complaints were ``aimed at obtaining additional concessions
from the U.S. executive and legislative branches at a time when
delicate negotiations have just begun between the United States
authorities'' and Palauan officials, the mission declared.
   In 1988,the 15,000 people of Palau received about $33 million in
U.S. aid. Jean-Michel Gaussot of France and J. Stephen Smith of
Britain led the mission for the Trusteeship Council, which is
evaluating Palau's progress toward adopting the proposed Compact of
Free Association with the United States.
   That agreement would make the islands self-governing but leave
the United States in charge of defense, with the right to use land
for any purpose it deemed necessary in exchange for $1 billion in
aid over 75 years. About $460 million of the U.S. aid would be paid
in the first 15 years.
   U.S. officials deny planning to establish military bases. Last
year, however, Adm. William Crowe, chairman of the joint chiefs,
told a congressional committee Palau would be ``one of the first or
priority areas we would have to look at'' if the United States lost
its bases in the Philippines.
   Palau's constitution bars nuclear weapons and nuclear power from
its territory. A majority of Palauans have favored the Compact in
several referendums, but it has not won the 75 percent needed to
overrule the constitutional ban.
   The United States captured the archipelago and other Pacific
islands from Japan in World War II. It consists of 200 islands,
totaling 192 square miles, about 500 miles east of the Philippine
island of Mindanao.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
