<DOCNO> AP890517-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Fusion-Utah     05-17 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion-Utah,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Officials Defend Research, Say Energy Ratio Increasing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the University of Utah on
Wednesday defended the school's room-temperature fusion claims,
saying there is only a 1 percent chance they are, as skeptics say,
the result of laboratory error.
   Chase Peterson told state legislators that scientists have
failed to disprove the claims of chemists Martin Fleischmann and
Stanley Pons, who contend they have sustained nuclear fusion in a
tabletop experiment.
   Peterson said others have failed to duplicate the results
because the experiment is difficult and takes time.
   ``There has been no disproving data,'' Peterson said. ``The work
has been described as simple, but it's really very difficult
electrochemistry.'''
   In separate state House and Senate appearances, university
officials said Pons, a Utah professor, and Fleischmann, of the
University of Southampton, in England, continue to report dramatic
results.
   James Brophy, the university's vice president for research, said
the experiment produces 100 times the energy needed to run it.
Pons' goal is a 1,000-to-1 ratio, Brophy said.
   When they announced their discovery at a March 23 news
conference, Pons and Fleischmann said they had achieved 4-to-1
ratio.
   Levels have been boosted by a change in the apparatus,
specifically an increase in the size of the palladium electrode,
Brophy said.
   Legislators, who last month voted overwhelmingly to appropriate
$5 million to support the research, offered no criticism of the
claims.
   Peterson said a small portion of the $5 million has been spent
on patent research and applications. The rest is in escrow until an
independent panel of scientists and businessmen decides the
experiment has been confirmed.
   Pons and Fleischmann have been derided by other scientists for
their claim. If fusion, which powers the sun, can be created at
room temperature, it could be a cheap and safe source of energy.
   Peterson said Pons and Fleischmann must ignore the public debate
and focus on their research. Without elaborating, he dismissed the
chance of fundamental laboratory errors as a 1 in 100 possibility.
   Peterson also said private corporations continue to show a
strong interest in the project, with 45 companies having e signed
confidential disclosure agreements that permit them to review the
school's patent applications.
   He declined to identify any of the companies except
Westinghouse, which has acknowledged sending its officials to the
Utah campus to review the project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
