<SECOND>AM-Britain-Explosive,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alert Issued For Tins Of Candy Containing Explosives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British airports and airlines have been alerted to
watch out for containers of marzipan candy that could contain
Semtex plastic explosive, the Transport Department said Wednesday.
   The department said in a statement that the alert followed the
discovery of a brand of Middle East marzipan containing Semtex. It
gave no other details about the find.
   Investigators say Semtex is thought to have been used in the
bomb built into a radio-cassette player that destroyed Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, last Dec. 21. All 259 people
on the New York-bound plane and 11 on the ground were killed.
   Semtex is made in Czechoslovakia. It is odorless, hard to detect
and can be molded into any shape.
