<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-17 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit Texas Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Punishing thunderstorms lashed Texas for the second day in a row
Wednesday with tornadoes and heavy rain, destroying 45 homes and 16
businesses, causing floods, and forcing the evacuation of hundreds
of people.
   Rains that drenched the Middle Atlantic States subsided, but
flooding forced the evacuation of dozens of northern New Jersey
residents and closed three major highways in the New York City area.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell across much of the
Plains, southern Missouri, Arkansas and the southern Rockies. Rain
showers fell along the Washington state coast.
   Thunderstorms, which pounded northern Texas on Tuesday, on
Wednesday hit much of the state's midsection.
   Tornadoes were reported in Winona and near Malakoff, Athens and
Jarrell, and damaging winds struck in Frankston and near Teaseville.
   In Jarrell, a town of 1,000 people about 40 miles north of
Austin, a twister destroyed 33 houses, 12 mobile homes and 16
businesses, and damaged 39 houses, said state emergency official
David Barham.
   At least six tractor-trailer rigs overturned on nearby
Interstate 35.
   Near Round Rock almost 20 miles north of Austin, rain and high
winds tore siding off an elementary school and damaged more than a
dozen homes. The school's 400 pupils were evacuated to a high
school.
   The storms dumped 5 inches of of rain on Lake Palestine in one
hour and 4 inches in Freestone County in two hours. More than 9
inches fell in Robinson, and 2 to 4 inches were common across
central Texas.
   In Dallas, the Trinity River was more than 5 feet above flood
stage and was still rising. Police, firefighters and others
escorted people from flooding neighborhoods.
   Rising water pushed a mobile home in Village Creek downstream to
a bridge, and flooding closed I-35 in Waco and Interstate 45 in
Navarro County and roads in and out of Blum. Homes in Corsicana had
3 feet of water, and flooding was widespread in McClennan and
Limestone counties.
   Flash flood watches remained in effect in central Texas, as well
as in southern Oklahoma and western Louisiana.
   Texas' Panhandle got golf ball-size hail southwest of Muleshoe
and in Lariat. The hail was so deep west of Muleshoe that cars
couldn't move.
   In West Palm Beach, Fla., the temperature climbed to a record 94
records. The old record for the date of 93 had was set in 1954 and
tied in 1985.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 44
degrees in Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 96 degrees in
Harlingen, McAllen and Kingsville, Texas.
   The nation's low Wednesday morning was 29 degrees in Truckee,
Calif.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across
eastern sections of the Plains states, the Mississippi Valley and
central Gulf Coast, with strong thunderstorms possible across
eastern Texas and Oklahoma, the lower Mississippi Valley and
southwest Missouri; scattered rain showers from the northern
Pacific Coast to the northern Rockies, with snow at higher
elevations; and mostly sunny skies in the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 50s and 60s along the
Pacific Coast and the northern Intermountain region; the 60s in
northern Minnesota and northwest Wisconsin, and along the New
England coast; the 90s across the central and southern Florida
Peninsula, the desert Southwest, inland California valleys and near
the Big Bend of the Rio Grande in southwest Texas; and in the 70s
and 80s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
