<FIRST>r i AM-Romania-Dissident     05-17 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Dissident,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regime Critic Beaten By Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An emigre source said Wednesday that
prominent Romanian dissident Doina Cornea was beaten by Romanian
police and told she will never get a visa for France to attend a
conference on human rights next month.
   Mrs. Cornea, 59, a historian, disappeared from public view late
last month after accusing President Nicolae Ceausescu of imposing
on his fellow Romanians a repressive and outdated brand of
communism ``which people can't endure any longer.''
   The Paris-based Romanian League of Human Rights said an
unidentified foreign diplomat spotted her on May 12 in her hometown
of Cluj, western Romania. The organization monitors human rights in
Romania.
   Mihnea Berindei, a league spokesman, said it was not clear where
she had been during the time she disappeared from her home.
   Police cars block both ends of the street where she lives in
Cluj and her telephone has been cut off, Berindei said.
   ``Cornea was beaten up by police, spat at and told she will
never get a visa for France,'' Berindei told The Associated Press
in Vienna by telephone.
   Mrs. Cornea, a former professor of French, lost her job at Cluj
University in 1983 for protesting Ceausescu's economic and cultural
policies.
   Last week, the Foreign Ministry in Paris summoned Romania's
ambassador to France, Petre Gigea, to lodge a formal complaint
about human rights abuses and to demand that Romania stop harassing
dissidents.
   A ministry official provided Gigea with a copy of a letter sent
on May 10 by French first lady Danielle Mitterrand to Ceausescu and
his wife asking for assurance Mrs. Cornea would be allowed to leave
Romania to attend the June conference in France.
   Mrs. Mitterrand, wife of President Francois Mitterrand, is
president of the France-Liberty Foundation human rights group and
sent the letter in that capacity.
   Mrs. Cornea last year called on Ceausescu to stop a huge village
demolition project intended to gain more farmland for use by
state-owned collective farms.
   In her letter to Ceausescu last month, she said, ``You humbled
the people's conscience, forcing them, through pressure and terror,
to accept lies as truth and truth as lies.''
</TEXT>
