<SECOND>AM-North-South Korea,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Accuses South of Firing at Border Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea accused South Korean troops Wednesday
of firing on a North Korean post in the demilitarized zone between
the countries.
   ``It was entirely thanks to the patience and self-restraint of
the civil policemen of our side that this incident was not expanded
into an armed conflict between the two sides,'' Pyongyang's
official Korean Central News Agency said.
   The agency's report, monitored in Tokyo, did not mention any
injuries, but said the alleged firing ``gravely threatened'' the
safety of the North Korean policemen and destroyed equipment.
   The agency said South Korean troops fired ``scores of bullets
from automatic rifles'' at a North Korean post in the Demilitarized
Zone at around 6:38 p.m. Wednesday.
   In another report, the official news agency accused the United
States of daily ``aerial espionage'' by U-2 high-altitude
reconnaissance planes.
   The agency said the U-2s were flown along the military
demarcation line between North and South Korea and that the United
States also had brought an E-3A AWACS plane into South Korea for
spying on the North.
   It said U.S. spy planes had flown 100 such reconnaissance
missions in the first half of May, or about seven per day.
   ``This shows that the U.S. imperial aggressors persistently seek
confrontation and war on the Korean peninsula,'' the KCNA report
said.
   The Communist North and capitalist South, divided since 1945,
fought a bloody war in 1950-53.
   The two sides, which technically remain at war since no peace
treaty was signed at the end of the Korean War in 1953, reportedly
have held a series of secret talks on measures to ease tensions on
the Korean peninsula.
</TEXT>
