<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     05-17 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Policemen, University Professor Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shining Path rebels allied with drug
traffickers ambushed policemen in two areas of Peru's
coca-producing jungles, killing nine and wounding 12, a government
official said Wednesday.
   Wednesday marked the ninth anniversary of the insurgency by the
Maoist rebel group, during which more than 14,000 people have been
slain.
   In Lima, three gunmen on Wednesday killed a university professor
when he left his home for work. Officials declined to say whether
the Shining Path was behind the attack. They identified the victim
as Abelardo Ludena Luque, a professor at the National Engineering
University.
   The two attacks on policemen took place Tuesday, an Interior
Ministry spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Six policemen were killed and four wounded when rebels
affiliated with drug traffickers ambushed them on a jungle highway,
the spokesman said. The attack occurred near the town of Tocache,
266 miles northeast of Lima.
   The spokesman also said three policemen were slain and eight
were wounded Tuesday when a rebel gang ambushed their vehicle as it
approached a bridge near the city of Tingo Maria, 240 miles
northeast of Lima.
   Tocache and Tingo Maria are in the heart of Peru's coca-growing
region, which is estimated to harvest about half of the world's
coca.
   The plant is semi-processed and then flown from clandestine
airstrips to Colombia, where it is refined into cocaine for sale in
the United States and Europe.
   The Shining Path began its insurgency on May 17, 1980 by burning
election material in the Andean province of Ayacucho. The attack
came on the eve of elections that put an end to 12 years of
military dictatorship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
