<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovak-Romania     05-17 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak-Romania,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ceausescu, Jakes Urge No External Communist Interference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a rejection of reforms that
have changed much of the Soviet bloc, Romanian and Czechoslovak
leaders on Wednesday said each nation's Communist Party should
decide its own political course.
   The statement by Communist Party leader Milos Jakes and Romanian
President Nicolae Ceausescu was issued by the official news agency
CTK during Ceausescu's one-day visit to Prague.
   The new problems facing communism require ``the building of
relations between parties on the basis of equality, independence
and the right of each party to work out its own political line ...
without any external interference,'' the statement said.
   It signaled a rejection of reforms that have changed political
life in Poland, Hungary and the Soviet Union. It closely followed a
visit to Prague by East German leader Erich Honecker, who also has
criticized political changes begun under Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   Both Czechoslovakia and Romania have bad relations with their
neighbor Hungary, and the statement emphasized that foreign
Communist parties should not interfere in domestic affairs.
   There was no indication that Jakes had raised human rights
issues with Ceausescu, who runs the most repressive government in
the East bloc.
   The human rights group Charter 77 wrote an open letter to Jakes
before the visit urging him to discuss Romania's record, which is
increasingly attacked in the West and in Hungary.
   Czechoslovakia's ties with Hungary have soured recently over
Budapest's decision to halt work on a joint dam project and an
unprecedented Hungarian television interview with former Communist
Party leader Alexander Dubcek.
   Prague officially protested to Budapest over the decision to
halt work on the Nagymaros dam and power station on the Danube
River, demanding that the project be completed.
   Czechoslovakia has invested $1.1 billion in constructing a
nearly completed companion dam at Gabcikovo, 40 miles east of
Bratislava.
   Hungarian-Romanian relations are even more strained because of
Romania's treatment of the estimated 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians
who live on its territory.
   In January 1988, Hungary took the unprecedented step of breaking
an agreement and refusing to send home Romanian citizens who sought
refuge in Hungary. An estimated 50,000 people, mostly ethnic
Hungarians who claim discrimination in Romania, have done so.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
