<FIRST>r i AM-St.Vincent-Elections     05-17 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St. Vincent-Elections,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell Swept Back Into Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTOWN, St. Vincent (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister James Mitchell won
a second term in office and his party swept all 15 seats in this
tiny Caribbean island's parliament, election officials said
Wednesday.
   Mitchell's New Democratic Party previously held 10 of the 13
seats in Parliament, which has been expanded to 15 seats.
   The opposition St. Vincent Labor Party lost all three of its
seats, including that of its leader, Vincent Beache.
   Mitchell, 58, is a leading proponent of unity among the four
English-speaking Windward islands: St. Vincent, St. Lucia, Dominica
and Grenada.
   He vowed to give new impetus to the unity movement after his
re-election by pushing for a referendum on the issue in the four
island nations.
   Carnival-like celebrations broke out shortly after midnight when
the final results were announced.
   Mitchell, who first came to office in 1984, made Wednesday a
public holiday to celebrate his victory, and the governing party
held a rally in downtown Kingstown on Wednesday afternoon.
   Several mock funerals were staged throughout the island by
Mitchell's supporters to portray the death of the Labor Party.
   The Electoral Office said 71.8 percent of St. Vincent's 61,046
registered voters participated in Tuesday's balloting.
   The New Democrats received 66 percent of the popular vote, and
the Labor Party received 30 percent. Two tiny parties received 4
percent.
   St. Vincent, which lives mostly from banana exports, has a
population of 110,000. It gained independence from Britain in 1979.
</TEXT>
