<FIRST>u a AM-LATeachers 1stLd-Writethru a0758 05-17 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Fact-Finder to Release Report on Teachers Contract Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with fact-finder's report recommendations;
reax from teachers, school district officials; Wednesday attendance figures;
picks up 8th graf pvs: `Teachers are ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fact-finder's report Wednesday urged
striking teachers to end the 3-day-old walkout that has crippled
education for more than a half-million students in the nation's
second-largest school district.
   The report concluded the Los Angeles Unified School District's
offer ``will provide a teacher compensation package which is among
the best in Los Angeles County, the state of California and in the
entire United States.''
   The teachers had contended the district was top-heavy with
administrators and concealing it financial reserves, but the report
concluded that the district spends less on administrators and
wasn't hiding surplus funds.
   The report said the district spends only 4.95 percent of its
total expense on salaries for administrators; the average in the 20
largest unified school district's in California is 6.3 percent.
   The report was prepared by lawyer Geraldine Randall, who began
investigating the dispute last March when the 16-month contract
negotiation reached an impasse.
   She was selected jointly by the Los Angeles Unified School
District and the teachers' union, but Wayne Johnson, president of
United Teacher-Los Angeles dismissed the conclusions, saying the
author was biased against teachers.
   ``If they (district officials) stand firm, the strike will
continue,'' he said.
   School board president Roberta Weintraub said the ``totally
exonerates the board of education ... and I urge each and every
teacher to go back to work. ''
   Weintraub said 60,000 copies of the report would be printed for
the striking teachers. She urged teachers to read the report and
return to work.
   On Tuesday, district spokeswoman Diana Munatones said the report
would serve as a focal point for both sides to return to the
bargaining table.
   Fact finders ``look at all the facts, listen to the arguments of
both parties and then basically come up with a recommended
decision,'' said Dennis Batchelder of the state Public Employment
Relations Board. ``In other words it's advisory, it's not a binding
decision.''
   Weintraub and Johnson have said money was the main issue holding
up an agreement, which neither expected before Friday.
   Johnson said the number of striking teachers is growing along
with the percentage of the district's 594,000 students who are
staying away from school.
   Morning attendance reports Wednesday showed 287,750 students
present out of a possible 552,597. The district said 8,207 regular
teachers came to work, along with 10,399 certified substitutes and
administrators.
   The district said about 11,250 regular teachers came to work
Tuesday, 1,000 more than Monday.
   Striking teachers account for almost two-thirds of the
district's 32,000-member workforce. Johnson claimed 23,000
teachers, counselors, nurses and librarians were honoring the
picket lines.
   Teachers are demanding a 21 percent pay increase in two years.
They also want relief from unpaid duties such as playground patrol,
and greater control over curricula and how money is spent.
   The district most recently offered a 21.5 percent pay increase
over three years. It also has offered to set up councils at
individual schools so that teachers would have more say in setting
curricula.
   District teachers earn from $23,440 in beginning salary to
$43,319 for those with doctorates, 98 extra course units and 19
years' experience.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
