<SECOND>AM-East Germany-Soviet,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Complete Pullout Of Tank Division In East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union completed the pullout of a tank
division from East Germany on Wednesday as part of a troop
reduction plan announced by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   East Germany's state-run news agency ADN said 20 tanks were
loaded onto flatbed railroad cars for transport back to Soviet
territory.
   The pullout of the division's last regiment located near
Jueterbog is part of a plan announced by Gorbachev in December
under which 50,000 troops and 5,000 tanks are to be withdrawn from
Eastern Europe.
   In all, 10,000 Soviet soldiers, 4,000 tanks and 137 aircraft are
to be removed from East Germany by the end of 1990.
   ADN said Wednesday was the deadline for removing all the
regiment's type T-64 tanks.
