<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government hospitals in New Delhi and
four other cities turned away thousands of people Wednesday,
accepting only emergency cases because of a strike by junior
doctors.
   Feroze Begum, a diabetic, said she traveled more than 12 miles
``in the hot sun to get a refill of my prescription, but there is
no doctor to authorize it'' at the Ram Manohar Lohia hospital.
   At least 3,500 doctors at New Delhi's 11 government hospitals
began a strike Tuesday after talks with Health Ministry officials
broke down. They were joined by more than 1,400 at hospitals at
Chandigarh, Pondicherry, Banaras and Aligarh.
   Nearly all the strikers are residents. Senior doctors are
handling emergency cases.
   Striking doctors demand a raise of about $53 in monthly pay that
ranges from $200 to $270 and want monthly compensation for not
conducting private practice raised from $16 to $40.
   Dr. Rohit Parashar, a strike leader, said the doctors had
received no communication from the government since the deadlock
Monday night.
   Hospitals generally were turning away half the people who
arrived for tratment.
   Only 588 beds were occupied at the 1,493-bed Lok Nayak
Jayaprakash Narayan hospital, New Delhi's largest. Lok Nayak and
the other hospitals discharged most of their patients Monday night
after negotiations failed.
