<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-UN     05-17 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-UN,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Irish Peacekeepers Wounded in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Irish soldiers from the U.N. peacekeeping
force in southern Lebanon were wounded Wednesday when a tank from
an Israeli-backed militia fired on their headquarters, U.N.
spokesman Timor Goksel said.
   He said the two were taken to a U.N. hospital in fair condition.
   Ireland has a 700-man battalion in the 5,800-member U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon.
   Goksel said a tank belonging to the South Lebanon Army militia
fired four shells at an Irish-patrolled area and one struck ``Camp
Shamrock,'' the Irish battalion's headquaters in Tibnine village,
wounding two soldiers.
   The site is two miles north of Israel's security zone, a buffer
set up in 1985 to protect Israel's northern settlements. Foreign
reports have said 1,500 Israeli soldiers patrol the strip with the
2,000-man South Lebanon Army.
   An Israeli army spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed the milita fired on the U.N. position, wounding the
Irishmen, but said it did so after guerrillas hiding near Irish
headquarters shot at a South Lebanon Army base.
   The national Itim news agency said guerrillas fired
rocket-propelled grenades and machine guns. It said militia
commander Gen. Antoine Lahd apologized to the peacekeepers and said
he would investigate.
   Goksel said no firing came from the Irish base and that the
attack was unprovoked.
</TEXT>
