<FIRST>u i AM-CostaRica-Hull     05-17 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Hull,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Against Hull Dropped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS A. SANDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court dropped charges against
American-born rancher who has been linked to the Nicaraugan rebel
supply network, one of his attorneys said Wednesday.
   John Hull was jailed Jan. 13 on charges of drug trafficking and
violating Costa Rican security. He was freed in early March after
he posted $37,000 bail, pending his trial.
   While in jail, the 69-year-old Hull had a heart attack and was
hospitalized for three weeks.
   Defense attorney Juan Jose Sobrado said the ruling by a Superior
Penal Court judge in Alajuela, just outside the capital, annulled
an earlier ruling by another court in San Carlos, about 100 miles
to the north.
   Sobrado said the Alajuela judge reportedly cited a lack of
evidence when annulling the earlier San Carlos ruling, which
ordered Hull jailed. The charges originally were filed in Alajuela,
but the case was later moved to San Carlos.
   Hull, of Evansville, Ind., has lived in Costa Rica for 20 years
and owns a ranch in San Carlos. His lawyers say he became a Costa
Rican citizen eight years ago.
   U.S. congressional witnesses have said Hull's ranch in Costa
Rica was a transshipment point for guns headed to the rebels in
Nicaragua and cocaine destined for the United States.
   Hull has denied any role in the illegal drug trade and said his
support of the Contra rebels was a patriotic gesture.
   Another attorney for Hull, Rita Herrera, said she had not
received an official copy of the court's ruling as of late
Wedensday.
   ``Officially we don't know anything, but we hope to have the
official ruling tommorrow,'' Herrera said in a telephone interview.
   Court officials in Alajuela could not be reached by telephone
for comment late Wednesday.
   Herrera said Hull's case probably would be rejudged by the San
Carlos court.
   ``It will start all over again,'' she said. ``But we are happy
for what we have achieved up to now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
