<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv19   05-17 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 19,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs May 19, or thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television journalist Bill Moyers says he sees
evidence of a powerful spiritual stirring in the world that makes
religion the key ``story of the next 50 years.''
   He told the annual convention of the Religious Public Relations
Council that the search for faith, meaning and values represents a
major challenge to the news media.
   Citing a record response to a series he did on the ``Power of
Myth,'' he said he now is focusing more on spiritual issues than on
politics or international affairs.
   ``It's the biggest story of the millennium,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Methodist Bishop Jack M. Tuell of
Los Angeles was installed as president of the denomination's
council of bishops at its May meeting here to serve for a one-year
term.
   He succeeds Bishop Ernest T. Dixon Jr. of San Antonio, Texas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty-three Roman Catholic priests who gave
their lives in service to their country as military chaplains are
honored in a monument to their memory in Arlington National
Cemetery.
   The monument is being dedicated on Sunday. The priest-casualties
included 70 in World War II, six in Korea and seven in Vietnam.
Among them, 68 were Army chaplains, 14 Navy and one Air Force.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent poll in Israel found that 61 percent of
the people oppose legal changes advocated by Orthodox leaders that
would bar admission under the Law of Return to Conservative and
Reform converts to Judaism.
   The poll of 1,096 Israelis, conducted for the American Jewish
Committee by the Smith Research Center, a leading Israeli polling
organization, also found that 51 percent say Reform and
Conservative rabbis should have the same status in marriages,
divorce and conversion that Orthodox rabbis now have.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 members of the National Religious
Broadcasters have not affirmed its new standards on ethics and
financial integrity, according to syndicated religion columnist
Michael McManus.
   Only 70 members have done so, he says. In addition, he writes,
the Internal Revenue Service is investigating 23 media evangelists,
six of them prominent television preachers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NOTRE DAME, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gift of $33 million has been given to
the University of Notre Dame, the largest it has ever received, by
a businessman-alumnus, Edward J. DeBartolo of Youngstown, Ohio.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II and the Archbishop of
Canterbury Robert Runcie, leader of world Anglicanism, have traded
some more arguments about ordaining women.
   Letters between the two prelates were released at a meeting here
of the primates of Anglican branches in 27 nations.
   Runcie had written the pope, urging study of the ordination
issue on an ecumenical basis, saying it hasn't even been tried and
expressing hope it would be carried out with ``trust and mutual
respect.''
   The pope said ordination of women in some parts of Anglicanismn
seems to ``effectively block'' mutual recognition of ministries,
since Roman Catholicism and Eastern Orthodoxy are ``firmly
opposed'' to it.
   However, the pope emphasized the ``strong bond of communion by
which we are already united'' and their mutual commitment to
increasing that bond.
</TEXT>
