<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0706EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Rogers Adv18   05-17 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Rogers, Adv 18,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday PMs, May 18, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kenny Rogers Says `Planet Texas' Has Great Possibilities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor-singer Kenny Rogers believes he's found
a theme in the song about cowboys in space, ``Planet Texas,'' that
will become as fruitful as his song-turned-movie ``The Gambler.''
   His $600,000 video of ``Planet Texas,'' a high-tech Western,
will have its debut on his NBC special Saturday. The special was
taped at a concert with Dolly Parton and Willie Nelson at the
Johnson Space Center in Houston. It's called ``Kenny, Dolly and
Willie: Something Inside So Strong.''
   The song, written by John Andrew Parks III, is also the lead
tune on Rogers' new album, ``Something Inside So Strong.'' The
video, which is loaded with special effects, was directed by Julien
Temple, who directed the current movie ``Earth Girls Are Easy.''
   ``The Gambler,'' an earlier Rogers hit song, was expanded into
three highly successful television movies.
   ``It's the most unique piece of music I've heard in 20 years,''
Rogers said of ``Planet Texas.'' ``It may be a new genre. It has to
do with space and time travel, but it's also a Western. These alien
cowboys pick me up and take me to a planet called Texas.
   ``We may do this as a movie for NBC, but we're also toying with
the idea of trying to attract a Steven Spielberg or George Lucas
and making it a feature film. It's such an unusual concept and
offers the same limitless possibilities that `The Gambler' did.
   ``It's easy to find projects,'' said Rogers. ``It's hard to find
projects that allow you do things that are unique and have no
comparisons. If I do any kind of acting my acting is questioned.
I'm not an actor. If I do something unique people get caught up in
it and are less apt to scrutinize my work.
   ``This is uncharted territory. There's nothing to compare it to.
My own philosophy has been that if you give us a little success
we'll make it a big deal. We did that with `Lucille' and we did it
with `The Gambler.' This can be a whole new career move.''
   He said ``Planet Texas'' was brought to his attention after
Parks was turned down for a record contract by Capitol Records.
   ``I was offered this terrific song and recorded it,'' he said.
``Then Capitol signed Parks to a contract. The only bad news is
that he has his own album coming out and I won't get his new songs.
This kid can sing. But it worked out good for him. He never could
have gotten a $600,000 video done.''
   Rogers had just flown to Los Angeles that morning from his
1,200-acre farm near Athens, Ga. He talked about the special before
going to NBC for an appearance on ``The Tonight Show.'' Afterward,
he planned to give a concert at a private party in Palm Desert,
then fly back to Georgia.
   He and his wife, Marianne, and his son, Christopher, 7, moved to
the farm two years ago. But, with his own private jet, he makes
regular jaunts for concerts, commercials, movies, charity
appearances and to look after his many investments. He's building
his own 18-hole golf course on the farm.
   ``I may sell the whole thing,'' he said. ``I'm basically a
builder. The fun is creating it, not living in it. I've overbuilt
every house I've had. It keeps me creatively busy.''
   Plans for Rogers' syndicated talk show have been pushed back to
1990. His manager, Ken Kragen, believes that by then, viewer and
advertiser rebellion against so-called ``trash'' television will
open up a market for late-afternoon shows.
   Rogers has also signed a new two-year contract to do commercials
for Dole, which also feature his wife and young son. Some of the
commercials were filmed on the island of Lanai, in Hawaii, which is
owned by Dole. Rogers is building a new home on the island.
   An older son, Kenny Rogers Jr., is also a singer and a host on
the ``Channel One'' program that is shown in schools.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   `CHINA BEACH' WINS NURSING GROUP'S PRAISE _ Nurses' groups have
complained about the cheesecake portrayal of nursing students in
NBC's ``Nightingales,'' but the American Association of Colleges of
Nursing has good things to say about the way nurses are depicted in
ABC's ``China Beach.'' The Vietnam-set series offers ``positive
depictions of nurses that will aid recruitment efforts as the
nation works to alleviate its acute shortage of registered
nurses,'' says the AACN. The group sent its praise May 2 in a
letter to executive producer John Sacret Young, saying the series
might be set two decades ago, ``but its relevance is present-day.''
A copy of the letter also went to ABC Entertainment President
Robert Iger.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs PMs, May 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
