<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-Short Adv02-04   05-17 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Short, Adv 02-04,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, June 2-4, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Martin Short HBO Special Looks at Hollywood</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Short insists that his HBO special
``I, Martin Short, Goes Hollywood'' is actually a salute to
Tinseltown, not a send-up.
   But perhaps that's fatuous entertainer Jackie Rogers Jr. talking.
   In the show, Short insists it is ``a celebration of Hollywood
done with style and class and proving once and for all that you can
do art in this town.''
   Oh, but that sounds so very much like something earnest Ed
Grimley would say.
   ``Hollywood is fun,'' said Short as himself, not as either of
his many alter egos. ``It's great fodder for satire, goodness
knows. People are obsessed with it. If someone had told me 10 years
ago there would be a nightly newscast devoted entirely to
entertainment, I wouldn't have believed it.
   ``The audience has become very sophisticated. My mother-in-law
will call from Toronto and tell me the box office grosses of my
latest picture. People in the Midwest will get the inside jokes in
this special.''
   The one-hour special premieres Saturday. Short is joined by
Christopher Guest and Tracey Ullman and Short's former SCTV
colleagues Joe Flaherty, Catherine O'Hara and Dave Thomas.
   ``When I do these shows, I put a lot of time and energy into
them,'' Short said. ``It's not a cakewalk. I have to find the time.
Like my work for `SCTV' and `Saturday Night Live,' I tend to
overwrite and strain the budget.
   ``I'd just finished a picture and was wrapping up my Saturday
morning animated series, `The Completely Mental Misadventures of Ed
Grimley.' I'd work on the script for the special for a while, then
put it away. I'd kept a loose thread to it at all times.''
   In the special, Short plays song-and-dance man Dale O'Day,
struggling actor Lawrence Orbach, gossip columnist Tony Soren,
insufferable albino singer Jackie Rogers Jr., and, of course, the
tensely optimistic Ed Grimley.
   The skit as the gossip columnist was completely improvised with
Guest.
   Short said Jackie Rogers Jr., a character he developed on
``SCTV'' as one of the gushing guests on ``The Sammy Maudlin
Show,'' is a ``grotesque character who symbolizes everything that's
bad about show business. When he tries to be deep, he's merely
pompous. You want somebody to punch him in the head or throw a pie
in his face.''
   Ed Grimley was originated onstage at Second City. ``He's a
conglomeration of people I've known,'' Short said. ``Ed maintains
himself with a spirit of enthusiasm. He runs a gamut of emotions in
five minutes. He's like a guy smelling the roses after a heart
attack, except he hasn't had a heart attack.''
   Short, whose latest movie is ``Three Fugitives,'' has a film
development deal with Disney Studios.
   ``It's hard to find something that's good and something that you
haven't done,'' he said. ``I'm also looking at a Broadway musical.
The ideal career for me would be able to do a TV special, a movie
and a play every year. When I was an actor in Canada, you didn't do
just one medium. You did everything and it broadened you.''
   Short moved his home from Toronto to Los Angeles last year. ``I
always had a home here and a home in Toronto,'' he said. ``We've
got two children and two years ago we were flying back for
Christmas and the kids were screaming. I thought, why are we doing
this? For our value system. If you're not from L.A., it can be very
healthy to live elsewhere. This is the war zone and you go home to
rest. But the reality is I no longer felt it was necessary to go
home.''
   He's married to Nancy Dolman, who was Gilda Radner's understudy
when Short and Radner were doing ``Godspell.''
   Short was born in Hamilton, Ontario, where he said he grew up
watching Lucille Ball, Dick Van Dyke and Jackie Gleason.
   ``Those were the three big influences when I was young,'' he
said. ``I was fascinated by the way Gleason could play Ralph
Kramden and be so real. ... It always amazed me how far you could
go within the reality. A character without any reality is pretty
dull.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 2-4</NOTE>
