<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-17 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0821</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crush of higher interest rates forced new
housing construction down for the third straight month in April,
the government reported in yet another sign that the economic
slowdown is hitting home.
   Residential construction starts dropped 2.7 percent last month
from March's rate to their lowest level in more than six years as
an upturn in the building of single-family homes was overshadowed
by a big drop in new work on apartments, the Commerce Department
reported Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing prices skyrocketed in California in
the first three months of 1989 despite rising mortgage interest
rates, but markets cooled in the Northeast, a real estate trade
group said.
   Meanwhile, home prices in many Midwestern industrial cities
posted healthy appreciation rates and real estate in oil-producing
states showed a spotty recovery, the National Association of
Realtors said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deal that would have created the world's largest
gold company collapsed after a New York judge refused to lift an
order blocking South Africa-controlled Minorco S.A. from acquiring
Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   Minorco Chief Executive Sir Michael Edwardes said Tuesday his
company's bid would lapse Wednesday after U.S. District Court Judge
Michael Mukasey maintained an injunction barring Minorco from
buying more Gold Fields shares.
   Luxembourg-based Minorco is the world's largest gold producer in
the non-communist world and Gold Fields is second.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Ogilvy Group Inc. said he
investigated every reasonable alternative but could not find
anything to beat WPP Group PLC's record $864 million buyout offer
for the advertising giant.
   Kenneth Roman, Ogilvy's chairman, said Tuesday he also was
confident there would be few if any client defections in the wake
of the buyout agreement reached late Monday, under which Ogilvy's
board unanimously approved WPP's proposal for a $54 a share tender
offer for all of Ogilvy's stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal bankruptcy examiner for Eastern
Airlines said there are no ``real live offers'' to buy the crippled
carrier and challenged suitors who have made proposals to ``put up
or shut up'' and put at least $100 million in cash on the table.
   Meanwhile Tuesday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland said
Eastern has provided valid reasons for its plan to sell its prized
Northeast shuttle service. Eastern already has an agreement to sell
the shuttle to developer Donald Trump for $365 million, but Lifland
gave the airline until Monday to consider a higher bid by America
West Airlines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employers who project worker absenteeism
through race, gender or age comparisons are making invalid
assumptions as well as discriminating, a researcher said.
   While simple comparisons of the absentee rates of men and women,
for example, would show women miss work slightly more than men, a
variety of other variables make such information useless to an
employer trying to determine if a given job applicant is likely to
have a poor attendance record, said the study released Tuesday by
the National Chamber Foundation, the research arm of the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp., driving
to overcome the incompatibility of its computers, announced a major
package of software that will run the same way on IBM machines of
all sizes.
   Analysts described OfficeVision, introduced Tuesday, as an
important part of IBM's attempt to duplicate and go beyond the
successful strategies of rivals such as Digital Equipment Corp. and
Apple Computer Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp resurgence in commercial banking helped
the nation's 500 largest service companies post an aggregate 55
percent profit rise in 1988, according to an annual Fortune
magazine ranking.
   Fortune's survey of non-industrial companies, released Tuesday,
also found service exports far outpacing imports as U.S. companies
in 1988 as American companies sold an estimated $70 billion in
advertising, auto insurance and other services to foreigners.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employers' failure to withhold taxes from
paychecks of workers who are erroneously carried on the books as
``independent contractors'' is costing the federal treasury
billions of dollars, government auditors said.
   In 1984 alone, the General Accounting Office said Tuesday in
testimony to the House Government Operations consumer subcommittee,
the loss was nearly $1.6 billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled back Tuesday after two strong sessions. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up nearly 82 points on Monday
and Friday, lost 10.44 points to 2,453.45.
   The dollar finished higher against the French franc and Italian
lira but slightly lower against other major currencies. Bond prices
closed mostly higher.
   Grain and soybean futures prices; copper prices continued to
slide, livestock and meat prices were mostly lower, energy and
precious metals futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
