<DOCNO> AP890517-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0237EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Service500     05-17 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Service 500,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fortune's 500 Non-Industrial Companies Post 55 Percent Profit Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's top 500 service companies provided
the ``all-purpose sweating'' for an industrial boom and posted
aggregate profits of $73.8 billion last year, a Fortune magazine
survey says.
   Fortune's survey of non-industrial companies said a sharp
resurgence in commercial banking also helped lift profits at the
nation's largest service companies by 55 percent over 1987.
   By contrast, the annual Fortune 500 survey of leading industrial
companies released last month showed a 27 percent rise in profits
to $115 billion among those companies.
   The report, released Tuesday for publication in the magazine's
upcoming June 5 issue, marked a rebound for service companies from
the year before, when the stock market crash and earnings problems
among unstable savings institutions contributed to a 22 percent
drop to $50.8 billion in the Service 500's profits.
   Fortune said the resurgence in the service sector was tied to
the nation's industrial boom, which required service company help
for shipping, sales ``and the all-purpose sweating to make it
work.''
   Fortune's 34th annual Service 500 survey indicated that a
turnaround by the nation's 100 largest commercial banks accounted
for most of the gain. The banks reported $17.5 billion in profits
in 1988, compared with a $5.3 billion loss the year before.
   Transportation companies, diversified services, savings
institutions and retailers on the list also showed strong gains.
   The only decline was posted by the nation's utilities, whose
profits fell 5 percent to $21.6 billion. Fortune attributed the
drop to nuclear power plant problems at several companies,
including Long Island Lighting Co., which registered more than $1
billion in losses partly because of its idle Shoreham nuclear plant.
   The top 50 transportation companies showed an aggregate 50
percent profit increase, to $5.48 billion, as airlines pulled in
higher fares and railroads hauled high tonnage to keep pace with
factories' production and export needs, Fortune stated.
   Retailers, the only bright spot in 1987 with a 16 percent profit
hike, registered a 10 percent gain last year, to $9.12 billion.
   Fortune said service industry exports exceeded imports by $7.8
billion in 1988, with a total of $70 billion in service exports
last year.
   The companies in the service survey, like Fortune 500 industrial
corporations, were ranked by sales.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. became the biggest
diversified services company with $35.2 billion in sales,
displacing Super Valu Stores, a wholesale food distributor. AT&amp;T
moved to the Service 500 from the Fortune 500 in 1988 because it
brought in more money from providing telephone service than from
manufacturing products like computers and telecommunications
equipment.
   Behind AT&amp;T were Fleming Cos., a wholesale foods distributor;
Super Valu and McKesson Corp., which is involved in wine and
spirits, chemicals, drugs and health care distribution and services.
   Citicorp, Chase Manhattan Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. remained
the top three commercial banking companies.
   The top diversified financial companies held their places.
American Express Co. was largest, followed by Federal National
Mortgage Association, Salomon Inc., Aetna Life and Casualty and
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   Among savings institutions, H.F. Ahmanson &amp; Co. was first,
followed by Great Western Financial Corp. and Calfed Inc. Last
year's leader, Financial Corp. of America, dropped from the list
after Robert Bass acquired the company's troubled American Savings
subsidiary.
   Top retailers were Sears Roebuck and Co. and K mart, followed by
Wal-Mart Stores Inc., which jumped from fifth the previous year.
   United Parcel Service swapped places with UAL, parent of United
Airlines, as the top transportation company, followed by AMR,
parent of American Airlines, CSX Corp. and Texas Air Corp., the
parent of Eastern and Continental Airlines, which fell from third
place in 1987.
   GTE Corp., Bellsouth Corp. and Nynex Corp. remained the biggest
three utilities respectively, followed by Bell Atlantic Corp. and
fast-growing US West Inc., which rose from ninth place.
</TEXT>
