<FIRST>r f PM-Minorco-GoldFields Bjt   05-17 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minorco-Gold Fields, Bjt,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Ruling Scuttles Bid To Form World's Largest Gold Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorco SA's attempt to create the world's
largest gold producer through a hostile takeover of Consolidated
Gold Fields PLC finally unraveled after months of wrangling before
U.S. judges and British market officials.
   A federal judge in Manhattan refused on Tuesday to lift his
order blocking South Africa-controlled Minorco from acquiring Gold
Fields before a $5.9 billion takeover bid was to expire.
   ``That Minorco has only until tomorrow to appeal this decision
is regrettable,'' wrote U.S. District Judge Michael B. Mukasey, who
first imposed the injunction last October on antitrust grounds.
   After Mukasey refused to stay his order pending appeal, Minorco
Chief Executive Sir Michael Edwardes said the Luxembourg-based
company, the largest gold producer in the noncommunist world, would
allow the Wednesday deadline to lapse.
   Rudolph Agnew, chief executive of Gold Fields, the
second-largest gold producer, said he was ``highly delighted'' with
the result of the battle, calling it ``a tremendous victory.''
   Last fall, Minorco, which is largely controlled by two South
African corporations _ Anglo American Corp. of South Africa and De
Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd. _ launched a hostile takeover bid for
Gold Fields. Minorco already held almost 30 percent of Gold Fields'
shares.
   Gold Fields and its U.S. subsidiary, Newmont Mining Corp., the
largest gold producer in the United States, sued in New York to
block the takeover.
   Mukasey halted the takeover bid, saying the combined entities
would control 32.3 percent of the non-communist world's gold market.
   On Tuesday, the judge said Minorco had ample time to appeal his
earlier rulings but ``for its own reasons and aware of the
onrushing dealine, Minorco chose not to do so.
   ``It should not now complain of unfair prejudice because it
chose voluntarily a strategy which now leaves little time to
appeal,'' he wrote.
   Minorco owns or has tenders for about 55 percent of Gold Fields'
shares, but Mukasey's injunction bars Minorco from buying shares it
doesn't own. The company said it would keep its position ``under
close review.''
   Britain's Panel on Takeovers and Mergers ordered Gold Fields to
drop out of the U.S. lawsuit unless it obtained shareholder
approval. Gold Fields voluntarily dropped out a week ago, leaving
Newmont as the only obstacle to the takeover. Gold Fields owns 49
percent of Newmont.
   Unless Minorco could get Newmont to withdraw its lawsuit, the
bid was to expire Wednesday under British regulations.
   In its last attempt to have the injunction lifted, Minorco
claimed Newmont lacked standing to continue the suit because it
told the British takeovers panel it was a U.S. concern not
controlled by Gold Fields.
   Minorco lawyers claimed that if Newmont was not controlled by
Gold Fields, it could not allege antitrust injury.
   Newmont originally claimed that because its U.S. operations were
more efficient than Minorco's South African mines, Minorco
eventually would shut down U.S. operations if the takeover were
accomplished.
   In upholding Mukasey's earlier rulings, a federal appeals court
said last month that ``Newmont's threatened injury is precisely the
type that the antitrust laws were designed to protect against.''
   Mukasey wrote that the premise of Minorco's argument was
incorrect.
   ``Newmont ... could suffer antitrust injury in the form of
reduced control over pricing and output as an independent
competitor if the takeover succeeded and Minorco controlled a
greater share of the world non-communist gold market,'' he wrote.
   He added that ``Newmont has standing as an independent
competitor to allege that the resulting combination of Gold Fields
and Minorco would substantially lessen competition and injure it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ogilvy-WPP Bjt   05-17 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ogilvy-WPP, Bjt,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sorrell Makes Quick Rise to Top of Ad Heap</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY103 of May 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Sorrell, the WPP Group PLC boss who is
closing in on his second record advertising buyout in three years,
makes the assembly of a world-class advertising and marketing
services empire look easy.
   The Ogilvy Group Inc. gave in late Monday to WPP's $864 million
takeover bid less than three weeks after Sorrell first proposed a
buyout to a company whose leaders admit they preferred independence.
   It appears he may have learned some valuable lessons since his
much rockier pursuit of another American advertising giant, JWT
Group Inc., for what was then a record price of $566 million in
1987.
   In getting the Ogilvy board to agree to the buyout quickly,
securities analysts say Sorrell may have avoided offending clients
who tend to get upset if they feel their ad agency's top management
is preoccupied with a messy takeover fight rather than minding the
client's business.
   And he may have scored points with Ogilvy employees by saying he
intended to keep Ogilvy and its management intact and wanted to
have them run Ogilvy autonomously from the former JWT Group's J.
Walter Thompson agency.
   Ogilvy founder David Ogilvy, reported to be vehemently opposed
to Sorrell's overtures initially, was offered and accepted the post
of chairman of WPP. Ogilvy Chairman Kenneth Roman stays on in that
post.
   In addition, Sorrell said he was leaving to Ogilvy and the
managers of its Scali, McCabe, Sloves Group agency the resolution
of whether the employees will be allowed to buy Scali McCabe.
   A little more than a year ago, six top executives of the Lord
Geller Federico Einstein agency that was part of JWT Group walked
out, leaving a still unresolved legal tangle after Sorrell refused
to let them buy the agency.
   ``This will not be another Lord Geller,'' Roman told reporters
on Tuesday, referring to the Scali McCabe matter.
   Ogilvy's board backed WPP's plan to launch a tender offer of $54
a share for all of Ogilvy's stock.
   The agreement, reached late Monday gives WPP another famous
advertising brand name with a list of blue chip clients like
American Express Co., American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and Sears,
Roebuck and Co.
   The purchase will elevate WPP, which placed third among the
world's advertising and marketing services companies in 1988, to
second place with $13.5 billion in billings, a shade behind
industry leader Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC, where Sorrell once worked.
   Nonetheless, Sorrell said quality rather than quantity has been
his objective in building WPP.
   At a news conference and in remarks to Ogilvy shareholders on
Tuesday, Ogilvy's Roman said he had investigated every reasonable
alternative but could not find anything to beat WPP's all-cash
buyout offer.
   He said management considered ``everything from white knights to
white squires to recapitalization to leveraged buyouts.'' He
declined to identify an potential suitors.
   Roman said he was confident there would be few if any client
defections in the wake of the buyout agreement.
   Some analysts have said WPP's acquisition of Ogilvy could prompt
some advertisers to take their business elsewhere. Thompson works
for Eastman Kodak Co., for instance, while Ogilvy works for rival
Polaroid Corp.
   Sorrell had proposed a friendly buyout at $45 a share in late
April, sweetened the proposal to $50 a share early last week and
boosted it to $54 a share this past weekend.
   Ogilvy stock closed at $32 a share the day before WPP's initial
proposal was disclosed. Ogilvy closed at $53.12{ a share Tuesday,
down 12{ cents from Monday's close.
   Burt Manning, who heads J. Walter Thompson, said he welcomed
Ogilvy's addition to WPP and said the buyout ``improves WPP's
chances for competing in the marketplace.''
   He said Thompson would nonetheless compete fiercely with
Ogilvy's main agency, Ogilvy &amp; Mather Worldwide, for clients.
</TEXT>
