<FIRST>r f PM-CNW-Japonica     05-17 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CNW-Japonica,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>CNW Management Hopes To Join Buyout Bidding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto CX4 of May 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japonica Partners says it is confident it
received substantial support from CNW shareholders in a proxy
contest, but the results won't be known for at least a week.
   Meanwhile, CNW's chairman said Tuesday that the railroad
company's management hoped to assemble a buyout bid to top
Japonica's $722 million offer.
   CNW Chairman Robert Schmiege announced managment's plans at the
company's annual meeting while Japonica, a New York-based investor
group, began a $44-a-share hostile tender offer for CNW's common
stock.
   At the meeting, shareholders were asked to vote to either retain
CNW's seven directors or replace them with a slate of Japonica
nominees.
   Japonica said it was confident its slate won substantial
shareholder support, but the group was disturbed by what it called
CNW's ``contradictory actions.''
   Japonica said CNW purported to be seeking competing bids for the
company while at the same time trying to persuade public officials
to intervene on behalf of the company.
   Schmiege denied that he or other company officials had pressed
federal or state officials to step into the battle between his
company and Japonica.
   Schmiege dropped his bombshell near the end of the annual
meeting when asked by a shareholder to explain management's role in
CNW's ongoing search for prospective buyers.
   ``The management group has been in active discussions _
discussions that were interrupted only to come over to this meeting
_ with an equity partner, with banks, with a subordinated debt
player and with an outside player, all of whom's cooperation and
participation is necessary for us to make a bid,'' Schmiege said.
   ``We are reasonably optimistic that we will succeed in this
effort and will be in a position to make a competing bid,'' he told
the approximately 300 shareholders attending the meeting.
   At a news conference later, Schmiege said he hoped to announce a
management bid within a week. He declined to identify any of the
parties participating in the discussions.
   CNW's stock closed Tuesday at $43.87{, up 12{ cents on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Japonica spokesman C. Howard Hardesty, who would become CNW's
chairman if his group succeeds, said Japonica would welcome any
competing bids but that he hopes CNW's board would set a deadline
for offers.
   In a speech to shareholders, Hardesty said Japonica intends to
sell CNW's real estate, excess equipment and Chicago-area commuter
lines to partially recoup buyout costs, but it is committed to
running CNW's core railroad freight business.
   ``This is an operating group, not a buy-and-sell group,'' said
Hardesty, a former president and chief executive of Purolater
Courier Corp.
   In another development, the Interstate Commerce Commission told
Congress Tuesday that it would continue to examine the possibility
of asserting jurisdiction over any non-railroad takeover of CNW.
But the ICC said any attempt to assert jurisdiction over such a
buyout would ``result in litigation in which the commission's
chances of success are questionable.''
   CNW is the parent of the Chicago and Northwestern Transportation
Co., a 6,000-mile railroad with 8,500 employees that operates in
nine states, most of them in the Midwest.
   CNW also operates Western Railroad Properties, a coal-hauling
franchise in Wyoming's Powder River Basin that Schmiege called
``the most profitable 200 miles of railroad in the country.''
   Japonica has identified the coal-hauling business as one of the
assets that attracted it to CNW.
</TEXT>
