<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-InsiderTrading     05-17 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insider Trading,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Charges Insider Trading Ring In Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The temptation to share inside information about a
corporate takeover apparently proved too much for a 24-year-old
paralegal at a prestigious law firm, the Securities and Exchange
Commission says.
   In a civil complaint filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court in
Boston, the SEC charged that Kerry A. Hurton handled confidential
papers about plans for a $230 million buyout of a southern
department store chain while she was working in the Boston office
of Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &amp; Flom in 1987.
   By passing information about the takeover to friends and
acquaintances, the SEC said, Ms. Hurton prompted at least five
people to buy a total of 65,020 shares of stock in the Birmingham,
Ala., chain of Parisian Inc. at an average price of $18 a share in
June and July 1987.
   When a buyout by Hooker Corp. was announced later that summer,
Parisian's stock shot up to more than $30 a share, the SEC said.
   The complaint seeks to force the defendants to return alleged
profits of $823,825 and pay up to three times that amount in
penalties. Lawyers for the defendants said they maintain they did
nothing wrong.
   Attorney John Wall, who represents Ms. Hurton, said she has
agreed to sign a consent decree in which she does not acknowledge
any past wrongdoing but agrees to refrain from passing inside
information in the future.
   ``I had asked the SEC to file the consent decree simultaneously
with the complaint,'' Wall said. ``But apparently they want the
publicity to be one-sided.''
   The SEC said Ms. Hurton worked for Skadden, Arps, a leading New
York law firm, from October 1986 to July 1988. During that time,
the firm represented Hooker, an Australian retailing and real
estate company.
   Peter P. Mullen, an executive partner in the 970-lawyer firm,
said Skadden, Arps cooperated with the SEC probe and suspended Ms.
Hurton in May 1988 ``as soon as we learned she was under serious
suspicion.'' He added that she was fired a few weeks later ``when
she refused to cooperate'' with the SEC investigation.
   ``From our point of view, we feel aggrieved, because in effect
she appropriated information she shouldn't have and flagrantly
violated our policies _ if in fact the charges are correct,'' he
said.
   Hooker completed the acquisition of Parisian for $30.65 a share,
or a total of about $230 million, in April 1988. Mullen said he did
not believe the insider trading had any effect on the deal.
Parisian has 16 stores in Alabama, Texas, Georgia and Florida.
   The SEC's year-long investigation was sparked by a tip from ``a
private individual'' said John Sturc, the agency's associate
director for enforcement in Washington.
   In its complaint, the SEC said Ms. Hurton passed the information
to a ``close personal friend,'' Eric Laboz of New York City, and
his former roommate at Boston University, Jonathan R. Beck of North
Hills, N.Y.
   In addition, Ms. Hurton allegedly gave the information to two
real estate investors, Bruce E. Maurice of Danvers and Sheldon M.
Stone of Marblehead, who in July 1987 gave her an $8,500 loan
secured by a second mortgage on a condominium unit sold to her by
Maurice, the SEC said.
   ``There was an initial price agreed on, and subsequently the
financing terms were changed in a way to make it easier for her to
buy the apartment,'' Sturc said. ``You have to draw your own
implications'' about whether the loan was a payoff for the
information, he added.
   Stephen Delinsky, attorney for Maurice and Stone, said they are
``sophisticated investors'' who chose Parisian stock without any
inside information.
   ``There is nothing wrong with buying stock and making money on
it, and there isn't a shred of evidence they did anything more than
that,'' Delinsky said.
   The SEC complaint charges that Sheldon Stone gave the stock tip
to his brother, Bernard Stone of Norwell, Mass., a supervisory
deputy U.S. marshal in Boston. Bernard Stone then advised five
people to buy the stock, but they have not been charged with
knowingly trading on inside information, the SEC said.
   Phone calls to Ms. Hurton's home in Boston were not returned
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Mrs.B-Mart     05-17 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mrs. B-Mart,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rose Blumkin Wants Back Into Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a week after Rose Blumkin announced
she quit Nebraska Furniture Mart in a spat with her grandsons, the
95-year-old Russian immigrant wants a piece of the business she
founded 52 years ago.
   ``I would buy it in a minute,'' Blumkin said of the carpet
department of the Furniture Mart, the nation's largest furniture
store at a single location with 300,000 square feet of retail space.
   ``I would pay him a high price,'' she said referring to Omaha
investor Warren Buffett, whose Berkshire Hathaway Inc. bought 90
percent of the store in 1983. ``Five million, $8 million, whatever
it takes,'' she said.
   Otherwise, Mrs. Blumkin said she'd be willing to manage the
carpet department for Buffett _ without any direction from each of
the two grandsons she has been know to refer to as ``Hitler.''
   Buffett paid $55 million for his stake in Furniture Mart, but
Mrs. Blumkin retained the title of chairwoman and remained a
fixture on the sales floor, selling carpeting and furniture from
atop her motorized golf cart.
   If Buffett hired her as carpet manager, she vowed to reimburse
him for any losses.
   Either as an owner or manager, Mrs. Blumkin said she wants ``to
show how a business should run . . . That's my point.''
   Mrs. Blumkin, popularly known as ``Mrs. B,'' hasn't talked to
Buffett since she walked out of the store May 3. She announced last
week she quit the business because her authority as carpet
department head had been undermined and she couldn't work with her
two grandsons.
   The two are Ronald, 40, Furniture Mart president and chief
executive, and Irvin, 37, vice president. They are the sons of
Louie Blumkin, 69, vice chairman.
   Because of the way the deal with Buffett was structured, Louie
Blumkin's family has increased its ownership to 20 percent with
Berkshire Hathaway retaining 80 percent. If Mrs. Blumkin can't talk
Buffett into agreeing to either of those plans, she said she might
set up a new wholesale carpet business and run it out of a vacant
warehouse she owns directly north of the Furniture Mart.
   Such a company, which would sell mainly to small furniture
stores and apartment house owners as well as to consumers, would
put her in competition with her former store, she admitted.
   The goal isn't to make money, Mrs. Blumkin said. She would pay
sales people commissions and share profits with them while donating
additional profits to charity.
   Mrs. Blumkin, who typically put in 60- to 70-hour weeks on the
job, said she doesn't know what to do with herself without work.
   The Furniture Mart's sales of furniture, carpets and appliances
reached $152.5 million last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SwissTourism     05-17 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swiss Tourism,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tourism Head Wants Geneva To Liven Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CYRIL TUOHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats and other negotiators from all over the
world constantly fill up Geneva's hotels and restaurants, but
ordinary tourists apparently find the place dull.
   Tourism in Geneva has been falling since 1984 and Olivier Vodoz,
head of the Geneva tourist office, believes it's time to liven
things up.
   ``Geneva must provide non-stop cultural, artistic, and athletic
events,'' he said. ``We have to organize large concerts, both
classical and rock, which will attract young people.''
   He thinks the city of 160,000 permanent residents suffers from
its staid image.
   ``Seventy percent of the people who are considered tourists are
either businessmen, representatives to international organizations,
or delegates attending conferences,'' he said. ``The other 30
percent are people simply passing through.''
   With 270 restaurants _ many of them catering to the
expense-account crowd _ a tourist office pamphlet describes Geneva
as ``one of the world's gastronomic capitals.'' But most prices are
out of reach for the backpack crowd. Geneva also has 39 discos and
night clubs but many require membership.
   Vodoz noted that chronic traffic congestion dissuades motorist
travelers from stopping in Geneva, which has one of the world's
highest automobile densities. In order to allviate that problem,
the city is increasing its number of parking places.
   High hotel prices _ $225 a night for a single at a plush
lakeside hotel _ also are listed as contributing to the decline in
tourist business in continental Europe's second most expensive
city, trailing Copenhagen, Denmark.
   ``With the help of the hoteliers we have made efforts to try to
reduce prices but we can still do more,'' Vodoz said.
   Some relief is expected from the recent weakening of the Swiss
franc against the dollar and other major currencies, and tourist
officials hope the forecasts of higher crude oil prices will mean a
return of free-spending Arabs.
   But while it attempts to attract more tourists, Geneva will
definitely not change its cityscape, Vodoz said.
   ``As a result the city may appear less exciting or dynamic than
other cities. We will never become a Hong Kong or a Monaco.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     05-17 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was stronger in early European
trading today ahead of this morning's scheduled release of U.S.
trade figures for March. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said trading was calm with most market
participants waiting for the trade figures to push the dollar up or
down.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose for the fifth consecutive trading day,
closing up 0.70 yen at 137.70 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted
at 137.60 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9448 West German marks, up from 1.9426; 1.7405
Swiss francs, up from 1.7360; 6.5825 French francs, up from 6.5685;
2.1911 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1820; 1,416.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,408.75; 1.1907 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1892.
   In London, one pound cost $1.6353 compared with $1.6398 late
Tuesday.
   Gold prices hovered in a narrow range and bullion dealers said
the market continues to lack enough volume to push prices one way
or another.
   Gold opened in London at $373.75 a troy ounce, compared with
late Tuesday's $374.25. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $373.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $373.95 compared with $374.40 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.25 to close at $374.74.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.51 a troy ounce, down from
Tuesday's $5.55.
</TEXT>
