<DOCNO> AP890517-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AlaskaVillage     05-17 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska Village,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Life in Fishing Village Uncertain Since Exxon Valdez Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY315,316,317,318,319 of May 11.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Story and photos by AP Photographer John Gaps III.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP LaserPhoto Package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TATITLEK, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one sense, this small native fishing
village was spared. Although the tanker Exxon Valdez hemorrhaged
more than 10 million gallons of crude just 5 miles from their cove,
local folks have seen little of the oil in their waters.
   In another sense, they're not so fortunate. ``It's probably
still going to get us,'' says village president Gary Kompkoff.
   ``Right now most of us would be out collecting salmon spawn,''
he said. ``But that has been canceled. We're not sure if we're
going to be able to fish at all this year. Ninety-eight percent of
the annual income of the village is fishing.''
   Tatitlek, settled in the late 1800s on the northern shore of
Prince William Sound, has 95 residents. All but 10 are Aleut
Indians, and many are Russian Orthodox, typical of this part of
Alaska.
   Tatitlek fishermen have caught salmon in Prince William Sound
for decades, but since the Exxon Valdez ran aground on Bligh Reef
on March 24, the familiar cycle of village life has been disrupted.
   ``Right now we're just trying to understand what this will mean
for us long term,'' said Kompkoff.
   The lucrative herring season has already been canceled.
   In the nearby fishing town of Cordova, loss of the herring catch
will cost $12 million. But Cordova fisherman are making up some of
the loss with income from working booms for Exxon, gathering
remnants of the spill in their boats.
   Few of Tatitlek's fishermen have been offered such work.
   Says Kompkoff, ``We've gone from fear to anger to apprehension
over this thing. It's going to be with us for a long time to come.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 0843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NordstromPlans     05-17 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nordstrom Plans,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clothing Retailer Plans New Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 48-store Nordstrom chain is shedding its
regional focus as it seeks to establish new ``beachheads'' on the
East Coast and in the Midwest, according to the co-chairman of the
Seattle-based clothing retailer.
   At the department store company's annual meeting Tuesday, Bruce
Nordstrom said the chain will continue to expand. Nordstrom entered
the East Coast market for the first time last year with a store in
McLean, Va.
   The company plans to build 14 new stores totaling more than 2.5
million square feet of space over the next five years. Most of the
stores will be 200,000 square feet or larger, compared to an
average 110,000 square feet for existing stores.
   Among them will be the company's first in the Midwest. Nordstrom
plans a Minnesota outlet in the giant Mall of America, a
5-million-square-foot shopping mall and amusement park under
construction in Bloomington.
   At least six more stores are on the drawing boards for the
Northeast and the company plans five new California stores in
smaller markets, such as Santa Barbara.
   ``I guess we are going to continue to build stores as long as
they continue to do as well as they are doing,'' Nordstrom said.
``The sky's the limit.''
   The company ended 1988 with record sales of more than $2.3
billion and record profits of $123 million.
   Profit in Nordstrom's fiscal first quarter grew to nearly $23
million compared to $19.2 million in the same period in 1988.
   Nordstrom stores averaged sales of $380 per square foot last
year.
   ``We would guess that has got to be at the very top end of the
industry,'' Nordstrom said.
   John Nordstrom, who with his brother James and cousin Bruce
co-chair the company, said after the meeting that developers are
offering to pay the company to locate as anchor stores in planned
malls.
   ``I think it's fair to say that when you go into Minnesota and
Indiana, we got an awful good deal,'' he said, because those
markets aren't particularly hot. Nordstrom plans to open an
Indianapolis store in 1993.
   The expansion program will cost more than $500 million over the
next five years, but John Nordstrom said the company does not want
to use too much debt to finance it. Its debt-to-equity ratio was 43
percent in January, and Nordstrom said the company wants to keep
that ratio below 50 percent.
   The company issued $150 million in long-term debt last year, and
sold $1.3 million in stock to gain equity financing.
   John Nordstrom said he did not think the company would seek
additional equity or debt financing this year, preferring to fund
expansion with retained earnings.
   But additional funds could come from stock sales in the future.
Shareholders Tuesday approved a measure that would allow the
company to issue 250 million shares of stock, up from 100 million.
The provision would allow for additional stock dividends, stock
splits, acquisitions and other purposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
