<FIRST>r f PM-UpjohnMeeting     05-17 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Upjohn Meeting,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Upjohn Keeps Poison Pill; Company Not For Sale, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shareholder proposal to dissolve
Upjohn Co.'s ``poison pill'' takeover defense was withdrawn and the
company is not for sale, its chairman says.
   Theodore Cooper on Tuesday turned aside rumors that Upjohn was
up for sale based on recent heavy activity in the company's stock.
   ``I'm not an auctioneer,'' Cooper told shareholders at Upjohn's
annual meeting. ``The company is not for sale.''
   Upjohn's stock climbed 62{ cents a share on trading of 1.3
million shares Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange to close at
$32.75. There have been rumors that a European competitor has its
eye on the company.
   Two months ago, the company strengthened its takeover defense,
which allows shareholders to buy stock at half-price if any one
stockholder acquires 20 percent of the company's 185 million
outstanding shares.
   The California State Teachers Retirement System, which holds a
block of Upjohn shares, had proposed that the so-called ``poison
pill'' defense be dropped. But Cooper said the proposal was dropped
before the annual meeting after a count of proxy votes showed that
it would fail.
   Two other resolutions were defeated at the meeting. One would
have required the company to cut all ties with South Africa and the
other would have kept proxy voting confidential from company
officials.
   Also at the meeting, Upjohn President Lawrence C. Hoff said
company sales, which last year amounted to $2.2 billion, would
continue to grow if any of four pending federal applications were
approved.
   Two applications before the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
would allow use of its Xanax central nervous system medication for
panic and depression. Also pending are applications for approval of
two new products, the antibiotic Zefazone and the antidepressant
Deracyn.
</TEXT>
