<FIRST>r f BC-Exxon-Fountain     05-17 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Exxon-Fountain,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protestors Put Oil in Exxon's Fountain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil was dumped early Wednesday into a dry
fountain in front of the Exxon Building in New York City's
Rockefeller Center.
   ``It was a very small amount, and we're cleaning it up,'' said
center spokesman Vince Silvestri. He said the puddle appeared to
have been motor oil and that the center had no information about
its origin.
   A caller identifying himself only as an Alaskan told The
Associated Press at 5 a.m. that he and a fellow Alaskan had dumped
50 gallons of oil in the Exxon fountain.
   They did it so that Exxon executives ``might feel a little
closer to the story'' of the oil spill in Alaska, he said, and ``to
protest that it's taking a long time to clean up.''
   The spill from the Exxon-owned oil tanker Exxon Valdez occurred
on March 24 off the coast of Valdez, Alaska.
   Silvestri said he had no estimate of how much oil was dumped
into the fountain, but said it was ``extremely considerably less
than 50 gallons.''
   The fountain has been undergoing repair and had no water in it.
