<FIRST>r f BC-Obit-Edison     05-17 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Obit-Edison,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Of Shoe-Founding Brothers Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Edison, the last survivor of five
founding brothers of Edison Brothers Stores Inc., has died. He was
89.
   Edison died Tuesday at his home in St. Louis. He was president
of the nationwide retailer of apparel and women's shoes from 1957
until 1968 and was a member of the board until his death.
   Together with his brothers _ Harry, Mark, Sam and Simon _ Edison
started Edison Brothers in 1922 in Atlanta and moved to St. Louis
in 1929.
   The brothers started shoe stores known as Chandler's, Baker's,
Leed's and Burt's. Today the firm also includes retail outlets in
shoes and and clothing known as The Wild Pair, Sacha of London,
Jeans West, Oak Tree, J. Riggings, 5-7-9 Shops and Joan Bari.
   Private services for Edison were scheduled for Thursday in St.
Louis. He is survived by a son, Bernard A. Edison of St. Louis; a
daughter, Ruth Tilsley of Santa Monica, Calif.; seven grandchildren
and one great-grandchild.
</TEXT>
