<DOCNO> AP890517-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-DeVazquez Adv21   05-17 0975</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-De Vazquez, Adv 21,1003</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday May 21 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Santa Fe Designer Rides Crest of Southwest Fashion Wave</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISABETH DUNHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Char de Vazquez once walked away from a
successful Mexican export business she created from a single animal
skin, but she didn't leave behind the flair for design that has
landed her creations in some of the finest stores from New York to
California.
   Today, her Char Designs Inc. manufactures leather and suede
clothes in New Mexico, home of the ``Southwest'' look glorified by
designer Ralph Lauren.
   Char Design items _ ranging from $33 hand-painted scarves to
$1,800 suede and velvet fox-trimmed opera jackets _ have been a
fashion standard for the last decade. All of the skirts, blouses,
jackets and other items created by de Vazquez and her staff of four
designers are made with lamb skin imported from New Zealand and
dyed in Britain. Many are hand-painted with detailed designs.
   They are found in Saks Fifth Avenue, Bonwit Teller, Lord &amp;
Taylor and Neiman Marcus. Notables from Sam Shepard and Robert
Redford to Johnny Cash and Ronald Reagan have been seen wearing the
buttery-soft shirts and jackets. Musician Joni Mitchell, ``Dallas''
star Linda Gray, and newswoman Maria Shriver also are past
customers.
   Overall, de Vazquez estimates that 100 retailers nationwide,
including her retail outlets in New Mexico and her boutique in Palm
Desert, Calif., carry Char Designs collections.
   The 44-year-old Santa Fe designer recalls ordinary circumstances
marked her business beginnings in Guadalajara, Mexico, where she
moved with the Mexican chef who became her husband shortly
thereafter. At first, he was working and she was not.
   She likens the story to a fairy tale.
   ``It was like the miller's daughter, you throw straw at her and
she's supposed to spin it into gold. I was left alone in this house
with some leather. So I made a handbag and painted it,'' says de
Vazquez, who had been a clothing designer in Sausalito, Calif. ``A
young couple from New York City saw it and asked me to do a
collection.''
   In the fall of 1968, the couple took the small line of handbags
to a boutique show in New York.
   ``Every single big department store in New York saw it. We were
nationally known in three to six months _ an overnight explosion,''
de Vazquez says.
   Within a year, the Mexican business, joined by her husband, was
shipping $25,000 in merchandise a month, and Hollywood provided a
major chunk of the clientele, she says.
   ``People would come down in vans and just stock up,'' she says.
   By 1976, de Vazquez says, ``we had 150 employees, and an entire
town that hand-painted all the leather for us.''
   But while business boomed, the marriage faltered.
   De Vazquez and her two small boys packed up and moved to Santa
Fe, a place she thought would be good for starting over.
   She says the Mexican business ceased within a year after her
departure. But with the help of her retired parents and her sister
Sherry Stein _ a San Francisco fashion designer who moved to Santa
Fe about that time _ it wasn't long before she was back on track.
   With their father helping finance the startup operation, the
sisters began Char and Sher Designs. They had their established
contacts, but decided on a strategy that was the reverse of what
made the earlier Mexican business succeed.
   ``I knew the formula,'' de Vazquez says. ``But we decided that
rather than making a lot of cheap stuff, we would make real
expensive stuff and not much of it and get the same dollar.''
   During the first several years, the family, with the help of a
friend who had worked for de Vazquez in Mexico, worked to establish
a regional market for the designs.
   The turning point came in 1979 when the August issue of
Gentlemen's Quarterly magazine carried a Char and Sher cowboy shirt
on its cover model. Before long, the company was at the forefront
of the Southwestern clothing flurry of the early 1980s.
   ``That exploded our entire business and we started selling to
every single major department store,'' de Vazquez says.
   Stein has since left to study design at Pasadena, Calif., Art
College and de Vazquez is running the business' complex 15 miles
north of Santa Fe in the village of Cuyamungue.
   She and her team of designers work out of studios on the
property, and sewers and cutters work among the reels of soft,
multi-colored lamb skin in an adjacent plant. Her parents, Adelene
and Lynn Blankenship, live in a home just behind her ``Viva''
wholesale outlet, but they and Stein no longer have financial
interests in the venture.
   The peak for the business came in 1984, when it grossed more
than $2 million, de Vazquez says, while recent annual revenues have
been in excess of $1 million.
   De Vazquez says 1982 _ the year the western market ``fell off a
cliff'' _ was the most difficult.
   ``There were millions of prairie skirts and all of a sudden
nobody wanted them,'' de Vazquez says. ``Accounts went broke. But
being small and innovative, we turned on a dime.''
   That meant giving way to variation in design, and, for a time,
veering away from the Southwest style to more conservative or
high-fashion looks.
   For now, thanks to the renewed popularity of Ralph Lauren's
westernwear, and the ever-increasing trendiness of Santa Fe itself,
leather skirts, coats and blouses seem to be in high demand.
   Still, de Vazquez says she is prepared for the death of the
trend.
   ``It won't make any difference any more,'' de Vazquez says.
``We've already entered into high fashion. If it calls for
Southwest we plug it in. If it doesn't, we don't.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 21</NOTE>
