<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Boeing     05-17 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Boeing,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways Confident New Boeing Jets Will Be Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Civil Aviation Authority said Wednesday
there is ``nothing basically wrong'' with Boeing's new 747-400
series jets but that the American company has not met modern
European standards.
   ``There is nothing basically wrong with the aircraft,'' said a
CAA spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom.
   ``But you can liken the situation to that of a motorist who,
some years ago would not have needed rear seat belts, but who now
does.''
   The U.S. regulatory body, the Federal Aviation Administration,
has approved the new aircraft, but European aviation authorities
are threatening to withhold airworthiness certificates for the
planes unless Boeing agrees to a number of design changes.
   Without the certificates the planes cannot be used for scheduled
commercial flights.
   British Airways, which has ordered 19 of the new planes, said
Wednesday it remains confident it will soon be operating them.
Eight of the planes are scheduled to be delivered to the airline
this year, the first next month.
   ``We are confident the issue will be resolved and that we will
take delivery of the aircraft and introduce them into service as
planned,'' said a spokesman for British Airways, also speaking
anonymously.
   European aviation authorities want changes made in the design of
floor beams supporting the planes' upper decks, and better
separation of certain electrical circuits.
   ``Boeing has not given enough attention to the way standards
have been developed,'' said the CAA spokesman. ``We are telling
them there are more modern standards to be taken into
consideration.''
   The first of the 747-400s to be introduced into Europe is
scheduled to be delivered Thursday to the Dutch airline KLM.
</TEXT>
