<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today in a subdued
response to a better-than-expected report on international trade.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose .18 to 2,453.63 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 635 up, 545 down and
563 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 62.06 million shares at
midmorning.
   The Commerce Department reported this morning that the nation's
trade deficit narrowed to $8.86 billion in March from a
downward-revised $9.82 billion the month before.
   Advance estimates on Wall Street had called for a March deficit
of $10 billion or more.
   The news sent the dollar higher in foreign exchange. But
analysts said it got a less exuberant response in the bond and
stock markets, in part because it suggested that the pace of the
domestic economy might not be slowing as much as had been hoped.
   In addition, brokers said traders were staying cautious ahead of
the scheduled report from the government Thursday on the consumer
price index for April.
   There is some concern on Wall Street that the figures will cast
some doubts on the belief that the Federal Reserve is beginning to
succeed in its effort to restrain inflation.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up \ at
52; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up [ at 34{; United
Technologies, up \ at 51}, and Eastman Kodak, up \ at 43\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.10 to 176.02. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .19 at 350.11.
