<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Workers'Rights     05-17 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Workers' Rights,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Plans ``Social Charter'' to Guarantee Workers' Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The EEC Commission said Wednesday it
had agreed on the outline of a plan for a ``social charter'' which
would guarantee the rights of workers throughout the 12-nation
trade bloc.
   The charter would spell out the obligations of member states to
guarantee the free movement of workers between the 12 European
Economic Community countries. It would also ensure the workers'
social security protection, working conditions and education
programs.
   Vasso Papandreou, the EEC's commissioner for social affairs and
employment, said the Commission wanted to guarantee that everybody
benefited from the EEC's plans to dismantle all trade and other
barriers by the end of 1992.
   ``Europe can be built neither against the wishes of companies,
nor against the wishes of workers or citizens. It needs the full
participation of all social groups,'' she said.
   Ms. Papandreou said she expected a clear mandate for such a
charter to be given to the commission by the EEC summit meeting in
Paris at the end of this year.
   ``There will be a solemn declaration by the heads of government
and state and a clear mandate to the commission to come up with an
action program by June 1990 at the latest,'' she said.
</TEXT>
