<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Forecasts Continue to Force Down Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade as predictions of rain
continue to drag down prices.
   The drop in prices is due to government and private forecasts of
above-average rainfall in parts of Iowa, Minnesota and other
western crop states affected recently by dry weather, said Rich
Feltes, an analyst with Refco Inc. in Chicago.
   The strong dollar is creating anemic demand in Europe for U.S.
soybean products. That and increasing exports of Brazilian soybeans
is putting pressure on soybean futures.
   Traders also are noting that the drag on corn and wheat prices
is being caused by the failure of the Soviet Union to order
additional grain through the U.S. export bonus program.
   In early trading, wheat was a \ cent lower to } cent higher,
with the contract for delivery in May at $4.10 a bushel; corn was a
{ cent to 1\ cents lower with May at $2.77 a bushel; oats were 3
cents to 4 cents lower with July at $1.86 a bushel; soybeans were
1{ cents to 3} cents lower with May at $7.28{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .23 cent lower with June at 71.35
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .13 cent higher
with May at 77.25 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .37 cent
lower with June at 47.80 cents a pound; pork bellies were .47 cent
lower to .23 cent higher with May at 33.30 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled mixed Tuesday, while pork futures were
lower.
