<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   05-17 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Put Up or Shut Up,' Bankruptcy Examiner Tells Suitors for Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 1 new graf after 2nd graf pvs, David I....to UPDATE
with Ritchie group saying it plans to revise its offer; INSERTS 1 new graf
after 10th graf pvs, Shapiro said...to UPDATE with quote from Ritchie group.
DELETES 17th graf pvs, ``Everyone overlooks... to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suitors who have made proposals to buy
strikebound Eastern Airlines have been told to ``put up or shut
up'' and put at least $100 million in cash on the table.
   David I. Shapiro, the bankruptcy examiner for Eastern, said
Tuesday there are no ``real live offers'' to buy the carrier.
   In response, one of the two groups bidding for Eastern said late
Tuesday it planned to revise its proposal with a new plan that will
include ``substantial equity capital.''
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland, meanwhile, said Eastern
has provided valid reasons for its plan to sell its prized
Northeast shuttle service. Eastern already has an agreement to sell
the shuttle to developer Donald Trump for $365 million, but Lifland
gave the airline until Monday to consider a higher bid by America
West Airlines.
   Joel Zweibel, the attorney representing Eastern's major
creditors, said they support a prompt sale of the New
York-Washington-Boston service.
   At an all-day bankruptcy hearing, Shapiro said there are no
``real live offers out there yet'' for all of Eastern. Two investor
groups have submitted buyout proposals to the court for the whole
airline including the shuttle.
   ``This is not bankruptcy as usual; this is an important case
involving the interests of the public,'' Shapiro told a packed,
humid courtroom. ``It's time to put up or shut up.''
   He asked the interested suitors to put at least $100 million of
their own cash at risk. The two buyout proposals depend heavily on
debt financing, according to sources close to the situation.
   Miami-based Eastern has been under Chapter 11 protection from
creditors since March 9, five days after the start of a paralyzing
strike by its Machinists union that was supported by pilots and
flight attendants. The bankruptcy court must approve any sale of
Eastern or any of its assets, including the shuttle service.
   Two investor groups, one headed by Chicago commodities trader
Joseph Ritchie and the other by former Piedmont Airlines chairman
William Howard, have submitted formal bids.
   Shapiro said the two groups have told him their proposals are
``opening shots'' in an eventual negotiating process rather than
final offers.
   The pilots union released a statement late Tuesday from the
Ritchie group saying it plans to submit a revised offer that would
address Shapiro's ``concerns over the need for substantial equity
capital.'' The statement noted the plan would be the first to
propose putting substantial equity capital _ as opposed to borrowed
funds _ at risk in an Eastern buyout.
   Lewis Kaden, an attorney representing the Howard group, told
reporters outside the courtroom that his group would also consider
buying the shuttle alone at a price below that offered by America
West but higher than Trump's.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes told the court that the shuttle
could easily be detached from the rest of the airline's operations.
Part of the $300 million net profit expected to be gained from the
sale to Trump will go to repay debts and rebuild other Eastern
operations, he said.
   Eastern has proposed a plan to rebuild as a smaller carrier and
sell some $1.8 billion in assets separately, including the shuttle.
   As part of the plan, Eastern announced in Miami Tuesday an
agreement to sell 15 aircraft to UAS-Invest, an aircraft leasing
company, for $277.5 million. The airline has announced several
similar deals in recent weeks.
   Phoenix-based America West has offered to pay $415 million for
the shuttle and $336 million for 10 Boeing 757s in a total package
worth $751 million.
   Trump's $365 million agreement with Frank Lorenzo, chairman of
Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., expires on May 27. Under their
contract, the developer would receive $8 million from Eastern if
the shuttle deal collapses.
   Lifland said Eastern had articulated a ``good, sound business
reason'' to sell the shuttle, although he has not yet decided
whether such a sale would be in the airline's best interests. He
postponed the next hearing on Eastern until Monday to give the
airline time to evaluate the offers.
   Lifland denied a request by a group of New York financial
institutions for more time to submit a bid for Eastern because it
couldn't meet last Wednesday's deadline. Shapiro called the group's
bid ``frivolous.''
   The consortium had said it would offer around $1 billion for
Eastern, but only if the deal also included assets that Lorenzo
sold to other airlines after he acquired Eastern in early 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
