<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1302EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-SchoolRecords Adv21   05-17 1062</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-School Records, Adv 21,1095</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, May 21 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Class Project: Make A Pop Star</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: lowercase ``down beat'' in 15th graf is cq; the name Ardie in
21st graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karen O'Connor, vice president of AEMMP Record
Co., hypes the company's latest release in the best tradition of
music promoters.
   ``I really haven't heard anything in a long time that was
powerful as this music,'' she says. ``It's a lot better than what
I've been hearing on the radio lately.''
   O'Connor is pushing a record, but if she pushes a bit too hard,
perhaps she's entitled. The record by the Bad Examples will be
AEMMP's sole release this year and the executive is only 20 years
old.
   AEMMP _ pronounced ``amp'' _ is a real record company owned by
Columbia College, a private liberal-arts school in downtown Chicago
with an enrollment of about 6,500.
   AEMMP also is a class. Company executives and workers are
students learning to operate what singer-songwriter Joni Mitchell
once called ``the starmaker machinery behind the popular songs.''
   For O'Connor, who quit two part-time jobs and spent her spring
break in Chicago to devote more time to this year's project, the
class could become a springboard to a job with a major record
company and advance her toward the goal of managing a big-name
rocker.
   ``This class is going to give us great resumes,'' she said.
   The objective of the class, called ``Decision-Making: Music
Business,'' is to find a musical act, sign it to a contract,
manufacture and market its record and get the band signed to a
major record company.
   So success for O'Connor and her approximately 20 classmates also
would give a boost to the Bad Examples, a pop-rock quartet selected
by the class from among about 200 acts as the brightest star on
Chicago's club scene.
   ``The more different people that are excited about the music and
working for it, the better it helps us,'' said Ralph Covert, the
group's songwriter and lead singer.
   AEMMP released the three-song set by the Bad Examples on April
26 in two formats _ 800 12-inch vinyl records and 200 cassette
tapes. The record-release party at a Chicago-area nightspot marked
the completion of the production phase of the project and the
beginning of the marketing push, which includes pestering radio
stations into playing the music.
   ``If you're going pop, you can't exist without airplay,'' said
Chuck Suber, a co-creator of the class. ``You can't even get into a
record store without something that's been pre-sold on the air.''
   O'Connor said AEMMP would pitch the Bad Examples release to all
national record companies. But she said it was at least as
important to promote the band via airplay, club appearances,
perhaps even a concert tour of college towns.
   ``If we start a buzz in Chicago, they're going to be that much
more interested in the product,'' she said.
   The AEMMP Records class was founded in 1982 by Suber, who had
just stepped down after 24 years as publisher of down beat
magazine, a jazz monthly, and Irwin Steinberg, who had just retired
as chairman of New York-based Polygram Records Inc.
   Suber also had taught part-time for many years in Columbia's
Arts, Entertainment and Media Management Program, for which the
in-house record company is named, although the department is now
called simply the Management Department.
   Suber and Steinberg still teach the academic portions of the
two-semester class. Debra Hale, a graduate student who served as
president of the 1984 AEMMP class, oversees the record company's
progress.
   Steinberg sees the class as a chance for students to do
``something real rather than a mock effort.
   ``They've got to put themselves on the line and go to market
with the artist and experience either the success or defeat,'' he
said in a telephone interview from New York. ``It's more than
theoretical _ it's real.''
   AEMMP's greatest success to date was in 1987, when its release
of a 12-inch single by an urban-dance trio called ATM led to the
group's being signed to a three-year deal with Omni Records, a
Philadelphia label distributed by the Atlantic Recording Corp.
   The group's first Omni release, a 12-inch single titled ``Try
Me,'' got some airplay on the East Coast last summer and a
follow-up is due out this summer, said ATM's leader, Ardie Rowe.
   Suber said ATM's contract with Omni calls for AEMMP to receive 2
percent of the revenues from the group's first two releases after
Omni has recouped the advance it paid the artists. But ATM's first
release didn't sell enough copies to bring any money back to the
college, he said.
   Since the only area of record-company management not covered is
studio recording, the class begins its star search with a call for
production-quality tapes.
   After the students select an act, AEMMP contracts with a record
maker to press the vinyl copies, a tape duplicator to make the
cassettes and an album-jacket company to package the product.
   With only a $1,500 budget, the students often rely on the good
will of manufacturers like AGI Inc., a suburban Chicago album-cover
manufacturer that has donated services to AEMMP since the class was
created.
   This year's musical entries were screened by AEMMP's
artists-and-repertoire committee, which selected five acts to
present to the entire class for a final decision.
   Suber said choosing the right act _ one with a fresh, yet
commercially palatable sound _ is the most difficult task the
students face.
   ``They have to change their attitude from music consumers to
music producers and that's not easy when you're a dedicated music
fan,'' Suber said.
   Student Henry Carpenter, who headed the arts-and-repertoire
committee, agreed.
   ``My personal taste in music is alternative music and heavy
metal,'' he said. ``But when we went through the tapes, I looked
for what I thought would be the most marketable product.''
   The Bad Examples, championed by O'Connor, emerged victorious
after an inter-class battle settled by field trips to two
nightclubs to see the finalists in action.
   ``Seeing them live and seeing the reaction of the people who go
to their show, I'm really behind the Bad Examples now,'' said
Carpenter, who had led the faction favoring another band. ``I'm
really confident they can get a major record deal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
