<DOCNO> AP890517-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Cocoa     05-17 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Cocoa,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Prices Hit 14-Year Low Before Rallying To Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa prices hit a 14-year low Wednesday before
recovering to finish the day higher on the London market.,
   The selling wave reflected the prospect of a glutted market for
the fifth consecutive season in 1988-89, traders said.
   Cocoa for July delivery closed at $1,158 a metric ton, up $1.64
from Tuesday's close. Earlier in the day, the contract traded at
the 14-year low of $1,140.
   Traders said most experts are predicting record world production
this season of about 2.3 million metric tons. That would be about
200,000 metric tons more than expected consumption, the biggest
surplus ever.
   In addition, signs that the Ivory Coast _ which has
international debts of more than $14 billion _ could be close to
abandoning its costly price-support policy also have encouraged
selling, traders said.
   The present price the government pays its cocoa farmers is equal
to about $1,312 a ton, traders said.
   Ivory Coast's international creditors have been pressing
strongly for a cut for some time, according to banking sources.
   Ivory Coast, which is Africa's biggest producer and relies on
cocoa for about a third of its export revenues, has for the past
year been refusing to sell at a price below its break-even level.
   As a result, the nation has accumulated stocks of about 400,000
tons, of which half already have been put into storage in Europe
for at least two years.
   Traders also said there was a likelihood of a record Ivorian
harvest of up to 720,000 tons, 100,000 tones more than initial
forecasts, for the October 1988-September-1989 season.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
