<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-17 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Buoyant, Gold Drops</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose sharply in Europe on
Wednesday, benefiting from a smaller-than-expected U.S. trade
deficit in March.
   Gold prices in Europe dropped to a 33-month low, while silver
was trading at a 26-month low.
   In late European trading, the dollar had moved to a 34-month
high against the Swiss franc, a 32-month high against the Italian
lira, a 30-month high against the French franc and a 28-month high
against the Dutch guilder.
   In London, the British pound slumped to a 20-month low, dropping
to $1.6140 from $1.6398 late Tuesday.
   The dollar also rose in Tokyo to a 18-month high against the
Japanese yen, closing up 0.70 yen at 137.70 yen. Later, in London,
it pushed up further to 138.95 yen.
   After fluctuating in a narrow range early Wednesday, the dollar
surged when the U.S. government reported an unexpectedly narrow
trade deficit of $8.9 billion in March and revised the February
deficit to $9.8 billion down from $10.9 billion.
   Economists had anticipated a $10 billion deficit for the most
recent month.
   ``Since there was no sign of central bank interventions,
everybody was buying,'' said a trader in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Selected late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday:
1.9675 West German marks, up from 1.9426; 1.7580 Swiss francs, up
from 1.7360; 6.6607 French francs, up from 6.5685; 2.2150 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1820; 1,433.00 Italian lire, up from 1,408.75;
1.1925 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1892.
   Gold, apparently pushed lower by the stronger U.S. dollar, fell
in London to a late bid price of $370.75 a troy ounce, down from
$374.25 bid late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, the metal fell to $370.25 bid from $374.40 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.25 to a closing bid of
$374.74.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a late bid price of $5.46 a
troy ounce, down from $5.55 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
