<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-TribuneStrike     05-17 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tribune Strike,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Tribune-Typographers Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has signed a consent decree
formally ending a nearly 4-year printers strike against the Chicago
Tribune.
   Both sides had previously accepted and signed the basic accord,
which includes an $8.56 million settlement fund, a new three-year
contract and withdrawal of a federal lawsuit filed by the Chicago
Typographical Union No. 16.
   U.S. District Judge Marvin Aspen signed the consent decree
Monday.
   Fifty-one printers who accepted a 1986 unconditional offer to
return to work can remain under terms of the new contract, which
took effect Jan. 3, or take a $30,000 buyout.
   Of the 240 original strikers, 119 remain out of work. They will
receive lump-sum payments based on age and tenure ranging from
about $30,000 to $90,000 and will receive company-paid medical
insurance after age 65.
   The strike resulted from the Tribune's desire to gain greater
control in hiring and assigning printers in the composing room.
   The printers' lawsuit alleged the company had violated a 1975
agreement in which they were guaranteed lifetime employment in
exchange for the introduction of labor-saving technology.
</TEXT>
