<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-17 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0264</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors
continued to be influenced by forecasts of heavy rains in western
crop areas.
   Prices have been driven lower in recent sessions because of
government and private forecasts of above-average rainfall in parts
of Iowa, Minnesota and other western crop states affected recently
by dry weather.
   In addition to the weather forecasts, soybeans were pressured by
the continued strength of the dollar, which is cutting European
demand for U.S. soymeal.
   ``We're not seeing much business,'' said Cathy Leow, analyst
with Thomsom McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``But we don't
expect to see much business this time of year,'' with the South
Americans coming into the market.
   Corn futures were lower, forced down by commission house and
professional selling. However, analysts say there is some
expectation that corn should recover, after trading on the same
weather forecasts since Monday.
   Wheat prices were up on reports of heavy exporter buying and
indications that domestic users are starting to buy, Ms. Leow said.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to 3\ cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.07{ a bushel; corn was a {
cent to 1{ cents lower with May at $2.77 a bushel; oats were a 3
cents lower to a { cents higher with May at $1.81 a bushel;
soybeans were a { cent to 5{ cents lower with May at $7.30.
