<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Northrop-Stealth     05-17 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Northrop-Stealth,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stealth Bomber Accounts For Half Northrop's Revenue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp.'s revenue on the B-2 stealth
bomber amounted to $657 million, or about half the company's
overall sales, for the first quarter, the company disclosed in a
letter to shareholders.
   The disclosure Tuesday marked the first time the firm has
revealed how much it has taken in from the bomber. The sales figure
was almost exactly what most analysts had been estimating since
Northrop began the B-2 program in 1981.
   Sales overall for the first quarter were $1.28 billion, with a
profit of $9.7 million that was down sharply from the $139.6
million profit of a year ago, the company said. Quarterly sales the
year before were $1.37 billion.
   Northrop failed to disclose stealth sales figures for the first
quarter of last year, saying that information remained classified
by the Air Force.
   Wolfgang Demisch, an analysts at UBS Securities, said revenue
from the bomber appeared to be declining.
</TEXT>
