deficit narrowed in March to $8.9 billion from a revised $9.8
billion in February. The market had expected a $10.2 billion
shortfall.
   The trade news sent the dollar's value higher in
foreign-exchange trading and reverberated into the stock market,
although the momentum weakened late in the day on worries that the
report signaled strong U.S. growth and higher inflation.
