<DOCNO> AP890517-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SteelImports     05-17 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Imports,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six-Year Low Reached</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports in March fell to their lowest
level in six years and their share of the domestic market shrank to
17.2 percent, well within the goal of the U.S. import quotas, a
domestic industry group said Wednesday.
   The month's 1.22 million tons of imports represented just 12.9
percent of the market when excluding 129,000 tons of semi-finished
steel U.S. companies imported to supply their own mills, according
to an importers group.
   ``Semifinished imports have been in critical demand by U.S.
rolling mills since early 1988,'' said John Griffin, president of
the American Institute for Imported Steel of New York, which
represents importers.
   Exports, meanwhile, rose in March to 606,000 tons, the largest
monthly total since July 1974.
   First quarter exports totaled 1.1 million tons, compared with
303,000 tons in the 1988 first quarter, the American Iron and Steel
Institute in Washington, which represents domestic producers, said.
   The rival groups interpret Commerce Department information to
serve their competing interests.
   The domestic group said steel prices in foreign markets are
higher than in the United States, making this country less
attractive to foreign producers.
   The leading steel-producing nations appear to be shipping less
metal in than authorized under the individual quotas they
negotiated with the United States, the AISI said. Foreign producers
undershipped their quotas by 25 percent last year.
   Imports were 1.34 million tons in February and 1.84 million tons
in March 1988.
   The 1.22 million tons shipped this March was the lowest since
April 1983. The import tonnage represented even less of the
domestic supply because shipments by U.S. producers were higher
that month, the AISI said.
   The five-year quotas instituted by former President Reagan in
late 1984 were intended to limit foreign steel to around 20 percent
of the U.S. market. Domestic steelmakers are campaigning to have
them renewed beyond their Sept. 31 expiration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Mega-ShipCompetition Adv21   05-17 0901</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mega-Ship Competition, Adv 21,0931</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday May 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nation's Top Ports Vying For World's Largest Cruise Ship</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT EVERGLADES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Port Everglades Director Joel
Alesi swivels around in his leather desk chair, he surveys gleaming
white cruise ships embarking on tropical voyages and giant cranes
unloading cargo vessels at the nation's second-busiest cruise port.
   But in his mind's eye, he envisions a mammoth passenger ship _
bigger than the biggest aircraft carrier _ gliding in from the
Atlantic.
   The dream is also shared by port officials in Miami and near
Cape Canaveral as the competition intensifies for the largest
cruise ship ever proposed.
   Although the Phoenix World City ship is still anchored to the
drawing boards, three ports that handle nearly 80 percent of the
world's cruise ship business are locked in a winner-take-all battle
to become the vessel's home port when _ and if _ it ever sails.
   At stake, say port officials, is a greater share of the rapidly
growing $5.5 billion passenger ship industry and the prestige of
hosting a vessel more massive than the three largest cruise ships
combined.
   Each port director believes he holds the proper blend of
location and amenities to come out on top when the home port is
announced this summer.
   ``We feel we are in very favorable position _ both
geographically and physically _ to accommodate the Phoenix,''
boasted Alesi at the Fort Lauderdale-area port.
   ``I think we have an extremely good shot,'' said Charles
Rowland, executive director of Port Canaveral. ``We're an
up-and-coming port and can give the Phoenix special attention.''
   ``The question is can the Phoenix afford not to come to Miami?''
asked Carmen Lunetta, director of the Port of Miami, which handled
65 percent of the world's 3.5 million cruise passengers last year,
making it No. 1.
   John Rogers, spokesman for the New York-based World City Corp.,
said a home port decision should be made in 30 to 45 days. Until
then, company policy prohibits any comments about the project, he
said.
   Billed in its promotional literature as a ``daring project by
virtue of its size and cost,'' the estimated $1.3 billion Phoenix
project was conceived by Knut Utstein Kloster, who resigned in 1986
as chairman of Kloster Group, owners of Norwegian Caribbean Lines
and Royal Viking Line.
   The plans call for its 5,200 passengers to be housed in three
hotels on the 1,260-foot twin-hulled vessel, more than 200 feet
longer than any operating cruise ship.
   Along its ``Main Street'' would be a chapel, cafes, a
100,000-volume library and a 2,500-seat theater large enough to
handle a Broadway musical.
   At 250,000 registered tons, the proposed ship would be heavier
than the combined weight of the three largest cruise ships. Since
no Caribbean port would be deep enough to handle the ship, on-board
yachts would ferry passengers and the 1,850-member crew.
   Rogers said World City is negotiating with West German
shipbuilders for a scheduled 1992 completion date, but no deal has
been struck.
   The 2,600-passenger Sovereign of the Seas, owned by Miami-based
Royal Caribbean Lines, is considered the world's largest cruise
ship measured by gross tons. But other ships are longer, such as
the 963-foot Queen Elizabeth II and the 1,041-foot France.
   Industry representatives from around the world at a recent Miami
convention predicted the number of cruise ship passengers should
continue to grow at 12 percent annually, topping 22 million
passengers by 2000.
   The efforts to lure the ship are nearly as grand as the project
itself.
   At Canaveral, port officials have offered to lease World City 95
acres of land to build four 350-room hotels and a marina.
Meanwhile, a new dock for the Phoenix is expected to cost between
$70 million and $90 million.
   Canaveral, which handled 644,000 passengers last year, is
expected to add at least two new cruise ships by next year, said
Rowland.
   He also said World City has been studying other cruise lines'
tie-ins with nearby attractions such as Disney World and Sea World.
   ``I don't see how the World City people could ask for anything
more than what we have here,'' said Rowland.
   But that's what they are saying in Miami and Port Everglades.
   Alesi said plans to build a 1,000-room hotel complex and
convention center at Port Everglades are enticing to Phoenix
planners. In addition, the port is the deepest in Florida and less
than 1{ miles from the main Atlantic shipping lanes.
   ``Just in terms of our location, we have to be attractive to the
Phoenix,'' said Alesi, whose port handled 1.6 million cruise
passengers last year.
   In Miami, which expects 3 million cruise passengers this year,
Lunetta said the port is the obvious choice for the world's largest
cruise ship.
   ``We could get ready to handle the Phoenix in 12 months,'' said
Lunetta, who plans to meet with World City executives in New York
later this month. ``It's only natural that the ship come here.''
   From his office near the port, Jay Lewis views the scrambling
with skepticism.
   Lewis, president of Market Scope Inc., a cruise industry
consulting firm, says he is still not convinced Kloster can muster
the financing for the project.
   ``The only thing that's heating up is the competition with the
ports,'' said Lewis. ``I don't think the project is going anywhere
at the moment.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, May 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
