<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market overcame some ambivalence over
the latest news on international trade to post a moderate gain in
brisk trading Wednesday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.98 to 2,462.43,
recouping most of Tuesday's 10.44-point setback.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
957 up, 514 down and 527 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 191.21 million
shares, up from 173.10 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 231.47 million shares.
   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday morning that the
nation's trade deficit narrowed to $8.86 billion in March from a
downward-revised $9.82 billion the month before.
   Advance estimates on Wall Street had called for a March deficit
of $10 billion or more.
   The news sent the dollar sharply higher in foreign exchange. But
analysts said it got a less exuberant response in the bond and
stock markets, in part because it suggested that the pace of the
domestic economy might not be slowing as much as had been hoped.
   In addition, brokers said traders were staying cautious ahead of
the scheduled report from the government Thursday on the consumer
price index for April.
   There is some concern on Wall Street that the figures will cast
doubts on the belief that the Federal Reserve is beginning to
succeed in its effort to restrain inflation.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up 1\ at
53; Philip Morris, up 2| at 135{; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph,
up [ at 34{; Merck, up ~ at 71{, and Eastman Kodak, up \ at 43\.
   McGraw-Hill tumbled 5~ to 68~. The company, which has been the
subject of takeover rumors and speculation lately, said Maxwell
Communications Corp. agreed not to try to acquire it for 15 years.
   Prime Computer fell 2 to 15}. MAI Basic Four Inc. said late
Tuesday it was reevaluating its hostile $20-a-share takeover bid
for the company.
   Holiday Corp., which said it would consider selling its Harrah's
Lake Tahoe casino-resort for about $400 million, climbed 3] to 45[.
   Upjohn gained \ to 33 in active trading. The company said the
Food and Drug Administration agreed to give ``expeditious'' review
to a drug Upjohn is working on for treatment of head injuries.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $19.67 billion, or
0.63 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.06 to 176.98.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 2.37 to 364.89, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 2.20 at 317.48.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
2.86 to 438.52. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 351.84, up 1.92.
