<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;Ls-BrokeredDeposits     05-17 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Brokered Deposits,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDIC Chairman: Agency Needs Power To Curb Broker Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. said Wednesday his agency needs additional power to curb
abuses by banks and savings institutions that raise high-cost
deposits through brokers.
   FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman, testifying before a House
Banking subcommittee, split from other bank regulators who said
current law provides them with enough authority.
   The practice of raising deposits through brokers has been
criticized for making the savings and loan crisis worse. The funds,
raised through brokers who earn fees by channeling clients' money
to institutions paying the highest interest rates, has allowed some
shaky institutions to grow far more rapidly than they could have
through local deposits.
   Healthy banks and S&amp;Ls object to the practice because they often
have to raise their rates to compete.
   But all the regulators, including Seidman, said brokered
deposits, used properly, can be beneficial, allowing institutions
to raise money to make a big loan or meet a temporary cash crunch.
Sometimes they are the only way for troubled institutions to stay
afloat while they wait the government to shut them down.
   Forbidding brokered deposits ``is a little bit like saying we
should abolish the manufacturing of automobiles because some people
drive too fast,'' said Comptroller of the Currency Robert L.
Clarke, who regulates nationally chartered banks.
   Clark, Federal Reserve Board member H. Robert Heller and Federal
Home Loan Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall, who oversees savings
and loans, told the Subcommittee on General Oversight and
Investigations that brokered deposits are currently under control.
They recommended further study before enacting legislation on the
subject.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, sponsored a provision on
brokered deposits in S&amp;L bailout legislation, which passed the
Senate last month. It would bar weak institutions from using
deposits brokers unless the institutions get a waiver from the FDIC.
   That is the reverse of the current practice under which brokered
deposits are assumed to be permissible unless regulators say
otherwise.
   Rep. Stephen Neal, D-N.C., sponsored a similar section in a bill
passed earlier this month by the House Banking Committee.
   Rep. Carroll Hubbard, D-Ky., chairman of the subcommittee, said
he held Wednesday's hearing to serve as a basis for debate when the
S&amp;L legislation reaches the House floor.
   But he said he has not yet decided whether to attempt to delete
the brokered deposit clause.
   Seidman, who under President Bush's proposal to close or merge
failed S&amp;Ls, would get broad new power to oversee savings and loans
in addition to commercial banks, said he would not object getting
specific authority to act against brokered deposits.
   Regulators currently must prove the deposits are being used
unsafely before they can act.
   But Seidman said he would prefer his agency to be permitted to
curb brokered deposits at healthy institutions, which at times use
them unwisely, and that it be able to set general rules on brokered
deposits rather than be forced to grant waivers to individual
institutions.
   Murkowski, testifying before Hubbard's panel, said securities
brokers, who earn fees for placing deposits, are lobbying against
his proposal.
   The deposits have soared in popularity, particularly after
investors fled the market following the 1987 stock crash.
   He said brokered deposits now account for 7.4 percent of S&amp;L
deposits, up from 2.6 percent for S&amp;Ls in June 1983. They account
for 5.3 percent of commercial bank deposits, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890517-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1817EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MinimumWage 4thLd-Writethru f0261 05-17 0896</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage, 4th Ld-Writethru, f0261,0914</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Gives Final Passage to Veto-Bound Minimum Wage Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts one graf after 4th graf bgng: ``For me ... to UPDATE
with Fitzwater saying Bush will veto bill `faster than the eye can see.'
Picks up 5th graf pvs bgng: Majority Democrats ...; Also moved on general
news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled Congress gave final
approval Wednesday to legislation raising the minimum wage for the
first time in eight years, but President Bush said it was
``inevitable'' he would kill the measure with the first veto of his
administration.
   The vote was 63-37 to approve the plan, which would boost the
minimum wage from $3.35 an hour to $4.55 by October 1991. That vote
left supporters four votes shy of the 67 needed in the Senate to
override Bush's veto.
   Only hours earlier Bush had vowed anew that his first veto
awaits the bill.
   ``For me the choice is very clear,'' Bush said. ``If the
majority of the Congress rejects my offer of a reasonable
compromise _ and we have made such a proposal _ a veto is going to
be inevitable.''
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said that when the
legislation reaches the president's desk, Bush will veto it
``instantly, faster than the eye can see.''
   Majority Democrats are also short of that two-thirds override
margin in the House, which passed the bill earlier this month, but
sponsors have promised a veto override attempt nonetheless as part
of an escalating political battle over the minimum wage and a
larger symbolic clash for momentum on domestic initiatives.
   Nonetheless, being able get a minimum-wage bill out of Congress
was a symbolic victory of sorts for its sponsors, who for the past
eight years could not get their proposal even that far because of
then-President Reagan's vehement opposition.
   And they vowed to advance another bill if Bush quashes the
measure passed Wednesday.
   ``We want to make it very clear that this fight is not going to
go away and we are going to continue this battle until we get a
fair and just increase in the minimum wage,'' Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., told reporters after the vote.
   Democratic congressional leaders are planning a mock signing
ceremony before formally transmitting the measure to the White
House, and plan to hold the bill until after Congress returns from
a Memorial Day recess so that Bush cannot veto it while sponsors
are away from Washington.
   Leading the GOP effort in Wednesday's debate, Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, said the legislation ``will translate into the loss of
hundreds of thousands of jobs and job opportunities for those who
most need our help.''
   But Kennedy, the measure's Senate sponsor, rejected such
assertions and made a final call for Bush to change his position.
   ``The fundamental issue, the overriding issue is whether the
Congress of the United State will once again make the minimum wage
a living wage and thereby ease the burden of poverty pressing down
on millions of our fellow citizens on the lowest rung of the
economic ladder,'' Kennedy said. ``The administration proposal is a
sham.''
   In a lengthy attack on Bush's stance, Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell said the president was choosing the wrong issue on
which to test his political muscle, saying the eight year freeze in
the floor wage has cost minimum-wage workers 40 percent of their
buying power.
   ``It is unconscionable and unfair to the weakest and most
vulnerable workers in our country to hold their wages hostage in
this way,'' the Maine Democrat said. ``There should be another,
better way for this test of political will to be conducted than at
their expense.''
   The minimum-wage fight has been brewing since Congress convened
in January, with the arguments little changed although the
legislation itself has been revised significantly since its
introduction, with the final product emerging from a House-Senate
conference committee three weeks ago.
   Sponsors of the leadership measure trimmed their final minimum
wage target from $4.65 to $4.55 but moved up the dates the three,
annual incremental increases are to take effect from January to
October. They also added a provision allowing employers to pay
employees with fewer than 60 days' work experience a subminimum
wage.
   Still the final product is far from a more modest proposal for
Bush, who from the outset has adopted a take-it-or-leave-it stance.
The president's measure, rejected by both the House and Senate,
called for a $4.25 an hour wage floor by January 1992 but would
allow employers to pay all new hires a subminimum for up to six
months regardless of prior work experience.
   Most Democrats have denounced Bush's ``training wage'' proposal
as a blatant attempt to allow employers to skirt paying the minimum
wage. Republicans have countered that it would protect thousands of
jobs that they say will be lost if the minimum wage is increased
and said the Democrats' two-month provision is too restrictive and
would require burdensome record-keeping.
   Bush has been urged by pro-business lobbying forces to venture
outside of Washington for an elaborate veto ceremony in a community
in the South or West where the president could present his argument
about the potential for massive job losses if the minimum wage is
increased without establishing a six-month subminimum. The White
House has not said whether Bush will do so.
</TEXT>
