<FIRST>u f AM-AT&amp;T-RateCut     05-17 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AT&amp;T-Rate Cut,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Says It Will Lower Selected Long-Distance Prices $140 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. said
Wednesday it would cut certain long-distance prices by about $140
million to comply with a new federal regulatory plan.
   The price cuts will take effect on July 1, the same time the
Federal Communications Commission's new price-cap plan begins.
   Under the price-cap plan adopted March 16, the FCC limits the
prices AT&amp;T charges rather than the profits it makes.
   The new cuts will bring rates for consumers and small businesses
down to the maximum permitted by the new regulation, AT&amp;T spokesman
Bryant Steele said.
   AT&amp;T's prices for large businesses had already been brought
below the price cap.
   The latest decrease will bring AT&amp;T's total interstate
long-distance price reductions to almost 40 percent in the five
years since the Bell System breakup, the company said.
   MCI Communications Corp. spokeswoman Pam Small said the mandated
cut was not a surprise. ``It's a small number, probably smaller
than we would have expected,'' she said.
   US Sprint Communications Co. spokesman Syd Courson said the
company would have no comment until its analysts had scanned the
price filing.
   Under the filing:
   _Prices on general long-distance service will drop about $60
million a year.
   _The Reach Out America discount calling plan for consumers will
be expanded at no extra charge. Prices of the basic and evening
bonus versions of Reach Out America will be cut.
   _The international Reach Out calling plan will be expanded from
four to 25 countries.
   _AT&amp;T will cut prices on calls its customers make between Mexico
and the United States and on calls from the United States to the
Philippines, Denmark, the Faeroe Islands in the North Atlantic,
Finland, Norway and Sweden. AT&amp;T also will cut prices on
international calls from Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
   _When holidays occur during the weekend but are legally observed
on a weekday, AT&amp;T will apply its holiday prices on the weekday the
holiday is observed.
</TEXT>
