<FIRST>u f AM-PennyStocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-17 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Penny Stocks, 1st Ld - Writethru,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comptroller Acts To Shut Down Blinder Penny Stock Operations In Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, The company... with 3 new grafs to UPDATE
with Blinder statement. Picks up 5th graf pvs, The alleged...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida officials on Wednesday accused the penny
stock brokerage Blinder, Robinson and Co. Inc. of a variety of
securities law violations and moved to kick the firm out of the
state.
   Comptroller Gerald Lewis said the state named 29 former and
current employees in a civil action to revoke their licenses,
including company President Meyer Blinder and his son, vice
president Larry Blinder.
   Denver-based Blinder, which has offices in 37 states _ including
10 in Florida _ and the District of Columbia was ordered to
immediately stop violating Florida securities laws.
   The company has 21 days to ask for a hearing to stop its Florida
licenses from being revoked.
   Rick Rouse, director of compliance for Blinder, Robinson,
expressed his confidence that the firm was acting in full
compliance with Floirda law, and said it would vigorously defend
itself against the charges.
   ``I feel it is totally irresponsible for the department not to
have related its concerns to me before they filed charges,'' Rouse
said in a statement issued Wednesday. ``Whenever there have been
problems, we have addressed them.''
   The alleged Florida violations could result in more than $5
million in fines.
   The action followed a 2{-year state investigation of Blinder
triggered by numerous complaints and queries from clients, Lewis
said at a news conference.
   The brokerage already is under investigation by state and
federal authorities elsewhere. The Florida comptroller's case is
being turned over to state prosecutors for possible criminal action.
   ``The history of their company is one of litigation,'' Lewis
said. ``We're ready for battle.''
   Thousands of investors in Florida are believed to have been
bilked by Blinder, which has been licensed in the state since 1973,
securities officials said. The officials said they did not have a
figure for the total amount of the alleged fraud.
   Penny stocks are low-priced, thinly traded securities that
generally cost less than $5 per share and are traded over the
counter rather than on a stock exchange.
   Lewis said alleged violations included manipulations in the
market for certain penny stocks, sale of unregistered securities,
unreasonable markups, failure to maintain proper records and
supervise employees, and unauthorized trading.
   He charged that in one case where an 80-year-old client lost
about $30,000 on penny stocks, Blinder employees bought and sold
stocks without the client's permission, conducted excessive stock
trades just to earn commissions and inflated the purchase price of
certain stock.
   The firm's troubles with the Securities and Exchange Commission
date to 1980 and include a probe initiated by the SEC in April 1987
into allegations that Blinder, Robinson had defrauded customers.
   The SEC has been investigating allegations dating to August 1983
that Blinder, Robinson violated federal law by marketing nine
distributions of unregistered securities, by falsely representing
the business prospects of the companies involved, and by
excessively marking up the prices of the securities.
   The SEC had two other actions pending against the company for
alleged bookkeeping violations.
   Last month, a U.S. District Court judge in Denver dismissed
charges in one of those cases _ a 1983 civil case against Blinder
and his brokerage _ and chastised the SEC for misconduct.
   Company attorneys have contended that the government had a
vendetta against the firm and Blinder said negative publicity
devastated business in 1988.
   Blinder began its business in Westbury, Long Island, N.Y., and
moved its headquarters to Denver in the late 1970s.
</TEXT>
