<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     05-17 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Drop on Release of Trade Figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metals futures were down sharply Wednesday on New
York's Commodity Exchange as investors bailed out following release
of better-than-expected balance of trade figures.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower,
energy prices were down, and livestock prices were down as meat
prices rallied.
   Gold settled $2.20 to $2.30 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $373.20 a troy ounce; silver was 7.1 cents to
7.9 cents lower with May at $5.429 a troy ounce; platinum was
$11.40 to $13.40 lower with May at $509.90 a troy ounce.
   The decline in metal prices came as the Commerce Department
released figures indicating that the U.S. trade deficit narrowed to
$8.86 billion in March as a record level of export sales helped to
offset rising oil imports.
   ``The continued strength of the dollar also adversely affected
metals,'' said Don Tierney, an analyst with Stanley Bell &amp; Co. in
New York.
   As the value of the dollar increases, its investment value
surpasses precious metals.
   Despite a recent report that the supply of platinum will
continue to fall short of supplies, platinum futures also were hit
by heavy selling.
   But Peter Cardillo, an analyst with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New
York, said the precious metals market is oversold at current levels.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade as investors continued to be influenced by
forecasts of heavy rains in western crop areas.
   Prices have been driven lower in recent sessions because of
government and private forecasts of above-average rainfall in parts
of Iowa, Minnesota and other western crop states affected recently
by dry weather.
   Soybeans also were pressured by the continued strength of the
dollar, which is cutting European demand for U.S. soymeal.
   ``We're not seeing much business,'' said Cathy Leow, analyst
with Thomsom McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``But we don't
expect to see much business this time of year,'' with the South
Americans coming into the market.
   Corn futures were lower and wheat prices were up on reports of
export buying and indications that domestic users are starting to
buy, Ms. Leow said.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to 3\ cents higher with
May at $4.07{ a bushel; corn was a \ cent to 1{ cents lower with
May at $2.77\ a bushel; oats were a { cents lower to a { cents
higher with May at $1.83{ a bushel; soybeans were a { cent to 5
cents lower with May at $7.29{.
   Energy futures were lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
with gasoline prices off sharply.
   The dropoff in gasoline prices was triggered by an American
Petroleum Institute report that imports of crude oil rose 15.2
percent in April, an average of 8.035 million barrels a day
compared to 6.97 million in 1988.
   There also was concern that overproduction by Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Nations would continue past the group's meeting
in June, said Robert Baker, an energy analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 17 cents to 57 cents lower
with June at $20.13 a barrel; heating oil was 1.15 cents to 1.25
cents lower with June at 47.96 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .43 cent to 2.53 cents lower with June at 63.27 cents a gallon.
   Trading in the cattle market was quiet in anticipation of the
Agriculture Department's release of the cattle-on-feed report.
   The report, released after the close of trading, indicated
higher than expected April marketings and feedlot placement. High
placements in feed lots could mean lower cash prices later in the
year.
   Pork belly prices were up the daily trading limit amid
short-covering and technical buy signals, said Paul Hare, an
analyst with Linnco Futures Inc. in Chicago. The advance was fueled
by expectations of renewed retail demand for bacon. Hogs were
higher, lifted by spillover support from pork bellies.
   Live cattle were .32 cent lower to .07 cent higher with June at
71.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .15 cents
higher with May at 77.27 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent lower to
.45 cent higher with June at 48.42 cents a pound; pork bellies were
1.35 cents to 2 cents higher with May at 35.75 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
