<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DefenseProfits     05-17 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Profits,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Questions Study that says Policy Changes Hurt Defense Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study concluding that changes in procurement
and tax policy hurt the defense industry's profits was based on
erroneous assumptions, a congressional investigative agency said
Wednesday.
   The General Accounting Office found that the conclusions reached
by the MAC Group, a Boston-based consulting firm that reviewed the
financial effects of policy changes implemented from 1984 to 1987,
``cannot be validated for the defense industry as a whole.''
   In its 1988 study, the MAC Group analyzed data on one weapon
program considered representative of nine anonymous defense
contractors. The study concluded that the changes would result in a
23 percent reduction in profits for defense contractors, additional
financing requirements of $8.5 billion for the nine contractors,
and a smaller return on their investment than is necessary to
preserve shareholder value.
   The study was funded by the Aerospace Industries Association of
America, the Electronic Industries Association and the National
Security Industrial Association, whose members include defense
contractors.
   The GAO investigationy, requested by Rep. Charles E. Bennett,
D-Fla., found that available public data and policy changes made
after the study, if projected to the entire defense industry, did
not support the MAC Group's conclusions.
   ``The MAC study seeks to show the impact of policy actions, but
it did not ascertain the industrywide level of profitability of
contractors either before or after these policy changes,'' the GAO
said.
   Bennett said in a statement that the GAO study shows that
``defense contractors have been talking poor but not showing us how
much profits are in their pockets.''
   ``Last year, the big defense companies hired some experts to
prove that defense contractors were hurting. Now we know that their
experts didn't prove anything,'' he said.
   Bennett, the second ranking Democrat on the House Armed Services
Committee, sponsored an amendment last year on profit issues that
was partly included in the fiscal 1989 Defense Authorization Bill.
   Under the law, a group of defense industry representatives and
federal agencies must by this fall recommend a method by which the
Pentagon measures profitability.
</TEXT>
