<FIRST>r f AM-Northwest-Davis     05-17 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest-Davis,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Extends Tender Offer for NWA Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles-based oil billionaire Marvin
Davis on Wednesday extended his $2.7 billion tender offer for NWA
Inc., the Northwest Airlines parent that has several other possible
suitors.
   Davis' $90-a-share offer, which has been rejected as inadequate
by NWA's board, was to expire at midnight Wednesday. Davis said it
will expire at 6 p.m. May 24, unless extended.
   Under a confidentiality agreement with NWA that gave Davis
access to non-public information about the company, no shares can
be purchased under the tender offer ``unless NWA takes certain
specified actions,'' Davis said in a news release.
   Other possible suitors also have signed the agreement, but Davis
has been the only one to launch a tender offer. NWA has urged
suitors to submit proposals on May 30.
   Only 3,134 shares of NWA's 29.1 million outstanding shares had
been tendered to Davis as of Tuesday, Davis said in the news
release.
   Others interested in the nation's fourth-largest airline have
been Pan Am Corp., the buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.,
NWA's machinists' union and a friendly partnership led by Los
Angeles investor Al Checchi. Pan Am is backed by a group that
includes investor Richard Rainwater, the Equitable Life Insurance
Co. and Texas' billionaire Bass family.
