<FIRST>r f AM-OilSpills     05-17 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spills,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panels Wans Exxon to Pay Cleanup Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee on Wednesday
unanimously passed a resolution calling on the Exxon Corp. to pay
all expenses surrounding the oil spill in Alaska.
   The resolution, which now goes to the full House, says that
Exxon and the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. ``have failed to keep
their promises and assurances to the Congress and the American
people'' that they could operate the pipeline in an environmentally
safe way.
   The measure gives Exxon until Sept. 15 to cleanup the mess
created March 24 when the Exxon Valdez tanker ran aground and
disgorged 10 million gallons of crude oil into the sound.
   It also says that Exxon ``should devote whatever resources are
necessary
   Coast Guard spokesman Jack O'dell emphasized that it was a
proposal and said his agency wouldn't have any response to Boxer's
comments until Thursday. and pay all expenses required to
compensate affected parties expeditiously.''
   The Coast Guard and Alaska state officials, along with federal
officials and the people who were directly affected by the spill,
are to be the ones to determine whether the cleanup is complete,
the measure says.
   Since the spill, the oil has moved more than 550 miles along the
Alaska coastline, killing thousands of sea otters, migratory birds
and other fish and wildlife.
   The result has been devastating to subsistence lifestyle of the
Alaska natives and to the commercial fishing industry, the
resolution states.
   Exxon has repeatedly taken full responsibility for the oil spill
and has been paying the costs of the cleanup.
   In other action related to oil, Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., on
Wednesday called on the Coast Guard to hold public hearings before
it changes rules about oil tanker traffic zones off the West Coast.
   She said the Coast Guard ``bowed to pressure'' from the Bureau
of Minerals Management, which wants more oil development off the
California coast, by decreasing the proposed distance allowed
between ship traffic lanes and oil rigs.
   In 1982, the Coast Guard had recommended a 5-mile ``free zone''
around rigs for 180 miles of the coast from Ano Nuevo to Santa
Barbara, Calif., Boxer said.
   She said the Coast Guard now is considering two one-mile traffic
lanes separated by a two-mile corridor in which rigs could be built.
</TEXT>
