<FIRST>r f AM-Long-TermCare     05-17 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Long-Term Care,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Urged to Provide Nursing Care Insurance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government should create an insurance
program to cover the millions of people who can't afford private
policies to provide nursing home care, witnesses told a House panel
Wednesday.
   The hearing of the Ways and Means health subcommittee ostensibly
was on a measure by Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., the panel chairman,
to set minimum federal standards for the emerging market in nursing
home insurance policies.
   But the witnesses who supported such a measure said what is
needed even more is a federal plan to guarantee nursing home care
for all Americans, regardless of their income.
   That proposition has wide sentimental support in Congress, but
few members are willing to step forward with a concrete to way
raise the estimated $40 billion a year such a program would cost.
   Custodial nursing home coverage was left out of the catastrophic
illness act that took effect Jan. 1.
   Stark, a major architect of the catastrophic coverage bill,
introduced nursing home legislation with a $40 billion price tag
last year, but it went nowhere.
   Testifying in support of Stark's private regulation bill,
Gwendolyn M. Bedford, a board member of the 30-million-member
American Association of Retired Persons, said ``AARP strongly
supports federal minimum standards for long-term care insurance.''
   But she went on to add: ``We believe that it is essential for
the federal government to play a much stronger role in financing
long-term care. ... there is a need for a comprehensive public
long-term care program based on the principles of social insurance
and shared risk.''
   That position was echoed by Gail Shearer, manager of policy
analysis for Consumers Union, which last year published in its
advertising-free magazine, ``Consumer Reports'' a survey of 53
private long-term care policies and found most ``very expensive,
severely limited in their coverage, or both.''
   ``We note that we prefer either a social insurance long-term
care program or government-administered optional long-term care
insurance,'' Ms. Shearer told the panel.
   While supporting regulation in the short term, she told Stark
that Consumers Union wants to work with him on legislation to
``address the larger long-term care problem: extending care to low
and moderate income Americans.''
   Ms. Bedford, of Phoenix, Ariz., went outside her prepared
testimony under questioning from Stark to explain in personal terms
why AARP's support for private insurance regulation is only a
stopgap position.
   ``I'm two years away from 80,'' she said. ``I cannot possibly
afford this (private coverage) in any way, shape form or fashion.
There is no way.''
</TEXT>
