<FIRST>r f AM-High-TechSmuggling     05-17 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-High-Tech Smuggling,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Network Accused of Smuggling Computers to East Bloc Nations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs agents smashed a ring that smuggled a
``phenomenal amount'' of high-tech equipment to Soviet bloc
countries, but a Belgian believed to be the ringleader remained at
large, officials said Wednesday.
   Four people were arrested Tuesday in Texas on conspiracy and
export law violations, and $1.8 million worth of sensitive computer
equipment was seized in Colorado as it was being readied for
export, said Customs Service spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   The name of the Belgian, who is believed to be living in Europe,
was not disclosed. An arrest warrant also was issued for Warren
Wetstein of Toronto.
   The ring arranged computer shipments from the United States
through European countries for delivery to Bulgaria, ``typically
the procuring agent on behalf of the whole Soviet bloc,'' said
Keith Prager, head of the investigative team code-named ``Miami
Exodus Group.''
   Customs' undercover investigation began 13 months ago, and has
received information on the export of tens of millions of dollars
worth of computer equipment by the ring in the past three or four
years, Sheehan said.
   ``This network of smugglers has been involved in a phenomenal
amount of high-technology smuggling,'' he said. ``This particular
network has been a main supplier, an enormous supplier of high-tech
equipment to Eastern bloc countries.''
   In addition to Romania and Hungary, the network made shipments
to or through Libya, Iran, Iraq, Yugoslavia, Austria and Belgium,
he said.
   The equipment seized from a Colorado Springs, Colo., warehouse
consisted of two Digital Equipment Corp. VAX 8820 computer systems
owned by Pioneer Standard Electronics of Cleveland, Prager said.
   The systems have numerous military and civilian applications, he
said.
   ``It can do virtually anything. It can run anything from a
traffic system in a city to radar to all kinds of military
applications,'' he said.
   The machines were to have been taken to Houston for shipment to
Europe, then to Turkey and finally Bulgaria, Prager said. The final
destination and intended use were not known.
   Customs began its undercover investigation 13 months ago, and
has received information on the export of tens of millions of
dollars worth of computer equipment in the past three or four
years, Sheehan said.
   The Soviet Union and other communist countries have sought
Western computer gear rather than develop their own, he said.
   ``They're willing to pay two, three, four, 10 times as much as
the technology is worth simply because it will save them 100 times
that amount in research and development,'' the spokesman said.
   Steve Smylie and his wife, Carole, who were arrested in Houston,
are accused of acting as brokers and consultants in the ring
through their firm, Technologies International Consultants, Prager
said. The company has no Houston telephone number.
   Jerry Blalock, also arrested in Houston, worked for Pioneer,
Prager said. Company chairman Pete Heller acknowledged Blalock was
an employee, but would not comment otherwise.
   Rick Parish, an employee of Global Computer Corp. of Dallas, was
arrested in Dallas, Prager said. Company president Ron Johnson was
out of the office Wednesday afternoon.
   Wetstein, a broker with Assets Conversion Specialists of
Toronto, was being sought in Canada, and extradition will be
pursued if he is captured, Sheehan said.
   The case will be presented to a federal grand jury in Miami next
week.
   Prager said the ring's members weren't working directly for the
Soviets.
   ``They're profiteers,'' he said. ``They're out to make money.''
</TEXT>
