<DOCNO> AP890517-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-US-ExportControls     05-17 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Export Controls,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>US to Lift Curb on Exports Worth $20 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security curbs will be lifted soon on
purchases by this country's allies of U.S. goods worth about $20
billion a year, a Commerce Department official said Wednesday.
   The object of the licensing is to prevent strategic items from
falling into the hands of the Soviets or terrorist groups.
   James M. LeMunyon, deputy assistant secretary for export
administration, said some of the allies are considering lifting
similar restrictions on trade among them. He reported that
representatives of several governments recently told him they
wanted to follow the U.S. lead, although he declined to name the
countries.
   LeMunyon was referring to goods traded among the 16 member
countries of the Coordinating Committee on Export Controls, a
publicity-shy body known as Cocom headquartered in Paris. It
includes Japan and all the countries in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization except Iceland.
   LeMunyon said last year the United States required 96,000
licenses for exports to these countries of goods worth about $100
billion. A new regulation will cut down the kinds of technology for
which licenses are required.
   ``About 20,000 licenses will be eliminated by this one
regulation,'' he said.
   LeMunyon would not give a precise date for when the new
regulation will go into effect, but said that in order to get it
out sooner, he was delaying consideration of one provision that
would eliminate additional licenses.
   LeMunyon spoke at a meeting called by the Aspen Institute, a
private policy study group, held in a committee room of the House
of Representatives.
   Among the speakers urging relaxation of export restrictions was
Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn, the new chairman of the subcommittee on
international economic policy of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee.
   ``We have a real opportunity for a change in export controls,''
he said.
   Gejdenson suggested that since the Soviets have withdrawn their
forces from Afghanistan, it's time to lift the restrictions former
President Carter imposed on exports to the Soviet Union when its
troops marched into that country nearly 10 years ago.
   Gejdenson predicted that President Bush will take a more
personal interest in export controls than did former President
Reagan, and said that would lessen what he called the ``lopsided
control'' by the Defense Department. Under Reagan, the Departments
of Defense and Commerce frequently clashed on what exports should
or should not be exported to the allies.
   One major change under the Bush administration has been the
departure of Richard Perle, an assistant secretary of Defense who
is a strong advocate of limiting shipments.
   Mitchell B. Wallerstein of the National Research Council, an
official government advisory body, said in 180 instances either
Reagan or a top aide had to make a decision on issuing a license.
That was no way to run a railroad, he commented.
   Harlan Cleveland, a former U.S. ambassador to NATO, presented a
report urging further paring of which items need a license for
shipment to Cocom members. The object is to focus attention on
items considered most important to deny to the Soviets.
   ``We need higher fences around fewer products,'' he said.
</TEXT>
