<FIRST>u f AM-Northrup-Cuts     05-17 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrup-Cuts,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northrop Plans to Cut Work Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. will cut up to 3,000 jobs or
about 7 percent of its workforce by year's end, the maker of the
B-2 stealth bomber disclosed Wednesday.
   The aerospace company is restructuring its corporate staff and
reducing support staff as its research and development projects
move into production, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Thomas
V. Jones told shareholders at the company's annual meeting.
   ``We expect to be able to decrease our overall employment
requirements by 6 to 7 percent, or about 2,500 to 3,000 positions
between now and the end of the year,'' he said.
   Jones did not say whether the jobs would be cut through layoffs
or attrition. A call to Northrop's office here after hours went
unanswered Wednesday.
   Jones also expressed satisfaction with Northrop's commitment to
build 132 B-2 bombers for the military.
   Revenue generated from the B-2 stealth bomber amounted to $657
million, or about half the company's overall sales for the first
quarter, according to a letter to shareholders.
   The disclosure marked the first time the firm has revealed how
much it has made from the bomber. The sales figure was almost
exactly what most analysts had been estimating since Northrop began
the B-2 program in 1981.
   In the first quarter, the company reported profits of $9.7
million on sales of $1.28 billion, with profits of $9.7 million,
down sharply from a year ago when profits totaled $139.6 million on
sales of $1.37 billion.
   Northrop failed to disclose stealth sales figures for the first
quarter of last year, saying that information remained classified
by the Air Force.
   But Wolfgang Demisch, an analyst at UBS Securities, said that
sales on the bomber appear to be declining.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
